<FIRST>u w AM-Obit-Collins     01-25 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Collins,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Red Cross President Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Francis Collins, a retired Army general
and a former president of the American Red Cross, has died of cancer
at Walter Reed Army Medical Center. He was 83.
   Collins, who was born in New York City and graduated from the
U.S. Military Academy at West Point in 1927, died Sunday. He lived
in suburban McLean, Va.
   During World War II, he served in the Pacivic and was transferred
to the Washington area in 1946. He joined the faculty at the Army
War College in 1950 and later was an executive assistant and special
assistant to the assistant secretary of defense for manpower and
personnel.
   From 1954 to 1957, Collins commanded two infantry divisions and
was commanding general of Army forces in Alaska. For the next four
years, he was assistant deputy and chief of staff for army personnel.
   He was appointed to the rank of four-star general in 1961 and was
named commander-in-chief of Army forces in the Pacific. He retired
in 1964 and became president of the Red Cross and retired in 1970.
</TEXT>
