<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Whitbread     01-25 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Whitbread,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse's First Novel Wins Richest British Book Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatric nurse who turned to writing as a
hobby won the Whitbread Book of the Year award for his first novel
``The Comforts of Madness.''
   Paul Sayer, 33, received the $34,000 prize on Tuesday from an
11-judge panel for his harrowing story about long-term psychiatric
hospital patients who cannot speak.
   The novelist works with elderly patients at a hospital in North
Yorkshire and his tale has been likened to Ken Kesey's ``One Flew
Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' about inmates of a U.S. psychiatric
institution.
   The total prize money of $46,750 makes the Whitbread Britain's
richest literary award.
   Sayer and four other writers had earlier won $2,550 each for
being selected as finalists for the Whitbread in five categories,
first novel, best novel, poetry, biography and children's novel.
</TEXT>
