<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0794 01-25 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0794,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Night Hank Williams Died' By Larry King Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to DELETE reference to talk show host. No PMs
planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rundown West Texas bar called the Sundowner
Recreational Club, dreams go down as easy as a cold bottle of Pearl
Beer and are just as intoxicating.
   They are the stuff of life for many of the characters in ``The
Night Hank Williams Died,'' Larry King's pungent yet poignant tale
of lost loves, missed opportunities, unfulfilled expectations and
fatal mistakes.
   It's not a perfect play, but until it collapses into violent
melodrama in Act 2, ``The Night Hank Williams Died'' has enough
low-key charm and homespun humor to soften the hardest of hearts.
   Maybe that's because King, author of ``The Best Little Whorehouse
in Texas,'' has a jaundiced affection for the folks he has put on
stage. It's love but love tempered by the knowledge that most of
these people will never amount to very much.
   Despite its title, the play has nothing to do with the death of
country-western star Hank Williams, although it is set in 1952 and
Williams' music wails from the bar's jukebox.
   Its main concern is Thurmond Stottle, a one-time high school
football hero in the tiny town of Stanley, Texas. Thurmond's
gridiron glories were nearly a decade ago. Now he's ``27 and working
on a beer gut'' while he pumps gas at the local service station.
   Between customers, Thurmond aspires to be another Hank Williams
or at least a songwriter who'll sell his compositions _ which have
titles like ``Little Bitty Bit of Love'' _ to Nashville stars like
Eddy Arnold.
   ``Nothin' wrong with dreams, providin' you act on 'em,'' counsels
Gus, the benevolent barkeep who extends Thurmond's beer tab as he
tries to rein in the boy's fantasies.
   Thurmond is galvanized by the arrival of Nellie Bess Powers, his
high school sweetheart. Her marriage to an up-and-coming
chiropractor has soured and she has come home ``to think about it.''
Her return rekindles Thurmond's adoration as well as his ambition to
make something of himself.
   King takes his time churning up the plot, but the wait has its
diversions. His dialogue is peppered with down-home conversation,
salty, sly and occasionally very funny give-and-take that is one of
the evening's main pleasures.
   Most of these lines are the property of actor Barton Heyman who
plays Gus, the bulky and blustery bartender. It's the play's most
fully realized role. By the time the curtain falls, Heyman has
revealed the frayed and forlorn humanity behind his coarse Texas
humor.
   Matt Mulhern has a harder time playing Thurmond who, when you get
down to it, isn't a very likable fellow. Mulhern also has a sweet,
pleasing singing voice, something at odds with his doltish,
one-track personality that smacks of loser from the very beginning.
At first, Betsy Aidem comes on as too much of a dust-caked Scarlett
O'Hara, but the caricature fades when she realizes the consequences
of her new fling with Thurmond.
   Strains show in the play when events turn melodramatic,
particularly with the appearance of Nellie Bess' fanatically devout
mother who still is ``keepin' in real close touch with Jesus.''
   Also painted in more black than white is the local sheriff, but
actor Steve Rankin does an expert job shading in the character with
a portrayal that's part good ol' boy and part smarmy Eddie Haskell
of television's ``Leave It to Beaver.''
   The direction by Christopher Ashley meanders through the play's
talkier moments and then seems frantic during its action-packed
finale. Still, Ashley allows time for the audience to savor the
people who inhabit designer Edward T. Gianfrancesco's wonderfully
ramshackled bar _ complete with deer head above the door.
   ``The Night Hank Williams Died'' is a bittersweet song to lives
and loves lost, spiced with enough laughs to soften the hurt.
Definitely worth a look.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
