<FIRST>r i PM-GreekCommissioner     01-25 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greek Commissioner,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Greek Radical Becomes EEC Commissioner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece's new commissioner in the European
Economic Community is Vasso Papandreou, a former Socialist radical
who once wanted Greece out of the organization.
   She and Christiane Shrivener, 63, of France are the first women
to serve on the 17-member EEC Commission, which is made up of senior
executives and now is charged with preparing for the removal of all
remaining trade barriers within the 12-nation community by the end
of 1992.
   The 44-year-old Ms. Papandreou, a close friend of but not related
to Greece's Socialist premier, Andreas Papandreou, was appointed by
Jacques Delors, the Commission's president. As with all other
commissioners she is expected to act independently of her country in
shaping EEC policy. She has been assigned the community's taxation
and customs union portfolio.
   ``The Commission recognizes that social affairs have been left
behind,'' she said in an interview. ``There is a lot of work to be
done and success depends both on Commission policy and my activity.''
   A farmers's daughter from southern Greece, Ms. Papandreou studied
economics at Athens Higher School of Commercial and Economic Studies
and then earned a Ph.D. at Reading University in England.
   She belonged to a generation of young leftists who bitterly
opposed the 1967-74 military dictatorship in Greece and who were
inspired by Andreas Papandreou's radical socialist policies,
including pledges to take Greece out of the EEC and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   But after leading his Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) to
power in 1981, Papandreou decided it would be too costly to take
Greece out of the EEC.
   As one of the trade bloc's poorer members, Greece receives more
than $1.5 billion a year in benefits. Premier Papandreou and the
government are now enthusiastically pro-European.
   Asked how she reconciles her radical and Marxist past with her
new job, the tall, dark-haired Ms. Papandreou said: ``It's not me
that's changed but PASOK.''
   As deputy industry minister while Greece held the EEC presidency
during the second half of 1988, Ms. Papandreou chaired meetings on
streamlining industrial legislation in the community.
   In the male-dominated world of Greek politics, Ms. Papandreou and
Culture Minister Melina Mercouri, the former actress who starred in
``Never on Sunday,'' have proved the only female high-fliers in the
Socialist government.
   In her first government post as director of the Organization for
Small and Medium-Size Businesses for two years from 1981, Ms.
Papandreou often was assailed by conservative businessmen, who
accused her of trying to impose Marxist policies.
   But her two-year stint as deputy commerce minister after winning
a Parliament seat in 1985 impressed even those critics.
   Ms. Papandreou's portfolio on the EEC Commission will be a
sensitive one.
   Socialist EEC member-governments, currently in the majority, will
be seeking to expand labor laws and increase social security
payments.
   But the conservative governments are likely to oppose more social
welfare legislation that might further complicate the 1992 goal of
moving services, goods and money freely around the community.
   Ms. Papandreou says that during her years in government she has
learned the art of compromise, crucial in building community policy.
   ``One always has to compromise,'' she said. ``But I'm taking a
positive view and this will be a challenge and a great experience.''
   ``She is very intelligent, a very good diplomat and knows how to
maneuver,'' said Christos Papoutsis, a Socialist member of the
European Parliament who has known Ms. Papandreou for 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-History     01-25 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-History,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Involvement In Gas Plant Recalls Past Horrors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges that West German companies
helped Libya build what may be a poison gas plant recall horrors
from two world wars and images of what a politician called the
``evil, self-deceiving German.''
   Germany shocked the world in World War I by wiping out 5,000
Allied soldiers April 22, 1915, with chlorine gas, introducing the
era of chemical warfare. The Nazis later use Zyklon B gas to kill
millions of prisoners, most of them Jews, at the Auschwitz death
camp.
   In addition to lessons of the past, the current debate dwells on
moral standards in a nation that has developed an arms export
industry in the last 15 years that ranks fifth in the world.
   ``German profits have grown much more quickly than ethical
standards,'' said the Rev. Friedhelm Hengsbach, a social sciences
professor at St. Georgen theological university in Frankfurt.
   ``The Germans are very smart in the sense of economic realities,
but they're not that shrewd when it comes to ethical responsibility
and political realities,'' the 51-year-old Jesuit priest said in an
interview.
   Norbert Gansel, a member of Parliament for the opposition Social
Democrats, put the problem succinctly: ``Now, our history has caught
up with us again. The evil, self-deceiving German is back.''
   In its current issue, the left-leaning magazine Der Spiegel said
the attitude of West German industry is ``export at all costs'' to
guarantee prosperity at home and ``tens of thousands of people pay
for the exporters' prosperity with their lives.''
   ``First comes the food, and then morals?'' it said, referring to
a line by the German author Bertolt Brecht. ``Not even that: many
deals are made completely without morals.''
   Government statistics say West German companies legally sell
about $16.6 billion worth of guns, submarines, munitions and other
arms overseas each year. That puts the country in fifth place behind
the United States, Soviet Union, France and Britain.
   Several state and local investigations are under way to determan
the amount of arms and arms-related goods sent abroad illegally.
   Included are inquiries into reports of West German involvement in
Iraqi poison gas production in addition to allegations that West
German companies helped build the plant at Rabta, south of Tripoli,
that Libya says makes medicines and the United States says is for
producing chemical weapons.
   Iraq acknowledged using poison gas during its war with Iran, in
which a cease-fire was reached in August, and has been accused of
using it on minority Kurds.
   Reports arise frequently of West German companies evading export
restrictions, as Gansel reminded a noisy parliamentary debate on the
Libyan matter last week.
   ``The string of arms-export scandals is long,'' he declared,
including sales of sensitive nuclear technology to Pakistan, India
and South Africa.
   Gansel, 48, said Zyklon B gas killed ``countless defenseless
Jews'' and reminded fellow legislators the image of the ``evil,
self-deceiving German'' had become a theme for both newspaper
cartoons and editorials.
   Many newspaper stories, magazine articles and TV programs about
the chemical plant scandal point out the German history of poison
gas dating to World War I.
   Der Spiegel called poison gas part of the ``horrifying tradition
of the German chemical industry'' and said, after describing the
1915 attack at Flanders:
   ``When the fog lifted, 5,000 Allied soldiers were dead and 10,000
seriously injured. The German Army had launched chemical warfare.''
   In Munich, the Suedeutsche Zeitung reminded readers in an
editorial Jan. 13: ``Not everyone may like the Germans; no one has
forgotten their past. Whoever has as much power as the Federal
Republic must also bear responsibility.''
   Joachim Perels, a political science teacher at Hanover
University, said in an interview: ``It is a question of current-day
morality and the Nazi past. You just can't lose sight of that second
point. It would be better if West Germany didn't supply Libya with
any materials that could be used for war.''
   Friedrich Justus Perels, the professor's father, was executed by
the Nazis along with thousands of others for alleged involvement in
the unsuccessful attempt to kill Adolf Hitler in 1944.
   Michel Friedman, spokesman for Frankfurt's Jewish community, said
of the Libyan scandal: ``German companies should be more conscious
of what's taking place in Libya,'' an enemy of Israel. ``It's part
of the special responsibility of the Germans, and a special
responsibility isn't just something to pray about on Sundays.''
   Andreas Hillgruber, a conservative historian on the University of
Cologne faculty, said attempts to link the scandal with the Nazi era
are an example ``of the past that won't go away.''
   ``You can view everything that the Germans do today against that
background,'' Hillgruber said.
   Hillgruber and other conservative historians have tried to
compare the extermination of 6 million Jews with other atrocities to
show the Nazi genocide does not stand alone in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Trains     01-25 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Trains,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll in London Crash Rises to 35</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from the collision of three trains
near a busy south London junction six weeks ago has risen to 35 with
the death of a 61-year-old man.
   Alan Philipson, a passenger aboard a London-bound commuter train
traveling from his hometown of Bournemouth in southern England, died
of his injuries at a London hospital on Tuesday, the hospital said.
   Rail officials said the train Philipson was aboard slammed into
the rear of another passenger train that had stopped for a
malfunctioning signal about 400 yards south of Clapham Junction on
Dec. 12.
   A freight train traveling in the opposite direction then plowed
into spillover wreckage and apparently hit some passengers who had
scrambled onto the tracks, officials said.
</TEXT>
