<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HomelessAds     01-25 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Homeless Ads,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Veterans Launch Ad Campaign About Their Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Vietnam Veterans has created a series of
advertisements narrated by Walter Cronkite and designed to focus
attention on the estimated 80,000 homeless veterans on America's
streets.
   The announcements for the Vietnam Veterans Workshop are shot in
grainy black and white film using professional actors who are all
Vietnam combat veterans, said Ken Smith, president of the workshop.
   The spots were unveiled Tuesday and will be broadcast on
television and radio and shown in movie theaters.
   The ads ask viewers to offer a pledge or volunteer to help the
workshop, which hopes to provide counseling or outreach centers for
homeless veterans.
   ``Two and a half million Americans went to Vietnam,'' it says.
``All any of them ever wanted was to come home. For 80,000, home has
become the streets, home has become a cardboard box, an abandoned
car.''
</TEXT>
