<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Cocaine     01-25 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Cocaine,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Discovered On Eastern Jet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 47 pounds of cocaine was discovered Tuesday on
an Eastern Airlines jet that had stopped at Miami International
Airport en route from Colombia to New York, officials said.
   No arrests were made by late Tuesday and U.S. Customs officials
are considering whether fines will be levied against the financially
troubled carrier, fined $1 million last fall after cocaine was
discovered on two flights within a two-week span, said Customs
spokesman Cliff Stallings.
   Before the cocaine was found, the plane had been cleared by
Customs inspectors following a routine search, said Stallings.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said a flight attendant found
a plastic packet containing cocaine inside one of the exit doors,
leading to an extensive search of the L-1011 aircraft that arrived
from Cali, Columbia, at about 4 p.m. EST.
   The cocaine was between the panels of the door and above the
lavatories of Flight 50, she said.
   But Stallings said several packets of cocaine were discovered by
a member of the cleaning crew in the rest rooms. He said vibrations
apparently dislodged the cocaine, which was concealed behind ceiling
panels above the rest rooms.
   Stallings said the manner the cocaine was hidden suggests it was
placed by someone with extensive access to and knowledge of the
plane.
   The search was completed about 9:30 p.m. EST, he said.
   All passengers were accommodated on other flights, Ms. Ceremsak
said.
   Since Sept. 13, Customs agents have seized five loads of cocaine
on Eastern flights from Colombia, including 68 pounds of cocaine
hidden in a box of ground coffee in November and 56 pounds of
cocaine found in a mail bag in October.
   Eastern says it spends more than $3 million a year fighting drug
trafficking.
   Avianca, Colombia's national airline, banned cargo from its
flights last June after paying $8 million in federal fines linked to
drug seizures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
