<DOCNO> AP890125-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Notebook Bjt   01-25 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Notebook, Bjt,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: A President Who Stops for Stop Lights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush stops at red lights. Sometimes.
   In a city used to seeing dignitary-bearing motorcades screeching
through traffic lights, sirens wailing, at all times of day and
night, the sight is more than a little unusual.
   There was Bush's 15-car motorcade, waiting for a traffic light to
change, right along with other backed-up traffic on a busy downtown
Washington street. No sirens. No flashing police-car lights.
   The president was on his way to a local Army base, Fort McNair,
for a Tuesday afternoon jog and didn't want to disrupt traffic any
more than was necessary.
   It's not as though anyone would write him a traffic ticket.
   He was simply following a pattern he'd established in his eight
years as vice president, said aide Bruce Zanca. ``Mr. Bush's
preference as vice president was to stop at lights, keep things as
normal as possible,'' Zanca said.
   Of course, as vice president, Bush didn't require 15 cars to go
jogging.
   He just stepped outside his door and ran. The vice president's
residence is on the sprawling grounds of the U.S. Naval Observatory,
and there's lots of space for jogging and other outdoor activities.
   There isn't as much room at the White House, forcing the new
president to seek out new jogging trails.
   Bush once suggested that he might return to the vice presidential
grounds from time to time to do his jogging, joking that he had
already sought _ and obtained _ permission from the man who would be
living there next, Vice President Dan Quayle.
   Bush, 64, jogs at a relatively sedate pace, about a mile every 10
minutes. He usually runs for 20 minutes, two or three times a week.
   The chief executive's decision to observe traffic signals
apparently only applies to personal trips, not when he's going
somewhere on official business.
   Then, it's the regular presidential motorcade _ which gets an
elaborate police escort and travels on streets where traffic has
already been cleared. Such motorcades completely ignore traffic
signals along the way.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who is trim at 6-foot-2 and 190 pounds, may jog to help
counter the waistline-expanding effect of another presidential
passion: deep-fried pork rinds.
   When Bush held his first Cabinet meeting on Monday, gone was the
crystal jar of jellybeans that predecessor Ronald Reagan used to
have sitting before him.
   By Tuesday, there was a large jar again _ only this one was
filled with pork rinds.
   It was a gift of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, one of a
group of House and Senate leaders that Bush had invited to meet with
him in the Cabinet Room to discuss the budget.
   Wright also presented fellow Texan Bush with a large bottle of
``Texas Pete'' hot pepper sauce.
   Bush is known to love to smother all manner of food with hot
sauce. During his campaign, a standard meal for Bush aboard Air
Force Two was tuna fish sandwiches drenched with hot sauce.
   ``We want to give a very warm welcome to the president,'' said
Wright.
   Bush picked up the bottle of hot sauce and closely examined the
label.
   ``How come Texas hot sauce is made in Winston-Salem, North
Carolina?''
   Wright retorted: ``Same way that some Texans were born in
Kennebunkport.''
   The room erupted in laughter, even though Wright's citation of
Bush's New England origins was off by a few states.
   While his family maintains a vacation home in the seaside resort
town of Kennebunkport, Maine, Bush was born in Milton, Mass., and
grew up in Connecticut.
   ``I'm just overwhelmed by both the pork rinds and the Texas hot
sauce,'' Bush said. ``You talk about cooperation, ecumenical spirit,
outreach. Just lovely.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ElectedOfficials     01-25 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elected Officials,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elected Officials Top Half-Million Mark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big government in Washington may get the most
publicity, but a new Census Bureau report shows that government is
big business in the rest of the country as well, with more than a
half-million Americans holding elective office.
   From school board president to the nation's president, Congress
to county commissioner, public officials total 504,404, the bureau
reported Tuesday in a study based on its 1987 census of governments.
   That's up from 490,807 elected officials counted a decade
earlier, the bureau said.
   ``It's quite a statement about the extent of democracy,
particularly the grassroots democracy, in the country,'' said Diana
Cull, a census statistician who compiled the figures.
   It means the United States now has more officeholders than bank
tellers. The Bureau of Labor Statistics estimated there were 467,000
tellers in 1987.
   But while the report found that holding public office is
widespread, it also shows officeholders don't necessarily represent
a cross-section of the nation.
   Only 20 percent were women, while 2 percent were blacks and 1
percent were Hispanic. Nationally, women make up just over half the
population while the nation is about 12 percent black and 7 percent
Hispanic.
   Most of the growth in elected officeholders since 1977 results
from the growth of special districts around the nation, Ms. Cull
said. These include independent water and sewer districts, housing
authorities, transit administrations and similar independent bodies
with elected boards.
   Special districts accounted for 80,509 elected officials on
29,532 governmental bodies in the 1987 study. That's up from 72,377
officeholders running 25,962 special districts in 1977.
   That increase of more than 8,000 officials was well ahead of any
other group, although special districts were only fourth in the
total number of officeholders. Municipalities, towns and school
districts continue to have larger totals of officials elected to
public office.
   The leading group is municipalities, with 137,688 officials
serving 19,200 communities in 1987. That's up from 134,017
officeholders in 18,862 municipalities in 1977.
   Townships came in second in both years, totaling 120,790
officials in 1987 and 118,966 a decade earlier year. During that
period the total number of township governments declined from 16,822
to 16,691.
   School districts were the nation's third largest job source for
elected officials, providing offices for 86,772 people in 1987. That
was down from 1977, however, when 87,062 people held elected school
board positions.
   That drop occurred in parallel with a decline in the number of
school districts in the nation, slipping from 15,174 to 14,721.
   The nation's 3,042 counties _ the same in both studies _ provided
somewhat fewer elected offices in 1987 than in 1977. The total fell
from 62,922 to 59,932.
   The states, meanwhile, increased their number of elected offices.
They harbored 18,171 elected officials in 1987, up from 15,294 in
1977.
   The 1977 report did not include figures for federal
officeholders. The new study put that number at 542, a total which
Ms. Cull said was unchanged.
   Elected federal officials include 435 members of the House, 100
senators, five congressional delegates from territories and the
District of Columbia and, of course, the president and vice
president.
   The 1987 report looked at the characteristics of local government
officials for the first time, Cull said.
   It found that women were most likely to be on school boards,
making up 26.5 percent of elected school officials. Women
constituted 23.1 percent of township officials and 20.8 percent of
county officers. They were 18.5 percent of the municipal officials
and only 11.5 percent of those serving on special districts.
   Blacks, on the other hand, were most often represented on
municipal governments, holding 3.3 percent of those posts.
   Blacks made up 2.6 percent of the county officials and 2.4
percent of school district officeholders. They were 0.6 percent of
the special district officials and 0.4 percent in town offices.
   School districts were the most common spot for Hispanics, at 1.8
percent. They held 1.3 percent of municipal offices and 1.2 percent
in special districts. Hispanics comprised 1 percent of county
officials and 0.2 percent of town officers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StateIncomes     01-25 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-State Incomes,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Income Growth Slowest in Energy States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Personal incomes are increasing the least in
the nation's energy states, while the coasts are recording the
biggest gains, the government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday the New England region had
the highest increase in personal incomes of any region, an 8.9
percent gain in the 12 months ending with September 1988. Following
close behind were the far West states of California, Nevada, Oregon
and Washington with a gain of 8.7 percent.
   At the other extreme were the Rocky Mountain states, a region
heavily dependent on oil and gas exploration, where incomes rose 6.1
percent on average from the third quarter of 1987 to the third
quarter of last year.
   ``We are still seeing the effects of weak energy prices,'' said
Commerce Department analyst Rudolph DePass. ``While some states have
been able to diversify their economies, others have not.''
   Nationally, non-farm incomes rose 7.8 percent in the period
ending in September, virtually identical to the 7.7 percent rise in
overall incomes posted for the 12-month period ending with the
second quarter.
   New England has led the country in income growth for much of the
recovery following the 1981-82 recession as its high-technology
industries have benefited from the big defense buildup of the Reagan
years.
   However, the rate of income growth has slowed in this area in the
past year, reflecting a slowdown in defense spending, DePass said.
   The most recent quarterly reports have shown that income growth
in America's Rust Belt has begun to stage a comeback, reflecting a
rebound in U.S. manufacturing as a weaker dollar has made American
goods competitive once again on overseas markets.
   The rebound in manufacturing has helped narrow but not eliminate
the bi-coastal lead in incomes, the department said.
   Critics of economic policies during the Reagan years say the
record peacetime recovery has essentially been a bi-coastal
expansion, with both coasts doing well while America's heartland
suffered.
   Over the 12 months ending with September 1988, incomes in coastal
states have grown by 8.3 percent, 6 percent above the national
average, while income in interior regions of the country grew 7
percent, 10 percent below the national average.
   Earlier in the expansion the difference was much wider with
coastal growth 10 percent higher than the national average while
interior regions were growing 17 percent below the national average.
   By state, Nevada had the biggest percentage increase for the 12
months ending in September, a 12.9 percent gain fueled by big
increases in construction payrolls. Hotel and motel construction
there reflected a boom in tourism.
   Nevada was followed by a 9.9 percent gain in non-farm incomes in
New Hampshire and a 9.6 percent rise in Hawaii. Also posting large
increases were Massachusetts and Florida, both at 9.3 percent.
   With inflation rising at an annual rate of 4.4 percent last year,
the figures showed that these states stayed well ahead of the
increase in prices.
   At the other end of the scale, income growth in some states just
barely kept up with the rise in prices.
   Wyoming ranked last with a 4.2 percent rise in non-farm incomes
over the period ending with the third quarter, followed by Alaska
with a 4.8 percent increase. Other states with low income growth
were Colorado, 5.2 percent; North Dakota, 5.3 percent; New Mexico,
5.3 percent, and West Virginia, 5.8 percent _ all states where
depressed energy prices have hurt incomes.
   The Commerce Department focuses on changes in non-farm income as
a better indication of a region's prosperity because of the often
erratic nature of agriculture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     01-25 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Super Bowl Scores Big Victory in Nielsen Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC and the Super Bowl, taking a cue from the
San Francisco 49ers, came out winners in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
television ratings last week.
   The Super Bowl coverage came in first by a wide margin. The
postgame show was second, also by a comfortable margin.
   NBC, in its 31st weekly victory for the season, took eight places
in the top 10 and easily won the week that ended Sunday.
   The 49ers defeated the Cincinnati Bengals in the Super Bowl as
NBC's coverage got a rating of 44.6. Each ratings point equals
904,000 homes with television, so more than 40 million homes tuned
in to the game. The postgame show had a rating of 32.5.
   The first part of the NBC miniseries ``Brotherhood of the Rose,''
which followed the game Sunday, placed ninth.
   A rerun of NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was third, with a rating of
25.3. NBC's ``Cheers'' was fourth.
   ABC's ``Roseanne,'' the biggest new hit of the season, was fifth,
and ABC's ``Who's the Boss?,'' was sixth as the network came in
second.
   Rounding out the top 10 were NBC's ``A Different World,''
seventh; ``Golden Girls,'' eighth; and ``L.A. Law,'' tenth.
   Third-place CBS had only one show in the top 20, its coverage of
the inaugural gala in Washington, which placed 20th. CBS' high-rated
Sunday show, ``Murder, She Wrote,'' was knocked to 46th place by the
Super Bowl coverage.
   NBC won the week with an average of 20.0. ABC had 12.1 and CBS
12.0.
   In the season to date, NBC has 15.6, ABC 13.0, and CBS 12.4.
   In the news category, ABC won with an 11.7 rating, closely
followed by CBS' 11.6 and NBC's 11.5.
</TEXT>
