<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Mel Torme says he expects to be
left out of the winner's circle this year at the Grammys, thanks to
his criticism of the award panel that voted him honors two years in
a row.
   Torme, who will be appearing at the Sands Hotel, Casino and
Country Club this weekend, blasted the National Academy of Recording
Arts &amp; Sciences for failing to nominate his partner on both
award-winning albums, pianist George Shearing.
   By 1982, Torme had received 11 Grammy nominations for Best Jazz
Vocalist. Because five of the nominated albums were collaborations
with Shearing, Torme asked the nominating committee why Shearing had
been ignored.
   ``They told me they had no category for him,'' Torme said. ``So
we make the album `An Evening With George Shearing and Mel Torme,'
'' Torme said. ``George asked me `why do you want to do this?' I
told him now, `We are a duo and that there is a duo category.'
Again, I got nominated and he didn't.''
   That album gave Torme his first Grammy in 1983, and in 1984 the
duo's follow-up ``Top Drawer'' earned him his second.
   This year, he is nominated for ``A Vintage Year,'' while Shearing
is again ignored. The Grammys will be awarded Feb. 22 on CBS-TV.
   ``I won't win this Grammy. I have come to understand how the
Grammys work, said the 64-year-old singer, who last year published
his autobiography, ``It Wasn't All Velvet.''
   ``I know that some of the people who vote don't like what I have
to say.''
</TEXT>
