<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When lawyers asked a second time for
permission to file a not-so-brief legal brief that would break the
state court's 50-page limit, the attorney on the opposite side
responded in terse verse.
   As Deputy state Attorney General Asher Rubin told the 1st
District Court of Appeal:
   ``Now plaintiffs come in once again. They claim that it's
outrageous, that lawyers of their stature should be cuffed to 50
pages.
   ``We urge the court to rule once more that 50 is the limit, for
otherwise their brief will be too long to even skim it.
   ``The issues can be analyzed in pages less than 50, if plaintiffs
could with thought and words endeavor to be thrifty.''
   Rubin said Tuesday, ``I couldn't resist.''
   He said he's taking a more serious approach to the merits of the
case, a lawsuit by low-income patients seeking to require that the
state reimburse counties for their care.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CEDAR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their far-ranging quest for new markets,
Michigan cherry growers have come up with some unusual products.
Take the cherry-pecan sausage, for example. Please.
   ``Cook it up slow, not too fast, and you'll think you died and
went to heaven,'' said Ray Pleva, the dish's inventor.
   ``It's a mild-tasting sausage with a light cherry flavor. It's
not sweet. It's not sour,'' said Pleva, who runs Pleva's Meats in
Leelanau County, the heart of the nation's cherry industry.
   Pleva's inventiveness is exactly the sort of thing the newly
formed Cherry Marketing Institute in Lansing is encouraging. The
sausages are among a dozen cherry products the institute will
introduce in March at an international food exposition in Japan.
   Institute Manager Dick Johnston sees Japan as a market ripe for
the picking _ assuming the Japanese can be enticed by cherry-filled
pastries, cherry sausages or cherry mustard.
   The institute has the same problem at home. Americans consume 225
million pounds of cherries a year _ nearly a pound a person _ but
Johnston said the market has remained stagnant.
   Cherry entrepreneurs, therefore, are spending more time in the
kitchen inventing new ways to use an old fruit.
   Pleva concocted his cherry-pecan sausages last fall, when his
daughter, Cindy, was the National Cherry Queen. He admits he has met
some skeptics.
   ``You should see some of the looks,'' said Pleva. ``But they
change when they taste it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STEPHENVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was a jailbreak at the new $2.5
million Erath County Jail, but Sheriff David Coffee and his deputies
weren't upset.
   They were just relieved to get out.
   It seems that Coffee and some of his deputies accidentally got
locked inside a hallway between cells at the jail Monday and had to
stage a breakout to get free.
   The unplanned lock-in occurred as the sheriff was showing off the
as yet unopened jail's security system. When the door to the control
room suddenly slammed shut, all the doors locked automatically,
leaving the keys inside the control room and the lawmen trapped
outside.
   It took about an hour, but the posse finally devised a plan of
escape.
   They found two poles left from the construction work and fitted
them together, inserted them through a slot in the control room door
and retrieved the keys.
</TEXT>
