<FIRST>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons     01-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Weapons,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Prepare Legislative Response to Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee and a conservative Republican member are
drafting companion bills aimed at punishing countries that use
chemical weapons and the private Western companies that help produce
them.
   The bills were announced at a hearing Tuesday in which senators
cited reports that the West German government did nothing to prevent
German industries from helping Middle Eastern nations obtain
chemical warfare capability.
   Also at the hearing, the head of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency said the United States is now satisfied West
Germany is responsibly addressing the situation and will act soon to
tighten export controls.
   The arms control chief, William F. Burns, also told senators that
the Soviet Union is stockpiling biological weapons in violation of a
1972 agreement banning them worldwide.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said he is readying a bill to require U.S.
diplomatic and economic sanctions against any nation using chemical
or biological weapons. He said the legislation will ask other
nations to do likewise.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said he will sponsor companion
legislation to impose sanctions against companies of any nationality
supplying chemical warfare equipment and technology to Third World
nations.
   ``I have every reason to believe that, in the end, the Congress
and the administration will see the wisdom of both approaches,''
Helms said.
   Burns told the hearing that about 20 nations have the capacity to
produce chemical weapons. He said about five or six are known to
have used or stockpiled them.
   Responding to questions, Burns listed Iran, Iraq, Libya, Syria
and North Korea as poison gas stockpilers. He said Iran, Iraq and
Libya are reported to have used chemical weapons.
   Burns also said the United States believes the Soviet Union is
maintaining stocks of biological weapons in violation of the 1972
international agreement outlawing the manufacture and possession of
germ warfare agents.
   ``We believe the Soviet Union does have a stock of biological
weapons and obviously they must have some capacity to produce
them,'' Burns said.
   Helms asked how, in that case, the Soviets can be trusted to
comply with a new international agreement, soon to be negotiated,
banning the manufacture, stockpiling and use of poison gas and other
chemical weapons.
   Burns replied that the 1972 agreement had no provisions for
monitoring and verifying compliance while any new pact will have
verification provisions.
   He acknowledged, however, that verification will be difficult and
that perfect monitoring probably cannot be achieved.
   Helms complained that West German companies were helping Third
World countries, especially in the Middle East, obtain chemical
weapons capability.
   He also said a West German company is helping Libya obtain the
ability to refuel warplanes in flight, extending their range and
giving them the ability to strike Israel.
   ``The problem is extremely grim,'' Helms said. ``With the
critical assistance of Western industrial firms, the four most
radical regimes in the world are acquiring weapons of mass
destruction.''
   Burns, who said he had discussed the situation with officials of
the West German Embassy, said the attitude of the Bonn government
has changed significantly.
   ``I think the West German government is on the right track and I
applaud the activities they are undertaking now,'' Burns said.
</TEXT>
