<HEAD>Man Searchs For Lost `Teddy Bear'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMARAC, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Craig Matalon is searching for his lost
``teddy bear.''
   Matalon accidentally left Kinky's cage open on Saturday night.
The 14-year-old female kinkajou climbed out, and was last seen early
Sunday by a neighbor.
   ``She can't live alone,'' he said. ``She'd walk up to somebody,
but I don't think anybody would know what to do with her.''
   Kinky, about the size of a large house cat, has short,
golden-colored hair, big brown eyes, a long tail and sharp claws.
   ``She looks like a teddy bear,'' he said. ``You can't help but to
fall in love with this animal.
   `I feel like I lost a child,'' said Matalon, who has owned Kinky
since she was 2 weeks old.
   The kinkajou, a raccoon-like animal native to South America, is
about 9 inches long and weighs no more than 10 pounds, said Lani
Wigand, director of education at the Broward County Humane Society.
