<DOCNO> AP890125-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Honoraria     01-25 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honoraria,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaking Bonuses Become Touchy Subject Amid Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some members of Congress, as well as the
lobbying groups that pay them, are self-conscious about the practice
of picking up large fees for speeches or panel discussions before
one interest group or another.
   Next week, for instance, the National Association of
Wholesaler-Distributors is hosting a two-day conference in
Washington where eight senators and four House members are scheduled
to speak.
   The association issued a notice, giving directions to the hotel
ballroom, times and topics, making sure reporters knew they were
welcome.
   It gave phone numbers in case anyone has any questions.
   Ask how much the senators and House members are being paid for
their speeches, and the conversation dies.
   ``I'm not prepared to get into an interview of that type,'' said
Dirk Van Dongen, president of the association.
   That kind of reaction is understandable, said Howard Marlowe,
president of the American League of Lobbyists, who would like to see
Congress abolish the practice of paying politicians to talk.
   The fees, known as honoraria, are an added source of personal
income for members of Congress, who can keep from $26,850 to $35,800
annually, depending on whether they are House or Senate members.
   ``It's perfectly legal, but the perception is that it's bad, so
therefore you have people who don't want to talk about it,'' Marlowe
said.
   ``We all in this town are competing for some forms of access and
power,'' he said. ``It is easier to buy it than to talk your way
into it _ that's buying access and not buying influence.''
   A proposal on Capitol Hill to ban the practice is informally
linked to boosting congressional salaries 50 percent from $89,500 to
$135,000.
   Members of Congress, who late in the spring are required to
disclose how much they make in speaking fees along with other
financial information, are not eager to give that out before they
have to.
   ``We are required by law to disclose that information on an
annual basis, but I don't think that it's a good idea to give it out
on a piecemeal basis,'' said David Dreyer, spokesman for Rep. Tony
Coelho, D-Calif., who made $78,500 in speaking fees in 1987, the
last year for which records are available.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., was reluctant to disclose how much
he's received in honoraria since Congress recessed before the
election last fall. But when pressed, his office acknowledged he got
$21,000 for making five speeches in Palm Springs, Calif., earlier
this month while he was at a golf tournament.
   Lawmakers in both houses can retain up to $2,000 per article or
event, with any fee exceeding that figure _ or any amount over the
annual cap _ going to charity.
   Rostenkowski, chairman of the Ways and Means Committee which
writes the nation's tax laws, made $245,000 in speaking fees last
year and gave enough of it to charity to drop just below the House
limit, which at the time was less than $26,000.
   Rostenkowski wasn't alone in Palm Springs in mid-January.
   The Tobacco Institute hosted 27 members of Congress at a posh
resort near there, but institute spokesman Walker Merryman wouldn't
say how much they were paid or how much of their expenses were
picked up. He did say that everyone was treated equally.
   Among those attending the conference was Sen. Thomas A. Daschle,
D-S.D., whose office said he earned a $2,000 honorarium, along with
round-trip air fare for him and his wife and three nights' lodging.
The tab: $1,392.
   Marlowe said the league of lobbyists has not taken a position on
the issue of abolishing honoraria, but he favors getting rid of the
practice because of the bad appearance, which he compared to a skin
blemish.
   If it is banned, he said, some of Washington's finest minds will
start looking for loopholes.
   ``I honestly am stuck on what will rise up to take its place, but
I have every confidence in the ingenuity of the players involved
that something will rise up,'' he said. ``Just like the zits _
another one can pop up in its place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Bundy'sLegacy Bjt   01-25 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy's Legacy, Bjt,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Grief, Unsolved Crimes Part Of Bundy Legacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After enduring more than a decade of Ted Bundy's
smug silence and denials, relatives of his acknowledged victims
found a chilling relief in his 11th-hour admission of a life of rape
and murder.
   ``The only thing I can say is thank God, it's finally over,''
said Vivian Rancourt of LaConner, whose 18-year-old daughter, Susan,
disappeared April 17, 1974. In the days before his execution
Tuesday, Bundy confessed to her slaying.
   But an investigator who heard some of Bundy's confessions said
there were crimes the serial killer wouldn't talk about and secrets
he took with him to Florida's electric chair.
   The 42-year-old Bundy, who was convicted of murdering three
people in Florida, admitted killing 23 other women after a decade of
denial, but he left a legacy of frustration for those who suspect he
killed many more.
   No one knows the enormity of Bundy's crimes. FBI officials said
years ago he might be implicated in 36 slayings throughout the West.
But Bundy's confessions included deaths to which he had not
previously been linked, such as two in Idaho, and he did not give
specifics on at least 10 others in which he was a suspect.
   ``I don't think we have even scratched the surface with Bundy,''
Sheriff Pete Hayward of Salt Lake County, Utah, said after the
execution. ``Somewhere there is someone Bundy has told the whole
story to.''
   Bundy confessed to eight Utah killings, but because he identified
only two victims there, authorities said many cases may never be
solved.
   Investigators said Bundy would not answer when asked about his
connection to two Utah deaths in which he is a suspect, including
the October 1974 strangulation and beating death of Laura Anne Aime,
17, of Salem, Utah.
   But there was no doubt Tuesday in the mind of her mother that
Bundy killed her child.
   ``He needed to die very badly,'' Shirlene Aime said, but she
conceded the last minutes of waiting for his execution were
``horrible.''
   ``It made me feel guilty,'' she said. ``Despite all the things he
did to my daughter and all the other girls, I started to think, `How
low am I, waiting for a man to die?' ''
   Her long-sought relief at Bundy's death was slow to come, she
said.
   ``I still have this empty feeling. I'm sick to my stomach. It's
an uptight, horrible feeling. But it is a relief to know he's gone,
and he won't do it again.''
   Bundy was executed for the 1978 rape and murder of 12-year-old
Kimberly Leach of Lake City, Fla. He also was convicted of killing
two women in 1978 at a Florida State University sorority house. His
gush of confessions in the four days before his electrocution did
not include those deaths.
   Robert Keppel, an investigator for the Washington state attorney
general, said the law student dropout from Tacoma was unwilling in
interviews to talk about some cases that gave him ``painful
memories,'' and balked at confessing to deaths before 1973.
   ``That seemed to be where he drew the line,'' said Keppel, who
spent about two hours during the weekend extracting confessions from
a shaken, tearful Bundy.
   Keppel said Bundy denied kidnapping and killing 8-year-old Ann
Marie Burr in 1961, when Bundy would have been just 14. But the way
Bundy talked about that crime, he left doubt about whether he might
have been responsible, Keppel said.
   Ann Marie disappeared from her parents' Tacoma home, near where
Bundy's family lived, during an early morning rainstorm. No clue to
her fate has ever been found, though there have been years of
speculation _ including that of Ann Marie's parents _ that Bundy was
to blame.
   ``He denied that he did it,'' Keppel said. ``But he kind of
offered some qualifiers. He told me he was too young at the time. He
told me, `Serial killers start a little older than that.' And he
said, `The neighborhoods were so far apart.' And he said his
newspaper route wasn't close to the Burr residence.''
   Beverly Burr said Tuesday she feels strongly that Bundy was
responsible for her daughter's disappearance, but added: ``If it was
Bundy, then there's no way we're going to find out. We can't do
much. We're helpless.''
   Keppel said his opportunity to question Bundy was limited to
Friday and Sunday, when the killer gave considerable detail about
the string of eight ``Ted'' murders in 1974 in the Seattle area. But
time ran out before he could get details on other killings.
   ``He told me that he would never talk about some cases because
they were too close and too painful to talk about,'' he said.
</TEXT>
