<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher, Stocks Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher Wednesday against the
Japanese yen, and share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
marginally, hitting another record high.
   The dollar closed at 127.65 yen, up 0.70 yen from Tuesdsay's
close of 126.95 yen. The currency opened higher at 127.86 yen, and
moved in a range of 127.37-127.88 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which rose to a
record high of 31,557.68 Tuesday, added 10.11 points, or 0.03
percent, to close at 31,567.79, a new high.
   The Nikkei posted early gains following similar climbs on
overseas markets overnight. It then due to investor concern over the
yen's weakness relative to the dollar and the index's rapid rise,
but remained slightly above Tuesday's close, traders said.
   In foreign exchange dealings, the dollar opened higher in the
wake of Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony to
Congress that indicated he may tighten monetary policy to fight
inflation.
   In a testimony Tuesday before the U.S. House of Representatives
Banking Committee, Greenspan said the risks of inflation were great
enough that the Federal Reserve ``might well be advised to err more
on the side of restrictiveness than of stimulus.''
   Early trading was dominated by dollar-buying but speculative
investors started selling the currency to adjust their positions,
said Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank.
   ``We already knew that the United States would tighten its
monetary policy by keeping the interest rates high, but Greenspan's
comment still prompted buying because investors have been looking
for market-affecting incentives,'' he said.
