<NOTE>Petition Asks Broadening of Ford Pickup Fires Probe</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials have been asked by a
private advocacy group to order the recall of 1.9 million Ford Motor
Co. pickup trucks because they allegedly are prone to catch fire.
   The petition, filed Tuesday by the Center for Auto Safety, asked
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to investigate
reports of fuel-system fires in Ford's F-series pickup trucks with
dual gas tanks made from 1983 through 1988.
   The center based its petition on eight reports of fires involving
F-series pickups, including a 1987 warehouse fire in Minot, S.D.,
allegedly started by a 1986 F-250 pickup whose fuel system caught
fire while unloading chemicals. Two people received serious burns,
according to reports received by the center.
   The advocacy group, often at odds with the auto industry and its
regulators, criticized as ``woefully inadequate'' a NHTSA
investigation of F-series pickups begun in December.
