<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany-Rights     01-25 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-Rights,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Criticizes East German Human Rights Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Persistent human rights abuses by East Germany
include the punishment of people who seek to emigrate, harsh
treatment of prisoners and the conducting of secret trials, Amnesty
International said today.
   While the Communist government has loosened up some travel
restrictions, some people caught trying to flee have been charged
with espionage, the London-based human rights organization said.
   Amnesty said ``a clear pattern of human rights abuse'' exists in
the country of 16.6 million people but said official secrecy and the
government's refusal to respond in detail to various allegations
make it difficult to obtain a complete picture.
   Western leaders last week sharply criticized East Germany's
record on the issue during a human rights conference in Vienna.
   East German leader Erich Honecker has been resisting calls for
reforms along the lines of those initiated in the Soviet Union by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Amnesty said East Germany's ``secret trials, secret directives to
lawyers and vaguely defined laws make it possible for the
authorities to penalize almost any activity of which they
disapprove.''
   Young East Germans, with the support of part of the Lutheran
Church, have been clamoring for greater freedom, including the
ability to travel outside the Soviet bloc.
   Amnesty quoted some East Germans as saying their applications to
emigrate were turned down because the stated reasons were ``not
sufficient.''
   ``Others have reported that the officials said that the
application was `illegal' without indicating which laws had been
broken,'' the organization said in a report.
   The East Germans have eased travel restrictions after years of
pressure from Western leaders. Western estimates say 1.5 million
people have applied to emigrate from East Germany. Many leave
illegally _ more than 9,700 in 1988.
   Amnesty said there have been cases of people being charged with
espionage if they had access to ``sensitive information'' and later
tried to flee.
   ``In such cases, no information has in fact been passed on
because the person was apprehended before this was possible,'' said
report says.
   It notes that stating one's reasons for wishing to leave East
Germany can be considered the crime of ``public vilification.''
   ``The `vilification' is considered public if, for example, a copy
of the application for an exit visa is sent to a higher authority or
written on a postcard,'' Amnesty said.
   Many of those persecuted by the government are would-be emigrants
who later turn to foreign organizations in hopes of seeking
attention for their case, the report says.
   It says potential witnesses and defense lawyers can be charged
with crimes if they challenge the prosecutor's version of facts in a
case.
   Amnesty said there were also reports of mistreatment in jail.
   ``One former prisoner complained that the only person she could
talk to immediately after arrest was her interrogator and that she
almost began to look forward to the daily interrogation sessions as
a break from the monotony of isolation in the cell,'' the report
says.
   ``A number of former prisoners have reported that inmates in
punishment cells were chained to beds for days on end as punishment,
being set free only to go to the toilet or for meals,'' Amnesty
reported.
   Refusal to work was the most common reason for confinement in a
punishment cell, a drafty, 6{-foot-by-6{-foot area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SRP-TestDamage     01-25 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SRP-Test Damage,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Criticizes Savannah River Operators Following New Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials say an accident that
occurred during testing at the Savannah River Plant is another sign
that problems at the nuclear facility are out of control.
   ``The issue is not physical damage. The issue is a lack of
formality, a lack of discipline,'' Richard Starostecki, deputy
assistant energy secretary, said Tuesday. ``This doesn't give you
confidence in their ability to handle anomalies.''
   The Engergy Department and Du Pont Co., the plant's operator, are
investigating Sunday's accident. Federal officials said there was no
leakage of radiation or other hazardous material.
   Du Pont officials said damage has tentatively been estimated at
$20,000 and will take only a few days to repair.
   The Savannah River Plant reactors, which produce plutonium and
tritium for the nation's nuclear weapons arsenal, have been shut
down since April for safety and maintenance reasons.
   The impact of the accident on the department's plans to restart
the reactor before the end of this summer is uncertain.
   However, DOE safety officials say the incident, which comes at a
time when safety of the nation's nuclear weapons complex is under
intense congressional scrutiny, casts new doubts on the ability of
plant operators to run SRP's three nuclear reactors.
   Starostecki, the DOE's top safety official, said the incident was
further evidence that suggested ``a lack of control over what's
going on in the reactors.''
   He said the mishap at the K reactor closely parallels earlier
problems at the P reactor in August, when operators failed to shut
down the reactor when they were confronted with erratic power levels.
   The latest problem began Thursday with a test of a portion of the
reactor system that uses water from the nearby Savannah River to
help keep the radioactive core cool during normal operations.
   During the test, operators opened a valve to divert water from
one segment of the cooling system to the portion being tested,
according to Gerald Merz, Du Pont's technology superintendent. Merz
said problems began when the operators forgot to close the valve
after the test.
   Unaware that the valve was still open, other operators on Sunday
began a test of another portion of the cooling system. When water
pressure in the portion of the cooling system they were testing
failed to increase as expected, they incorrectly assumed the problem
was inadequate pumping capacity.
   Merz said the operators then switched on a second pump, which
created enough force to break the valve. He said that caused water
to surge through the entire system at up to six times the normal
pressure level.
   ``Rather than take a prudent course of action when they weren't
getting the numbers they expected during a test, which would have
been to stop the test, somebody elected to turn on another pump,''
Starostecki said.
   Du Pont officials ordered a halt to further maintenance and
testing at the K reactor. The Energy Department says that work must
be conducted before a restart can be attempted.
   Merz said the company's initial investigation suggests that
operators failed to explicitly instruct technicians to close the
valve in question after the test Thursday.
   But Merz, Starostecki and Roger Rollins, DOE's acting director
for reactor assessment at SRP, said Tuesday that the faulty decision
by operators during the Sunday test was a bigger mistake.
   ``They should have stopped,'' Merz said. ``They were seeing
something different than what was expected as far as the pressure
levels, and the correct action would have been to halt the test and
call in the engineers and figure out what was happening.''
   He said Du Pont is considering taking disciplinary action against
the operators involved.
   Rollins said the DOE is investigating the matter, including a
delay in reporting the problem to top plant officials. He said word
of the mishap Sunday night did not reach the department's managers
at Savannah River until Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
