<FIRST>r a PM-Gotti     01-25 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gotti,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Crime Boss, Charged With Ordering Hit, Freed on Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reputed mob boss John Gotti, who according to his
attorney ``has never run away from a problem,'' walked out of a
courtroom free on bail after being accused of ordering the shooting
of a construction union official.
   ``Did I ever worry yet?'' a smiling Gotti asked reporters waiting
for him as he arrived back at his home 20 hours after being arrested
by dozens of law officers on a street in Little Italy.
   ``I have nothing to worry about.''
   At a bail hearing Tuesday, the prosecution asked that Gotti be
held without bail, arguing that the reputed head of the Gambino
crime family had access to massive sums of mob money and would flee
if freed.
   Gotti's income is ``literally that of the family,'' Assistant
District Attorney Michael Cherkasky told acting Judge George Roberts.
   ``His financial resources are enormous. He's gambled on numerous
occasions and lost enormous sums of money. We're counting in the
hundreds of thousands of dollars,'' Cherkasky said.
   But Gotti's lawyer, Bruce Cutler, said Gotti has strong family
ties here and had never failed to appear for a court date.
   ``He's not going no place. He has never run away from a
problem,'' Cutler said.
   Roberts set Gotti's bail at $100,000, and about an hour later the
48-year-old Gotti _ dressed in the same tailored brown suit and
yellow turtleneck he wore when he was arrested Monday _ was back on
the streets.
   At a news conference Tuesday, District Attorney Robert Morgenthau
released a grand jury indictment that accused Gotti and two
associates of conspiring to order the shooting of John F. O'Connor,
who allegedly had a restaurant vandalized for using non-union
carpenters.
   ``It was the specific goal and intention of the conspiracy to
punish John F. O'Connor, and thereby reaffirm the authority of the
Gambino crime family over all others who might challenge it,''
according to the indictment, which charges Gotti and the other two
men with conspiracy and first-degree assault.
   O'Connor, vice president and business manager of Local 608 of the
United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners, was shot four times in
the May 1986 attack, but survived.
   Law enforcement officials said O'Connor apparently did not know
the restaurant, Bankers and Brokers in lower Manhattan, was managed
by an alleged associate of the Gambino organization, the nation's
most powerful crime family.
   Gotti codefendant Anthony (Tony Lee) Guerrieri, 60, a reputed
soldier in Gotti's organization, was freed on $50,000 bail. Both men
pleaded innocent.
   The judge ordered the two to return to court Monday.
   The third man indicted, Angelo Ruggiero, identified as a captain
in the Gambino family, was placed in custody at a hospital where he
is undergoing cancer treatment, and will be arraigned later,
Morgenthau said.
   Morgenthau said investigators learned through electronic
surveillance that a contract to shoot O'Connor had been given by the
Gambino group to the leader of the Westies, a gang that operated on
Manhattan's West Side.
   Several members of the Westies were named as co-conspirators in
the indictment, but were not charged.
   A missing member of the gang, Kevin Kelly, was indicted in
absentia in September 1986 on attempted murder charges for the
O'Connor shooting. Law-enforcement officials believe Kelly has been
killed.
</TEXT>
