<FIRST>r i PM-China-Africans     01-25 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Africans,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Of Mali Arrives, Receives Protest Letter From Africans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African students who want to leave China because
they say the Chinese are racist asked the president of the
Organization of African Unity today for money to pursue their
studies elsewhere.
   Mali President Moussa Traore, who heads the OAU, arrived in
Beijing on Tuesday for his third visit since 1973 and was met at the
airport by a delegation of Malian students from universities around
China.
   Traore was given a letter asking him to help African students
leave China, the African students said. The OAU has recently
criticized China for its treatment of African students.
   ``African students feel menaced by a climate of insecurity which
is implicitly encouraged by Chinese authorities,'' said a copy of
the letter obtained by The Associated Press.
   ``We would like to leave China not only with the aim of returning
to our respective countries but with an aim of continuing our
studies in countries where living conditions will be favorable,''
the letter says.
   It asks the OAU to provide the students with scholarships ``to
enable us continue our studies.''
   Most of the 1,500 African students in China are on Chinese
government scholarships. It was not clear how many of them the
letter represented.
   Telephone calls to the Mali Embassy for comment were not answered.
   A brawl on Dec. 24 at a university in Nanking triggered
anti-African protests by Chinese in several cities and attacks on
African students' dormitories in that city.
   Today, about 500 Africans continued a class boycott that began
Jan. 4 at the Beijing Languages Institute and about half the 140
African students in Nanking remained on strike there.
   Chinese authorities on Tuesday released Alex Dosoo of Ghana, the
last of three African students arrested in Nanking for allegedly
taking part in the Christmas Eve brawl. Dosoo had been under house
arrest at a guest house in Nanking for 11 days and in jail the
previous two weeks.
   In a telephone interview from Nanking, Dosoo said Chinese
authorities told him he could continue his studies in China. He said
he would rather return home.
   Ghana protested Dosoo's arrest and threatened to withdraw its 26
students from China. Most of the other African embassies have been
silent on the issue.
   Dosoo's release appeared aimed at lessening any problems China
might have with Traore during his visit. China has long courted
Africa in its attempt to be a leader of the Third World.
   An official Xinhua News Agency report on Traore's visit late
tonight stressed China's strong ties to Africa.
   ``Strengthening cooperation with Third World nations, including
those of Africa, is the cornerstone of China's foreign policy of
independence and peace,'' Xinhua said.
</TEXT>
