<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     01-25 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Arrested In Wenceslas Square Face Charges Of Hooliganism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Czech activists who were arrested
last week while trying to place flowers on Prague's Wenceslas Square
face charges of disturbing the public and hooliganism, an informed
source said today.
   Prominent playwright Vaclav Havel and 15 others were detained
after the eight tried to lay flowers in memory of Jan Palach, a
student who burned himself alive 20 years ago to protest the death
of the ``Prague Spring'' reforms after the Soviet-led invasion of
1968.
   Five of that group were released last weekend but may also be
tried, dissidents in Prague said this week.
   Havel, like the other eight still in prison, will likely be
prosecuted separately, said the source, who was reached by telephone
from Vienna.
   The source, who asked not to be identified, said the lawyers of
the eight accused dissidents were summoned to the prison Tuesday and
informed of the results of a police probe.
   Under Czechoslovak law, both the accused and their lawyers must
be informed of the outcome of such an investigation before the
charges are presented to the public prosecutor.
   According to the source, if convicted they face a maximum penalty
of two years in prison.
   The eight were identified as Dana Nemcova and Sasha Vondra,
spokesmen for the Charter 77 human rights group, Stanislav Penc,
Jana Petrova, Otakar Veverka of Independent Peace Association, Jana
Sternova, also a senior Charter 77 member, as well as Petr Placak
and David Nemec of the Czech Children group.
   Two other people arrested on Jan. 16, Jitka Vavsikova and Jiri
Fiala, have not been heard of since, and it was not clear if they
are still under arrest, said sources in Prague and Vienna.
   In addition to hooliganism, Havel also faces additional charges
for having called for an unauthorized demonstration in interviews
with foreign media Jan. 9-15, the source in Vienna said.
</TEXT>
