<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Brewery     01-25 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Brewery,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>2,000 Brewery Workers Face Layoffs In Merger Of Carling-Molson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven breweries employing at least 2,000 Canadians
will be shut down under the proposed merger of Carling O'Keefe and
Molson's, a newspaper reported today.
   The Molson brewery in Toronto and Carling's Montreal plant are
chief among the victims, the Toronto Star quoted industry sources as
saying.
   The sources told the newspaper the new brewing company also will
close Carling operations in St. John's, Newfoundland; Saskatoon,
Saskatchewan; and Vancouver, British Columbia. Molson facilities
will close in Lethbridge, Alberta, and Winnipeg, Manitoba, the
newspaper said.
   Molson Breweries is the name of the new company formed by last
week's merger of the second- and third-largest breweries in Canada.
   The merger still needs approval from the federal Bureau of
Competition Policy. Approval is expected.
   The companies said they would close one plant in every province
where both have operations to become more efficient in a bid at
cracking the giant U.S. beer market.
