<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     01-25 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Expedites Parole Review for Adams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Pardons and Paroles will
give quicker consideration of parole for a man whose 1976 conviction
for killing a Dallas police officer was questioned in the movie
``The Thin Blue Line.''
   ``I would speculate it would be within the next 30 days,'' said
Glenn T. Heckmann, the board's executive director.
   The board on Tuesday granted Randall Dale Adams an expedited
parole review, meaning his December review would be moved up.
   State records show Adams, 40, who is serving a life sentence, has
been denied parole eight times, most recently on Jan. 10.
   Adams' parole request was expedited based on information provided
by State District Judge Larry Baraka, said Karin Armstrong, an
information officer with the board.
   Baraka last month ruled that Adams did not receive a fair trial
in 1977 and recommended he be granted a new one or set free.
   The key witness against Adams changed his story last month,
testifying that Adams didn't commit the murder and wasn't even in
the car police officer Robert Wood stopped just before he was gunned
down.
   However, the witness, David Ray Harris, stopped short of saying
he pulled the trigger himself in Wood's slaying.
   Harris is on Death Row for another killing, and Dallas district
attorney John Vance has discounted his testimony.
   Adams, always maintaining his innocence, contends prosecutors
wanted to convict him rather than Harris, who was only 16 at the
time. If convicted as a juvenile, Harris would have been released at
age 18.
   ``The Thin Blue Line,'' a documentary by Errol Morris, questioned
Adams' guilt.
   Adams has served more than 12 years in state prison. In 1980, his
death sentence was commuted to life.
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals also is considering Baraka's
recommendation that Adams be given a new trial or set free.
Attorneys said it could take as long as two years to act on it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
