<DOCNO> AP890125-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Refugees     01-25 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Refugees,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phnom Penh, U.N. Sign Refugee Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Hanoi government in Cambodia has
signed an agreement with the U.N. refugee agency to allow Cambodian
refugees to return home from camps along the Thai border, state
radio reported today.
   An official Cambodian government broadcast said the agreement,
signed Monday in Phnom Penh, deals with ``principles and procedures
to welcome back voluntarily repatriated Cambodian refugees.''
   ``The memorandum has been signed and the UNHCR (U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees) would be ready to facilitate Cambodian
refugees who ... wish to return,'' said a U.N. refugee agency
official in Bangkok, Kaiser Zaman.
   Only about 17,000 of the quarter-million Cambodians along the
Thai-Cambodian border are being assisted by the U.N. body, but
others could seek transfer to the U.N. refugee camp of Khao I Dang
and then apply for repatriation, refugee sources said.
   Large numbers of Cambodians fled violence, starvation and disease
as Vietnamese troops invaded their country in late 1978 and ousted
the brutal Khmer Rouge. Vast camps were set up along the frontier,
most of them controlled by various anti-Phnom Penh guerrilla groups,
including the Khmer Rouge.
   During a news conference last month, Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen said his government would be willing to welcome all 250,000
refugees.
   Refugee officials generally believe most will not seek
repatriation because of the continued conflict in Cambodia.
   Only about 4,000 Laotian refugees in Thailand have returned home
under a similar U.N. refugee program that began in 1985.
   Last June, the U.N. refugee agency submitted the names of three
Cambodian refugees who wished to return to Phnom Penh authorities as
``test cases.'' The government has yet to respond to these
repatration requests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
