<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     01-25 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, Feeding the City, Distribute Flour to Factory Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet troops, shouldering what one of
their generals has called Moscow's new task of feeding Kabul, today
distributed 275 tons of airlifted flour and heating fuel to more
than 5,000 workers at a state-owned factory.
   The distribution at a concrete block factory _ in the presence of
invited Western correspondents _ was noticeably orderly compared
with unruly scenes of Afghan soldiers beating back crowds from
Soviet armored personnel carriers during other emergency handouts in
the capital last week.
   The Afghan workers, most of whom maintained still want the Soviet
army out of the country, hauled away 150-pound sacks of flour that
soldiers unloaded from trucks.
   Soviet Col. Vadim Solovye, asked about reports the Soviets
suspect emergency supplies handed over to the Afghan regime wind up
with party officials, said merely: ``To do this through the Afghan
(administration) would take a long time.''
   Behind the Soviet-built factory near Kabul's airport, Ilyushin-76
transport planes were seen landing and taking off in what the
Soviets said was the fifth day of a week-long airlift of 400-500
tons daily from the Soviet cities of Tashkent and Fergana.
   Soviet officers said the airlifts will continue as needed when
the army completes the scheduled withdrawal of its troops by Feb. 15.
   It is unclear, however, whether Moscow will be able to continue
feeding this capital's 2.2 million people if Moslem insurgents _ who
are already causing severe disrupts for road convoys _ mount an
economic blockade aimed at strangling President Najib's regime after
his Soviet protectors withdraw.
   ``Anything can happen, but I think that (a blockade) will remain
really just a threat,'' Maj. Gen. Lev Serebrov, deputy head of the
Soviet military command in Afghanistan, told reporters.
   This week's emergency airlift followed acute shortages in the
city last week, with fights breaking out in long lines at bread
stores.
   Western diplomats say the state-owned silo that holds the
capital's flour supply is down to less than one day's supply. The
Soviets say the city needs 120 tons a day, but Afghan officials say
it needs 500 tons.
   ``It's good they're going, but don't worry, they'll continue to
help us,'' said a 16-year-old who identified himself as Humanani.
The youth came with his father to help carry away several sacks of
flour for their family of nine.
   Sayed Wazir, a wrinkled 55-year-old, complained: ``For two weeks
it's been very hard to get anything.''
   Asked what would happen when the Soviet troops go, he looked
bewildered. ``Perhaps the government will help us,'' he said.
   In another development, Western diplomatic sources said Afghan
military and state security police were making house-to-house
searches and hauling off young men for army conscription.
   Despite evidence of substantial troop movements north toward the
Soviet border and by air, Serebrov said Sunday that the final stage
of the Soviet withdrawal has not yet begun.
   He remained cautious today: ``Just say the withdrawal is
continuing.''
   Western diplomats, who believe the Soviets want to cover up he
withdrawal for security and diplomatic reasons, say the final stage
of the two-stage withdrawal started at the beginning of January.
   Under a U.N.-mandated agreement, 50,000 Soviet troops left
Afghanistan by last Aug. 15 and the rest _ another 50,000 _ are due
to be gone by Feb. 15.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in Dec. 1979 to prop up
the pro-Marxist government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
