<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru a0513 01-25 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Has Not Forgotten Japan's War Role, Foreign Secretary Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th pvs, ``About 27,000, to UPDATE with
comment from British veterans' group. Pick up 8th pvs, ``Howe said...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's sending of representatives to Emperor
Hirohito's funeral does not mean it has ``forgotten or forgiven''
the atrocities Japan committed during World War II, Foreign
Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said.
   The decision to send Prince Philip and himself to the Feb. 24
funeral was made because Japan now is ``an important, democratic
member of the free world,'' Howe said.
   His comments were contained in a letter to Labor Party lawmaker
Jack Ashley that was released today. They are the government's most
detailed response yet to widespread public criticism over British
representation at the funeral of a man many veterans still consider
a war criminal.
   ``I am aware of the very strong feeling which has been expressed
and I can assure you that Britain's representation at the funeral
certainly does not mean that we have forgotten or forgiven the
atrocities committed during the Second World War,'' Howe wrote.
   ``Nothing can obliterate what happened then. Nor shall we ever
forget the great debt we owe to those who fought and died in the Far
East and the terrible sufferings of so many in Japanese prison
camps. The same is true of our Allies, many of whom are being
represented at the funeral by heads of state or government.''
   President Bush is among world leaders who plan to attend the
funeral.
   About 27,000 British prisoners of war died at the hands of the
Japanese during World War II, many of them in the forced
construction of the notorious Burma railway.
   A British war veterans' group said today it appreciated Howe's
remarks but still was dismayed that such a senior member of the
royal family was attending the funeral.
   Harold Payne, president of the Federation of Far Eastern
Prisoners of War Associations, said he feared that ``with all these
high dignitaries going, the Japanese will assume they are being
exonerated for all the dreadful things they did in the war.''
   Howe said the Allies decided at the end of the war in 1945 that
Hirohito should not be held responsible either for the war itself or
for atrocities committed during the war. They found no evidence
linking him personally with political decisions taken by the
Japanese empire during that time, he said.
   ``Indeed, the one decision that the emperor clearly had taken
himself was in August 1945, when the war cabinet was split on
whether to continue the war,'' Howe said.
   ``The government then, for the first time, turned to the emperor,
who decided that Japan should surrender and that he should
personally broadcast the news to the nation.''
   Howe said the queen decided her husband, the Duke of Edinburgh,
should represent her at the funeral after receiving advice from the
government.
   ``It (her decision) was taken in light of the fact that Japan
today is an important, democratic member of the free world and an
important partner of the United Kingdom,'' said Howe, who will
represent Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Ashley said today that ``misguided ministerial advice to the duke
will insult many ex-servicemen precisely because they cannot forgive
or forget.''
</TEXT>
