<HEAD>Teen Sentenced For Setting Gasoline-Soaked Dog Ablaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who police said poured
gas on a chained dog before his friend set it on fire has been
sentenced to 18 months in prison.
   Charles E. Hill Jr., 17, and the friend fatally burned the
Doberman pinscher April 22 in a dispute over a bicycle with the son
of the dog's owner, police said.
   ``It made me sick,'' said Judge Leroy H. Moe, who sentenced Hill
to a year in jail on a misdemeanor animal-cruelty charge and 18
months in prison for burglary of the dog owner's residence and
possession of cocaine.
   The sentences will run concurrently.
   The judge on Tuesday also ordered Hill to undergo a psychiatric
evaluation and perform 100 hours of community service.
   After imposing the maximum jail term for the animal-cruelty
charge, Moe urged the Legislature to upgrade the crime to a felony
punishable by up to five years in prison.
   Hill had pleaded guilty. The co-defendant, Odis Knowles, 17, is
scheduled to stand trial on Thursday.
