<FIRST>r a PM-MurdererMemo     01-25 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Murderer Memo,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recent Parolee Moved After Police Memo Alarms Neighborhood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parolee convicted of killing a police
officer and mutilating a college student was moved from his home for
fear a list of his crimes sent anonymously to neighbors might spark
violence, officials said.
   Raymond Louis George, 36, was moved from his North Hollywood
apartment on Tuesday. He had lived there less than a week.
   George was paroled Jan. 18 after nearly three years in prison for
carrying a knife. He previously served nine years for killing a
police officer, assaulting two others and attacking a 19-year-old
student with a machete in 1974.
   This week, copies of a Police Department internal memo listing
George's crimes were mailed anonymously to neighbors.
   ``We moved him because ... I was afraid there might be some sort
of demonstration,'' said Jerry DiMaggio, regional administrator of
the Parole Division of the California Department of Corrections.
``George is a dangerous person, and we didn't want him to `go off'
if a confrontation occurred.''
   The location of his new home was not disclosed.
   The memo detailed George's criminal history, calling him a
mentally ill man who ``believes his mission in life is to kill
police officers and women.'' An anonymous note accompanying the memo
said he is ``a time bomb waiting to go off.''
   George takes medication for a psychiatric condition.
   ``Somehow the memo got passed around the community, and it
snowballed from there,'' DiMaggio said.
   Capt. Daniel B. Watson, who wrote the memo, said he has begun an
investigation to determine who was responsible for its unauthorized
release.
   Lawrence Singleton, convicted of raping a girl and hacking off
her arms, was paroled from a California prison in 1986. Officials
had to move him repeatedly because no community would accept him.
</TEXT>
