<FIRST>r i PM-Marcos     01-25 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Apparently Seeking Plea-Bargaining With U.S. Authorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ailing Ferdinand Marcos wants to open
talks with U.S. and Filipino authorities on racketeering charges,
which may be a first step toward a plea-bargain to allow him to
return home, officials said.
   Justice Secretary Sedfrey Ordonez told reporters Tuesday that he
received a telephone call from U.S. Assistant Attorney Charles
LaBella, who has been gathering evidence against the deposed
president.
   Ordonez said LaBella told him that Marcos wanted to open talks on
the October racketeering indictment, in which he and his wife Imelda
are accused of embezzling more than $100 million during his 20-year
rule.
   Ordonez refused to spell out details of what Marcos wanted to
discuss other than to say it was limited to the U.S. federal
racketeering charge.
   ``All that was impressed upon me was that Marcos ... is
determined to discuss with the American authorities and the
Philippine government,'' Ordonez said. Marcos and his wife have
lived in Hawaii since he was ousted in the 1986 military-civilian
revolt that propelled Corazon Aquino to power.
   Ordonez said the government wanted to make sure that any
intermediaries were authorized to speak for Marcos and his family.
   ``My reply is we must first be sure that these persons are duly
authorized to speak,'' he said. ``Their plan is to have a spokesman
for Marcos, spokesman for Imelda and spokesman for the children,''
he added.
   In New York, LaBella said Marcos' lawyers contacted him to relay
an undisclosed message to the Philippine government. LaBella refused
to disclose the contents and refused to describe the message as
plea-bargaining.
   The Philippine consul-general in Honolulu, Tomas Gomez, said he
was unaware of the messages from LaBella, but Gomez added: ``If
they're really going through Charles LaBella, it sounds more like a
plea-bargain with the U.S. government, and if that's the case, it's
a very delayed response.''
   Presidential Executive Secretary Catalino Macaraig recently said
the Philippine government can no longer decide whether Marcos can
return home because Marcos is under criminal indictment in the
United States.
   The Philippine government claims Marcos and his associates
embezzled up to $10 billion before his ouster. Mrs. Aquino has
repeatedly refused to allow Marcos to return from exile in Hawaii,
citing national security.
   She has also said Marcos must return all the money he allegedly
stole before there could any discussions on conditions for his
return.
   Marcos was hospitalized Jan. 15 in Hawaii suffering from
pneumonia and bronchial asthma. He was hospitalized twice last month
for treatment of congestive heart failure.
   In Honolulu, a hospital spokeswoman said Marcos' condition was
upgraded to satisfactory and he was removed from a respirator.
</TEXT>
