<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 0850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Quake 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0541,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Death Toll a Quarter of Estimate, Call Off Search</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details of recovery effort, aid flown
in, new quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<UNK>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SHARORA, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said today the death toll from
an earthquake and mudslide in Soviet Central Asia was only about a
quarter of the 1,000 originally estimated, and they called off
efforts to find more survivors.
   ``We will transform the settlement of Sharora into a common grave
with a monument to commemorate the victims of this catastrophe,''
said Khusain Kasymov, Communist Party chief in the Tadzhikistan
republic's stricken Gissar region.
   He said there was no hope of finding more survivors in Sharora,
where 52 homes were buried and 100 bodies were hauled from the mud
and debris.
   The republic's prime minister, Izzatullo Khayoyev, said 274
people were known to have died in Monday's pre-dawn quake, which
toppled all 88 mud-brick dwellings in Okuli-Bolo and sent mudslides
as high as 50 feet onto the villages of Sharora and Okuli-Poyen.
   ``There may be a difference of five or seven people in the
casualties, but no more,'' Khayoyev said in an interview on a grassy
hill overlooking Okuli-Bolo, 20 miles southwest of the capital,
Dushanbe.
   The official Tass news agency earlier made a preliminary estimate
that up to 1,000 people died in the quake and mudslide. Officials on
the scene did not explain the discrepancy in figures.
   A day of mourning was declared in Tadzhikistan, which borders
China and Afghanistan. All flags were at half-staff, plays and
concerts were canceled and restaurants were closed.
   ``The bitter truth is that nobody can be rescued from under a
landslide provoked by the earthquake,'' Tass said.
   But there were stories of miraculous survival.
   Kholmurod Barotov, 17, of Sharora said his 6-day-old cousin
survived the quake held above the torrent of mud by her father, who
perished.
   One man, 27-year-old Sergei Muratov, was found alive buried in
the mud, the prime minister said. Tass said Muratov was in grave
condition at a Dushanbe hospital.
   The agency said Sharora, the largest of the stricken villages,
would be rebuilt near its former site and that construction would
begin in several days.
   The 40-second tremor, which measured 5.4 on the Richter scale,
hit before dawn Monday, loosening layers of mud that cascaded onto
the rural villages.
   Last month, a quake registering 6.9 on the Richter scale killed
about 25,000 people in Soviet Armenia.
   Workers using shovels and bulldozers dug for survivors Tuesday,
but local officials said today the efforts were in vain.
   Vitaly Zhukov, who works at the republic's official news agency
and is chief of a press information center set up in the wake of the
tragedy, said no survivors were found Tuesday.
   Tadzhikistan officials said there would be no attempt to dig out
the bodies of victims, unlike the efforts that lasted for weeks
after the Armenian quake.
   ``Moslem law, the Shariah, says that people buried alive must be
left there,'' Khayoyev said. Most of Tadzhikistan's 4.8 million
people are Moslem.
   He said relatives of those killed in Sharora voted Tuesday to
fence off the settlement and transform it into a common graveyard.
   But other officials said two families had objected, and when
foreign journalists visited the site today, residents and police
were digging with shovels in at least two places.
   Zhukov said the republic would need about 400 prefabricated
houses for survivors in the stricken villages.
   Tass said the Soviet Red Cross sent a planeload of relief
supplies to the region and that the Armenian Red Cross announced it
would send a rescue team to Tadzhikistan.
   A special bank account was set up in Moscow to accept
contributions to aid victims.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda on Tuesday said much
of the mud was carried to the villages by an earthen canal saturated
by melting snow in the Babatag hills overlooking the buried towns.
   When the quake hit, it ``moved in a huge mass onto the
villages,'' Pravda said. ``There is a danger of new mudslides in
similar places in the event of a new natural blow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
