<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Damascus ^Rival Shiite Factions Clash Despite Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with fighting despite cease-fire.
Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``The Israelis...''</UNK>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Shiite Moslem militias battled with
mortars and machine guns in south Lebanon today several hours after
negotiators for both sides reached a cease-fire accord in Syria.
   Police said at least five fighters were injured in the one-hour
battle between the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
the pro-Syrian Amal militia in south Lebanon's Apple province.
   A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
fighting broke out between Hezbollah positions in the villages of
Jbaa and Ein Bouswar and Amal fighters in the hamlets of Kfar Filla
and Jarjou.
   Jbaa is the key to a triangular-shaped enclave controlled by
about 500 Hezbollah fighters on the western edge of Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Earlier in the day, the Syrian Foreign Ministry issued a
statement in Damascus saying the Shiite factions had agreed to an
immediate cease-fire following three days of mediation by Syria and
Iran.
   It said the militias would continue negotiations aimed at
reaching a ``comprehensive reconciliation agreement to regulate the
relationship between Amal and Hezbollah and deal with the reasons
for tension for the sake of Lebanon's unity and its liberation from
Israeli occupation.''
   The factions have been fighting on and off for nine months in a
struggle for control of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the country's
largest sect.
   More than 500 people have been killed and 1,500 wounded in a
series of battles that began in April. Several earlier cease-fires
collapsed under the deep-rooted hostility between the rival militias.
   The Israelis and their militia allies control a ``security zone''
Israel maintains north of its border with Lebanon. The zone was
created in 1985 as a buffer against cross-border guerrilla attacks.
   The Shiite battles have strained the strategic alliance between
Iran and Syria, Tehran's main Arab ally during its eight-year war
with Iraq, and both sides have sought to quell the fighting.
   Hezbollah seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon. The more secular and nationalist Amal seeks a multisect
government in which Moslems would share power equally with the once
dominant Christians.
   Hezbollah advocates guerrilla attacks on Israel in a Moslem
campaign to liberate Jerusalem. Amal seeks only to drive the
Israelis out of the border strip and wants to curb Hezbollah's raids
because they provoke Israeli retaliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
