<FIRST>r a PM-FarmShooting     01-25 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Shooting,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Kills Ex-Sweetheart's Friend, Self At Mushroom Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRUNEDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose girlfriend had broken up
with him fatally shot one of her friends at the mushroom farm where
he worked, then killed himself outside a school as police closed in,
authorities said.
   The gunman, Ignacio Vasquez Segura, 25, of Watsonville, also
seriously wounded two co-workers Tuesday at the farm 80 miles south
of San Francisco.
   His former girlfriend, Francisca Partido, was not at work when
Segura, wearing sunglasses and carrying a semiautomatic rifle,
walked into a packing shed.
   The 50 workers inside scattered when Segura asked for one woman
by name, shot her, then sprayed the inside of the building with
gunfire, said Francisca Gabriella Geisler, a lab technician who was
working in the shed.
   ``Everybody was going crazy. I saw them screaming and trying to
hide,'' she said.
   A 26-year-old woman was killed in the first burst of gunfire,
said sheriff's investigator Bob Reneau. Her identity was not
immediately released.
   Geisler said the woman had tried to help Segura's former
girlfriend since the couple split up three months ago.
   The wounded workers were listed in stable condition today at
Watsonville Community Hospital.
   Segura, who was carrying three clips of ammunition, fired about
12 shots, then fled in a sports car and stopped several miles away
near North Monterey County High School, with a California Highway
Patrol vehicle behind him, authorities said.
   He shot himself in the head before backup officers arrived
moments later, authorities said. Reneau said Segura revved his
engine to full acceleration, muffling the shot.
   The school had been alerted to the shootings and chase, and
Principal Dennis Carocci ordered students to remain in their
classrooms. He said he closed the gate to the school as Segura drove
up.
   Segura's arrival at the school prompted fear of an incident
similar to the slayings last week of five youngsters in a Stockton
schoolyard.
   The high school received about 60 calls immediately after the
incident from concerned parents, Carocci said.
</TEXT>
