<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Press 1stLd-Writethru a0550 01-25 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Press, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Denies Paper Quoted ANC Official</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 5 grafs to UPDATE with protests from newspapers. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of a liberal
Afrikaans-language newspaper pleaded innocent today to a charge of
violating security laws by quoting a banned leader of the African
National Congress.
   Max du Preez, editor of Free Weekly, said the article in question
did not directly quote Joe Slovo, leader of the South African
Communist Party and the only white member of the ANC's national
executive committee.
   Instead, du Preez said, the Nov. 11 article conveyed the views of
the writer, Mark Swilling, a political scientist who joined other
South Africans at a conference in October in West Germany attended
by Soviet officials and ANC leaders, including Slovo.
   Slovo and virtually all other ANC leaders cannot be quoted
legally in South Africa. The organization, which operates from
offices abroad, has conducted a bombing and sabotage campaign aimed
at undermining white-minority rule.
   Free Weekly, established last year, is the only anti-apartheid
newspaper aimed specifically as Afrikaners, the mainly
Dutch-descended whites who control the government.
   At the hearing today in Johannesburg Magistrates Court, du Preez
pleaded guilty to charges that four issues of Free Weekly were
published before it was registered with Department of Home Affairs.
   The hearing will resume Feb. 13.
   In Johannesburg and Cape Town, journalists and political
activists held meetings to protest the government's continuing
crackdown on opposition newspapers and magazines.
   Four anti-apartheid publications, all with circulations of less
than 20,000, have been warned by Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha
that they face temporary closure for allegedly publishing subversive
material.
   The editor of one of the threatened publications, Glenn Moss of
Work in Progress, said the government ensured that its propaganda
was publicized but prevented its opponents from speaking out.
   Another of the threatened publications is Al-Qalam, a monthly
newspaper produced by the Muslim Youth League.
   Its staff issued a statement saying in part: ``The limits to what
we publish will be determined not by the apartheid state, but by our
divinely guided principles of truth and justice.''
</TEXT>
