<FIRST>r w PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0463 01-25 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Leaders Say Pressure to Get a Budget Agreement Very Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Foley, Michel quotes; picks up 4th graf
pvs, Wright presented.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure to get an agreement on a federal
budget is very strong, the House Democratic leader said today,
because nobody wants to see an across-the-board cut in federal
programs.
   ``We have a target pretty much of a budget resolution by about
the 15th of April,'' Rep. Tom Foley, D-Wash., House majority leader,
said on the ``CBS This Morning'' television program.
   ``Nine months from now we run into the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings
(deficit-reduction) deadlines. That means you're going to have an
across-the-board cut in both defense and domestic accounts, unless
they're exempt accounts, which will take care of the budget deficit
targets if we don't have a budget plan that's agreed on between the
House and the Senate and the administration,'' he said.
   ``That sort of pressure to get an agreement is very strong,
because no one wants to see ... an across-the-board cut,'' Foley
said.
   President Bush met Tuesday with Foley and other congressional
leaders to set the stage for this year's budget work. He plans to
speak about his administration's priorities in an address to
Congress on Feb. 9 and then detail his budget proposals soon
thereafter.
   Rep. Robert Michel, R-Ill, the House minority leader, said he
hoped the time frame would be telescoped to considerably less than
nine months.
   ``We'd like to do as we did last year, get our appropriations
bills out on time. That means that the budget resolution and its
allocations ought to be done just as quickly and speedily as
possible,'' he said.
   Foley said he wants to see the specifics of Bush's budget before
making any decision on a budget summit.
   ``We haven't decided on a precise formula or process yet but we
are listening to the president's suggestions and we are promising to
get back to him after we hear the specifics of his budget,'' he said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, made a point Tuesday of
emphasizing there would be consultations, not negotiations.
   ``We'd like to wait and until we see a budget, until we see where
the areas of agreement and disagreement would be, before we
consult,'' Wright said.
   Wright presented Bush a jar of pork rinds and some hot pepper
sauce, one of the president's favorite snacks.
   ``There is (a) good atmosphere,'' said George Mitchell, D-Maine,
the Senate Majority Leader.
   The president's choice for budget director, Richard Darman,
suggested weekly meetings between the White House and selected
leaders from Congress in order to expedite the budget process.
   But while lawmakers said they'd be glad to meet, and would work
to keep the process running on time, none was ready to put a new
team of negotiators above the committees already charged with
working out spending plans.
   ``The president's team will be welcomed, as soon as they want to
come, by our budget committees,'' Wright said.
   ``It would be to our advantage to have the leadership meet in an
informal sort of way from time to time, moving the process along,''
said Michel. He did not support bypassing the current process, he
said.
   Although there is precedent for a budget ``summit'' _ one
occurred in late 1987 after the stock market crisis _ it is
unpopular on Capitol Hill because it cuts most lawmakers out of the
process. In addition, cautious congressional leaders do not want to
be wedded in any way to the Bush budget proposals until they are
made public.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said the president needed first to send up his budget and
then begin discussions without setting up a new framework.
   While a ``summit'' can serve a function, it also carries the risk
of leaving the rest of Congress behind _ and alienating the votes
needed to enact the results, he said.
   ``You could cut a deal at a high level only to find out that
members aren't going to be with you when it comes to a vote,'' he
said. ``A worse thing than failing to get an agreement is getting an
agreement that fails.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
