<HEAD>Kidnapped Man Found Shot Dead In Mall Parking Lot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who kidnapped a warehouse director
snatched a $25,000 ransom and eluded FBI agents and police staking
out the drop-off site, authorities said. The victim was found shot
to death the next morning.
   The surveillance team had lost track of the car the kidnapper
used to pick up the ransom Monday night, Bergen County Prosecutor
John Holl said Tuesday.
   ``It was dark,'' Holl said, adding that officials had been unable
to see clearly enough to give a description of the kidnapper.
   Irving Flax, 58, was abducted Monday on his way to work at the
LDF Trucking Warehouse in Secaucus. He later called to say he
wouldn't be coming in.
   Flax's wife, Marilyn Flax, received two calls from a man
informing her that her husband had been abducted and demanding that
she deliver $25,000 in a plain brown paper bag to the parking area
of a restaurant in Paramus, Holl said.
   Officials from the FBI, the prosecutor's office and police
watched as a man signaled to Mrs. Flax to drop the bag, Holl said.
The man then drove away in a car belonging to the victim.
   Flax was found shot to death in his car Tuesday morning in a
parking lot in Paramus.
   Holl said it was not known whether Flax knew his kidnapper.
