<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-UN 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0504,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shells Hit U.N. Unit Headquarters; 40 Lebanese Expelled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD deportations, U.N. reaction. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two howitzer shells today hit the
headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon but did
not explode, U.N. spokesman Timur Goksel said.
   He told reporters the 155mm shells were fired from around
Marjayoun, headquarters of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army, in
Israel's self-designated security zone. SLA militiamen patrol the
buffer zone with Israeli forces.
   The nine-nation U.N. force, deployed in south Lebanon since 1978,
has frequently been caught in cross fire between rival forces in the
region.
   One shell hit the garden of Maj. Gen. Lars-Eric Wahlgren, Swedish
commander of the 5,800-man U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, in the
compound in the southern border town of Naqoura, Goksel said.
   The other fell between the camps of the Italian and French
contingents inside the beachside headquarters compound, he said. No
casualties were reported.
   A security source in south Lebanon, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the shells were fired during what ``appeared to be a
major operation'' by the Israelis inside the security zone.
   He said he had no details of the reported operation but noted the
Israelis fired about 500 flares that illuminated the security zone
during the night. Several artillery and mortar rounds were fired in
the region, which overlaps the U.N. force's operations zone, the
source reported.
   Israel set up the 6-to-10-mile deep security zone when it
withdrew the bulk of its army from south Lebanon in 1985.The border
strip is designed to curb guerrilla raids into northern Israel.
   Also today, Israeli troops and SLA militiamen expelled 40
Lebanese from the Sunni Moslem village of Shibaa inside the security
zone for refusing to cooperate with an Israeli-sponsored local
administration, police reported.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules,
said they were rounded up during the night and included 25 children
between the ages of one and 12.
   They were driven in SLA trucks to a crossing on the northern edge
of the security zone, where they walked into the Syrian-controlled
Bekaa Valley, the spokesman said.
   On Jan. 5, 30 Lebanese were deported from the zone after being
charged with ``disrupting security'' there.
   Wahlgren visited Shibaa following today's expulsion and said, ``I
express my deep concern over the incident. I've sent a cable this
morning to the secretary-general of the United Nations in New York
explaining the situation.'' ``There is nothing to justify this
action. It is against international law,'' the UNIFIL commander
added in a statement.
   The statement said those expelled included ``a man of 81 and a
woman of 80 and nine children from the same family, the youngest
nine months old.''

</TEXT>
