<FIRST>r a PM-ShotgunSlaying     01-25 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shotgun Slaying,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pro Basketball Player Convicted Of Murdering Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former professional basketball player
has been convicted in the shotgun slaying of his wife and could face
the death penalty.
   Michael Donnell Niles, 33, of Corona, a forward for the Phoenix
Suns of the National Basketball Association in 1980 and 1981, was
found guilty Tuesday of conspiring with Noel Jackson to murder Sonja
Rose Niles in 1984.
   A jury on Monday convicted Jackson of the crime.
   Prosecutors said Niles hired Jackson to kill Mrs. Niles for a
$5,000 cut of a $100,000 life insurance policy. The two men accused
each other of the murder.
   A witness testified that Niles said he wanted his wife killed
because she ``messed me out'' of money from basketball.
   Because the jury determined it was a murder for financial gain,
Niles could face the death penalty at sentencing next week.
   Niles, who had played for California State University, Fullerton,
was a third-string forward for the Suns. He averaged 2.6 points in
46 games.
