<SECOND>PM-Takeoff Aborted, 1st-Ld Writethru,a0499,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>16 Injured As Jet Aborts Takeoff In Thailand</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details, 16 injured. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Thai Airways International jetliner
aborted a takeoff today from Bangkok airport, and 16 people were
injured during the emergency evacuation, officials said.
   The Airbus 300-600 with 252 people aboard was taking off for
Tokyo when the pilot noticed a fire warning indicator and aborted
the flight, said airline Vice President Chusak Baachaiyud.
   As the aircraft stopped, a smoke warning indicator came on and
the pilot ordered an emergency evacuation, Chusak said at a news
conference.
   He said passengers were injured as they left the aircraft on
eight slides from emergency exits.
   Except for one Thai national, all passengers aboard Flight 640
were Japanese, an airline spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The injured, all Japanese, were released from a local hospital
after treatment and were to fly back to Japan late today, Chusak
said.
   He said an investigation showed that a rupture in a high pressure
pneumatic duct caused the aircraft's left engine to overheat. The
smoke warning followed because the sudden and rapid stop generated
excessive heat in the braking system, Chusak said.
   Thai Airways International is the country's flag carrier and
flies to destinations in Asia, Europe and the United States.
</TEXT>
