<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roh Advised To Accept Opposition Demand For Referendum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government leaders today advised
President Roh Tae-woo to accept opposition demands for a referendum
on whether voters support him, officials said.
   At a meeting, leaders of the governing Democratic Justice Party
told Roh voters should have the chance to assess his performance,
said party officials.
   They said Roh called the meeting to deal with opposition
allegations he was trying to avoid the referendum.
   On Tuesday, Kim Dae-jung and other opposition party leaders
agreed to push for the referendum. Before he was elected in December
1987, Roh promised he would hold such a referendum after taking
office, but he set no date.
   Government party leaders lack broad public support but have said
Roh is confident of victory.
   Some opposition leaders contend Roh would have to resign if he
lost a referendum. Roh has only said he would ``accept
responsibility'' if defeated.
   Roh has introduced broad reforms since he took office in
February. But the opposition accuses him of being reluctant to take
firm action to deal with past government abuses.
   Opposition leaders have demanded the government punish officials
involved in corruption and other abuses under the authoritarian
government of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Chun went into rural exile in November after making a public
apology for misdeeds under his administration, and Roh has asked the
nation to pardon him.
   In a related development today, prosecutors questioned three Chun
loyalists, including the former government security head, Chang
Se-dong, on charges of abusing power under the old government.
   Chang played a key role in helping Chun seize power in a coup in
1980.
</TEXT>
