<SECOND>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Optimistic After Jury Notes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with deliberations resuming; PICKS
UP 9th graf pvs, `Ms. Nussbaum ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg was optimistic when jurors asked
for clarification of murder laws, indicating they might be torn over
his guilt or innocence in the death of his illegally adopted
daughter, an attorney said.
   ``For the first time during deliberations, he is feeling more
optimistic,'' defense attorney Ira London said Tuesday.
   The jury returned today for a third day of deliberations.
   Jurors on Tuesday asked state Supreme Court Justice Harold
Rothwax if they could infer that Steinberg fatally beat 6-year-old
Lisa Steinberg based on testimony that he beat his former live-in
companion, Hedda Nussbaum.
   Rothwax told jurors they could not, repeating what he told them
during his instructions. London then moved for a mistrial, which was
denied.
   Steinberg, a disbarred attorney, is charged with murdering Lisa,
whom he obtained at birth from an unwed teen-ager but never legally
adopted.
   The child was removed comatose from Steinberg's Greenwich Village
apartment in 1987 and died at a hospital three days later of a brain
injury.
   Lisa's death in an affluent, well-educated househould attracted
wide attention and raised questions about the duty and ability of
neighbors, teachers and social workers to recognize and report
evidence of child abuse.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former children's book editor, testified as
the prosecution's star witness that Steinberg told her in bed, after
they used cocaine and while Lisa lay comatose on their bathroom
floor, that he had ``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want to get
up.''
   The prosecution maintains that Ms. Nussbaum, whose murder charges
were dropped in return for her testimony, was too physically and
emotionally disabled by 12 years of living with Steinberg to have
harmed Lisa.
   Steinberg's lawyers charge that Ms. Nussbaum fatally beat the
child in a jealous rage.
   Later Tuesday, the jury asked Rothwax if it could move on to the
lesser homicide counts against Steinberg if it was not unanimous on
the murder charge.
   Rothwax reiterated that jurors could consider manslaughter only
if they were unanimous in acquitting him of murder.
   The jury received the case Monday after 12 weeks of trial and 52
witnesses.
</TEXT>
