<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MeatInspection     01-25 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meat Inspection,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meat Group Opposes Overhaul of Inspection System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national meat trade association is urging the
Agriculture Department to withdraw a proposal for overhauling
federal inspection at meat and poultry processing plants.
   USDA made the proposal last November to carry out a 1986 law that
would get tougher on inspections of the most troublesome processing
plants but ease up on those with good records.
   Over time, officials estimated the USDA inspection force at the
affected plants would be reduced by half by retirements and
resignations. The program would rely increasingly on ``good'' plants
policing themselves.
   Department officials said the proposed rule changes would
strengthen inspection in the 6,300 plants that process meat and
poultry by focusing on those that need it most.
   But the American Meat Institute, in comments filed with USDA last
week, said the plan has serious problems and should be withdrawn and
then developed more carefully.
   The group said the proposal is ``overly complex, cumbersome and
burdensome to the regulated industry.''
   Manly Molpus, institute president, said the industry organization
``has supported and continues to support the fundamental thrust of
the changes envisoned in the law'' but that there is ``clearly a
need to rethink'' the proposal.
   The USDA period for public comments on the proposal runs through
Feb. 2. Molpus said the industry doesn't go along with ``the notion
that a rule should be finalized hastily in the face of so many
unanswered and unresolved questions.''
   As proposed, the new rule would apply to plants that make
frankfurters, beef stew, chicken soup, luncheon meats and scores of
other processed items that include meat and poultry. The proposed
rule would not apply to slaughter plants, which would remain under
continuous federal inspection.
</TEXT>
