<FIRST>r a PM-Reagan-PhoneCall     01-25 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Phone Call,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President's Son Admits Leaving Threats On Answering Machine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Reagan, the son of the former
president, has admitted he left a profanity-laced, threatening
message on the answering machine of a photographer suing him over
the publication of two pictures.
   Photographer Roger Sandler has filed a complaint against Reagan
over the Jan. 15 phone call.
   Police Lt. Mike Farrell said he spoke with Reagan on Tuesday and
was preparing a report for the district attorney's office for
possible prosecution.
   Sandler said a caller identifying himself as Michael Reagan said,
``You can quote me,'' then launched into a tirade that threatened
physical harm against Sandler and ended with the words, ``I hope
your ... family dies in a plane crash with you in it.''
   The call was made after Reagan received a subpoena from Sandler
for a small claims action in which the photographer is seeking
$1,500 for copyright infringement over the use of two pictures in
Reagan's 1988 book, ``On The Outside Looking In.''
   Sandler said the pictures were not authorized and uncredited.
   Reagan said in a statement Tuesday, ``I regret that he was
uncredited,'' but contended that Sandler has been continually
raising his prices for the photos.
   ``I lost my cool, which I should not have done, and I apologize
for that,'' Reagan said. ``But I actually apologize more to my
friends and my family for this kind of behavior which is caused by
the pressures placed on me because of my position.''
   Sandler said he wouldn't drop the police complaint.
   ``He seems to act erratically and it seems that he has a violent
temper,'' said Sandler.
   Under California law, it is a misdemeanor to call another
individual with intent to annoy and use obscene language or threaten
to inflict injury. The maximum punishment is six months in jail and
a $1,000 fine.
</TEXT>
