<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   01-25 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0811</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Jan. 21
   Herald-Dispatch, Huntington, W.Va., on honoraria for members of
Congress:
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the powerful House
Ways and Means Committee, has just returned to Washington from balmy
Palm Springs, Calif., where he delivered speeches to a variety of
lobbyists for the tobacco, outdoor advertising and public power
industries.
   Rostenkowski's reward: up to $2,000 per speech, plus all expenses
for himself and his wife, LaVerne. ... Mind you, this warm weather
sojourn for Rostenkowski was 100 percent legal.
   Nor was it unique. Most of his colleagues in Congress accept
similar speaking fees, or honoraria _ as well as first-class airline
tickets and free hotel stays at exotic vacation spots _ from
lobbyists with an interest in pending legislation. ...
   The lawmakers who accept this kind of hospitality protest, of
course, that their votes can't be bought.
   Perhaps not.
   But if Americans are to have any faith and trust in those they
elect to Congress, then those individuals must be above suspicion.
That's clearly not the case as long as the honoraria gravy train
continues to steam down the track.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 22
   Aberdeen (S.D.) American News on honoraria for members of
Congress:
   As part of the (Congressional) pay increase deal, the Quadrennial
Commission recommended a ban on honoraria.
   Honoraria, ... critics say, (are) legalized bribing by special
interest groups or individuals. ...
   In our opinion, honoraria (do) not necessarily need to be banned
_ although the salary hike should be banned. Honoraria should,
however, be strictly regulated. If honoraria remain legal, we
suggest:
   _Lawmakers should be allowed to accept honoraria only when
Congress is not in session ...;
   _Reporting guidelines for honoraria must be reviewed to make sure
there is strict accounting by members of Congress ... (and);
   _Charities receiving lawmakers' honoraria should be carefully
governed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 24
   Sun-Sentinel, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on Andrei Sakharov:
   In the fairy tale, ``The Emperor's New Clothes,'' it takes a
small boy to point out to the kingdom's spellbound subjects that the
preening emperor is actually naked as a jaybird in his fine new suit
of ``invisible thread.''
   With similar brutal honesty, dissident Andrei Sakharov is now
playing the role of unofficial conscience for the Soviet Union,
informing the world that President Mikhail Gorbachev's celebrated
new policies of restructuring, openness and democratization may have
been written in invisible ink. ...
   But Sakharov's warning should slow the rush to anoint Gorbachev
as a born-again champion of human rights.
   The United States and western Europe must closely monitor his
treatment of domestic political opponents and make it clear that
deeds must match words if he expects anyone else to come to his
party in 1991.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 20
   The Tulsa (Okla.) Tribune on Vietnam and Cambodia:
   In the musical ``Oliver!'' there is a number in which that
charming villain, Fagin, sings, ``I'm reviewing, the situation ...''
and, after considering the possible consequences, concludes, ``I
think I'd better think it out again.''
   This would be a good approach for the Bush administration to take
toward the U.S. policy of pressing for Vietnamese withdrawal from
Cambodia.
   An oversimplified foreign policy would call for all Communist
forces to withdraw from countries where they don't belong. ...
   What we may not have thought through is the new agony which may
be imposed on the Cambodians if the Vietnamese withdraw.
   Our long war in Vietnam conditioned us to consider that country's
Communist regime the worst of all possible alternatives. But a good
case can be made for the proposition that the Cambodians were
considerably worse off under the bloody Khmer Rouge regime, 1975-79,
than they have since been under Vietnamese occupation.
   George Bush and his adviser would do well to think it out again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 21
   Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller-Times on gun control:
   Few crimes more tragically illustrate the lunacy of this nation's
gun fetish than the slayings of those five schoolchildren in
California by a misfit wagging an AK-47 assault rifle.
   Such weapons are built for one purpose: to kill as many as
quickly as possible.
   Yet they are readily available for sale _ and the National Rifle
Association irrationally opposes any restrictions on selling such
killer semi-automatic weapons.
   The gun lobby, which has such success in convincing Congress the
nation should be awash in weapons, might find it beyond its
persuasive powers to explain to the parents of those five children
why they had to be put in jeopardy so Bubba could blast away at beer
cans at a 40-rounds-per-minute or greater clip.
</TEXT>
