<TEXT>
   Jan. 20
   The Journal, New Ulm, Minn., on Ronald Reagan's years as
president:
   Ronald Reagan turned over the reigns of government (Friday) to
George Bush. A fitting finale would be for Reagan to stand up in the
saddle on a white stallion, wave his Stetson and gallop off into the
sunset. A movie-like ending for our first actor-turned-president. ...
   It's hard not to think about the Reagan years in terms of a movie.
   Reagan leaves office an immensely popular figure, a leader who
kept smiling and waving while others fell around him. From James
Watt to Ed Meese, his administration was plagued by friends and
followers miscast in their appointed roles.
   But no one ever seemed to blame Reagan for the troubles his
appointed administrators caused. He was the star, the likeable guy
no matter how bad his supporting cast was.
   Reagan was fond of using anecdotes and stories to illustrate and
build support for his views. Listening to him speak was almost like
watching movie clips. In fact, some of his anecdotes actually were
movie clips, but nobody seemed to mind his ability to confuse
fiction and fact. ...
   All in all, the Reagan years have been like an uneven movie
script. There have been holes in the plot and bad casting in some
roles, but the leading man managed to carry it off.
</TEXT>
