<FIRST>r a PM-SpottedOwl     01-25 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spotted Owl,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists' Suit Reinstated, But Injunction On Timber Sales
Lifted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has reinstated a
lawsuit seeking to block logging near spotted owl nests on
government land in Oregon.
   The 3-0 ruling Tuesday by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
was a partial victory for environmentalists, whose suit had been
dismissed by a federal judge in Portland.
   But the appeals court also lifted its ban on logging of so-called
``old-growth'' timber _ timber from virgin or long-established
stands _ near spotted owl sites, at least until the lawsuit is
decided.
   That section of the ruling prompted timber industry lawyer Mark
Rutzick also to claim victory.
   There are 289 spotted owl sites within the timber sale area on
the western slope of the Cascades, said attorney Victor Sher of the
Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund.
   The suit contends logging of old-growth timber would eliminate
the birds by destroying their habitat.
   The spotted owl, which lives in northern California, Oregon and
Washington, is not an endangered species under federal law, although
Sher said the Fish and Wildlife Service is under court order to
reassess the bird's status by May 1.
   Environmental groups regard the spotted owl as an ``indicator''
species, whose reduction in a given region is a signal that other
forms of life are threatened.
   While removing the ban it imposed last June on new logging of
old-growth fir within 2.1 miles of a spotted owl site, the court
said environmental groups could ask a federal judge to forbid sales
from specific sites as they are proposed.
   The timber industry blamed the court's previous order for the
loss of 1,000 lumber and plywood mill jobs, but Sher disputed that.
   U.S. District Judge Helen Frye in Portland had ruled previously
that a 1987 law prohibited the environmentalists from suing. That
finding was largely reversed by the appeals court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AirlineMaintenance     01-25 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Maintenance,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Members Seek Repeal of FAA Rule Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Machinists' Union members fanned out across
Capitol Hill on Wednesday to lobby for repeal of a Federal Aviation
Administration rule change that would allow U.S. airlines to handle
more aircraft maintenance at foreign repair stations.
   About 250 union members sought congressional support for
legislation introduced by Rep. Norman Y. Mineta, D-Calif., that
would repeal the FAA rules change.
   On Nov. 22, 1988, the FAA revised Federal Air Regulation 145 to
eliminate a rule that limited foreign repair to work on aircraft
which are used in operations conducted completely or in part outside
the United States. Under the change, aircraft flown on U.S. domestic
routes can also be repaired at foreign work stations.
   John Peterpaul, transportation vice president of the Machinists'
Union, said the two main issues were jobs and safety.
   ``You're talking about a potential here for thousands, tens of
thousands of jobs to be lost,'' Peterpaul said. About 90,000 of the
union's 600,000 members work in the aviation industry.
   Peterpaul said the safety issue has become ``very, very
distressing'' in view of recent incidents involving aging U.S.
airliners, including sudden in-flight disintegration of aircraft
fuselages and loss of engines.
   ``An airplane doesn't make any money on the ground _ it's always
got to be up in the sky,'' he said. ``This competitiveness that's
been created as a result of deregulation I think is one of the main
culprits involved _ why some of these carriers have gotten so lax in
some of their maintenance.''
   Mineta said that ``prior to the rule change, the ability of
airlines to get their domestic aircraft serviced abroad was quite
limited.''
   With the change, however, ``United States domestic aircraft will
now be able to be maintained overseas ... on a free and open basis,
without prior approval,'' he said.
   ``Let's not mince words,'' Mineta told a union gathering. ``You
know that this is bad policy, I know that this is bad policy. And
those new rules should be repealed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
