<DOCNO> AP890125-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Earthquake     01-25 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Earthquake,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Killed After Earthquake in Gold Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook the
gold fields of the Orange Free State today and was followed by
avalanches at one mine that killed two miners and injured four,
officials said.
   Anglo American Corp., the nation's largest mining company, said
it did not know if the avalanches were caused by the quake, which
measured 4.5 on the Richter scale.
   The earthquake struck at 12:15 p.m. and was centered at Welkom,
in the heart of the Orange Free State mining area, said Luis
Fernandes, chief of the South African Seismological Network in
Pretoria.
   The quake was felt 280 miles to the east, in the coast city of
Durban, Radio South Africa reported.
   Anglo American said after the quake, avalanches occurred in the
No. 3 shaft of its President Brand mine, killing two men and
injuring four.
   The company said the shaft continued to operate, despite
extensive damage to the underground infrastructure.
   The South African Press Association said items were thrown from
store shelves, windows shattered and walls cracked in buildings in
the industrial areas around Welkom.
   Radio South Africa said people rushed from buildings, ceilings
collapsed and shelves overturned in the area, but no injuries were
reported. The report said most businesses in Welkom were closed and
multistory buildings were evacuated.
   OK Bazaars, a national supermarket chain, said its store in
Welkom will remain closed until construction experts analyze the
structural damage from the quake. The company said a pregnant woman
in the store at the time of the temblor was treated at a local
hospital for shock.
   The press association said an aftershock was felt 20 minutes
later in Welkom and surrounding towns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
