<DOCNO> AP890125-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dali 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dali, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0557,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral for Dali</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with funeral. Pickup 5th pvs, ``He
left...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD LORANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FIGUERAS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art collectors, dignitaries and those who
surrounded Salvador Dali during his last reclusive years today
attended funeral services for the artist, who was buried under the
museum where his first exhibition was held.
   Several thousand onlookers applauded as four pallbearers in red,
blue and gold outfits designed by the artist carried his coffin from
a church to the Theater-Museum. It was placed in a marble tomb in
the floor.
   The museum is a former municipal theater where the surrealist
artist first showed his paintings to the public in 1918.
   The tomb dug Sunday, the day before Dali died, is below Dali's
floor-to-ceiling work, ``Lincoln in Dali Vision,'' a giant nude
painting of his late wife, Gala, that turns into a portrait of
Abraham Lincoln when seen from across a courtyard.
   Earlier, a Catalan-language funeral service was held for Dali in
the nearby 14th century Roman Catholic Church, where he was baptized
84 years ago.
   ``Salvador, now that you have found the beauty with which you
have tried to surround yourself, we wish you a perfect rest and
peace,'' said parish priest Narciso Costabella.
   Spanish Culture Minister Jorge Semprun, Catalan regional
government president Jordi Pujol, Dali's cousin Montserrat Domenech
and close friends of the painter joined townspeople in the small
church.
   Dali died in Figueras Hospital of heart failure brought on by
respiratory problems and pneumonia.
   He left an estate estimated at $87.7 million. The estate's exact
value is difficult to calculate because of the erratic prices of
20th century art and the widespread existence of forgeries.
   Dali's will reportedly divides his estate among the governments
of Figueras, Catalonia and Spain. Under Spanish law, it cannot be
read until at least 15 days after his death.
   A major question is whether private collectors own the lucrative
reproduction rights for their Dali works.
   ``I'm here because of a 45-year-old friendship, to pay my
respects to a dear friend and that's all,'' said A. Reynolds Morse,
owner of the largest private Dali collection outside Spain in his
St. Petersburg, Fla., museum.
   The American collector told The Associated Press he did not want
to discuss possible legal battles until after the mourning period
was over.
   Also in town for the funeral was Robert Descharnes, a French
photographer who had been close to Dali since the early 1980s and
was the principal merchant for his works.
   The Spanish press has implied that Descharnes, the author of what
is considered the most complete catalogue of Dali's works, kept the
painter in seclusion and controlled everything around him.
   Decharnes has called the accusations ``absolutely wrong.'' He
administers the Dutch-based company Demart, which owns reproduction
rights to Dali's works until 2004.
   Italian collector Giuseppe Alboretto, who owns more than 500 Dali
works, said today he had prepared legal action against Decharnes,
who he said had prevented him from visiting the painter.
   Figueras Mayor Mariano Lorca said he did not know whether Dali's
only living close relative, his sister Ana Maria Dali, figured in
the will.
   The Barcelona daily La Vanguardia reported that the sister
planned a private funeral service in her home in nearby Cadaques.
   A founder of the surrealist movement in the early 1930s, Dali was
the last of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that
included Pablo Picasso and Joan Miro. A fervent Catalan, he returned
to his native region in 1948 after living in Madrid, Paris and
several U.S. cities.
   In later years he was known as much for his outrageous
personality and theatrical interviews as for his paintings.
   Dali went into seclusion and sank into depression when his wife,
manager and muse, Gala, died in 1982.
   He had a history of heart problems and had been confined to a
wheelchair and fed through tubes since he was badly burned in a 1984
fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
