<FIRST>u a PM-Sheriffs-Overcrowding 1stLd-Writethru a0586 01-25 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sheriffs-Overcrowding, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0586,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Brings Inmates To Capitol In Protest Against Overcrowding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with explanation from governor's
spokeswoman; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Jarvis said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff brought 69 inmates to the Capitol today
in a protest against jail overcrowding, but the prisoners were sent
back on orders from Gov. Joe Frank Harris without even getting out
of their buses.
   ``It was totally irresponsible on the part of the sheriff and was
reckless endangerment of the public,'' said Harris spokeswoman
Barbara Morgan.
   The two busloads of DeKalb County inmates arrived as part of a
protest by Georgia sheriffs, who blame jail overcrowding on the
state's practice of forcing local jails to accept state inmates
until prison space opens up.
   The buses pulled up to a curb outside the Capitol but left about
15 minutes later.
   DeKalb County Sheriff Pat Jarvis said that he never intended to
take the prisoners into the Capitol, that the inmates were
nonviolent and that he had informed police and Capitol security
guards in advance.
   ``This is not a sideshow, this is business,'' he said.
   Jarvis said the demonstration was in support of a Senate bill
that would let counties decide whether to accept overflow state
prisoners. Currently, counties are paid $15 a day per prisoner,
which Jarvis said is about half the actual cost.
   ``We are a holding facility, not a prison,'' said Jarvis.
   Asked where the state should put the 4,000-plus prisoners it has
in county jails, Jarvis said, ``That's not my problem. Where am I
going to put them?''
   Corrections Commissioner David Evans has asked for 7,100 new
prison beds in the fiscal year beginning July 1 to ease
overcrowding, but Harris included no money in his $7 billion budget
proposal for new prison space.
   Bud Cody, executive director of the Georgia Sheriffs Association,
said half of Georgia's jails are overcrowded with state prisoners at
a cost of $27 million a year to local taxpayers.
   ``We've got a very desperate situation,'' he said.
   Earlier this week, overcrowded jails in Colquitt and Turner
counties were the scenes of minor uprisings, and overcrowding was a
factor in recent disturbances at prisons in Milledgeville and at the
Hall County jail.
   ``These things are going to continue to pop up as long as we've
got too many prisoners,'' Jarvis said.
</TEXT>
