<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-IRA 2ndLd-Writethru   01-25 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-IRA, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0562,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Renegade Unit Reportedly Ignores IRA Order To Disband</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with slaying today. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army is engulfed in a serious
internal dispute because its most ruthless unit apparently has
refused to obey the IRA leadership's order to disband, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Times of London quoted unidentified IRA supporters as saying
the order stemmed from a dispute over the unit's killing of
Protestant civilians. The unit will likely continue operating as a
renegade group, the newspaper said.
   Also today, a 26-year-old construction worker was slain in the
Northern Ireland city of Belfast by two gunmen, and police said they
were investigating whether it was another incident of sectarian
violence.
   On Tuesday, another London newspaper, The Independent, quoted
unidentified IRA sources as saying the guerrilla organization had
ordered the unit in question disbanded and disarmed because of the
Protestant slayings.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite the province
with the Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   The controversial unit reportedly is based just across the border
from Northern Ireland around the towns of Ballyshannon and Bundoran.
   The Times said the unit had coordinated the bombing of an annual
memorial service for World War dead at Enniskillen in County
Fermanagh on Nov. 8, 1987. The attack, which killed 11 civilians,
provoked worldwide condemnation of the guerrillas. The IRA admitted
it made a grave error and apologized.
   The Independent reported that one of the killings that angered
IRA leaders was that of Harold Keyes, a 23-year-old Protestant from
County Fermanagh in Northern Ireland. Two gunmen killed Keyes Jan.
15 as he visited his Roman Catholic girlfriend at Ballintra in the
republic, 10 miles across the border.
   Keyes was a former reservist with the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
Northern Ireland's predominantly Protestant police force, but left
the force three years ago. Prime Minister Charles Haughey of Ireland
condemned the slaying as ``brutal and senseless.''
   The Independent said another Protestant civilian victim of the
unit was a 21-year-old Fermanagh woman, Gillian Johnston, who was
slain in March.
   The unit said at the time that its target had been her brother,
who the group claimed was a member of the Ulster Defense Regiment, a
locally recruited British Army unit in Northern Ireland.
   The family and police denied the brother was a member of the
force, and a later IRA statement said the killing had been a mistake.
   The Times said the unit is believed to have seven members,
including a prosperous Irish businesswoman who acted as its
intelligence officer.
   It said the unit has strong links to the Irish National
Liberation Army, a breakaway Marxist rival of the IRA. The newspaper
quoted IRA supporters as saying the unit might switch allegiance to
the rival.
   In today's slaying, Press Association, Britain's domestic news
service, identified the victim as David Dornan from Ballynahinch, 15
miles south of Belfast. The news service said Dornan was a
Protestant and that police thought the shooting may have been a case
of mistaken identity.
   He was operating excavating equipment in a Protestant
neighborhood in Lisburn near Belfast when the gunmen stepped from
behind bushes and opened fire, police said.
</TEXT>
