<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Scott     01-25 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Scott,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ireland's Foremost Architect Dead at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Scott, Ireland's foremost
architect who designed his country's shamrock-shaped pavilion at the
1939 New York World's Fair, has died at the age of 83.
   Scott, who died Tuesday at home, designed some of Dublin's
best-known modern buildings, including the state broadcasting
company's headquarters, the central bus station, and the home of the
Abbey Theater, Ireland's premier playhouse.
   The World's Fair building, named best pavilion by an
international jury, won him global recognition, and Mayor Fiorello
La Guardia awarded Scott honorary citizenship of New York.
   A lover of the writings of James Joyce, Scott built his home by
the seaside south of Dublin next to the Martello Tower, where the
novel ``Ulysses'' opens. In the 1950s he and two friends purchased
the distinctive cylindrical tower to turn it into a Joyce museum.
   He was an honorary fellow of the American Institute of Architects
and in 1975 received the Royal Institute of Architects Gold medal,
the only Irishman to win the prestigious British honor.
   Born June 24, 1905 in Drogheda, Scott was an accomplished actor
before taking up architecture full-time. Specializing in the plays
of Sean O'Casey, he took the lead role in the 1927 Broadway
production of ``The Plough and the Stars.''
   His wife, Patricia, died in 1969. He is survived by four sons and
a daughter.
</TEXT>
