<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Censorship     01-25 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Censorship,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Censors Ordered to Stand Trial for TV Showing of `9{ Weeks'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered four government censors to stand
trial on obscenity charges for clearing the way for the TV showing
of the film ``9{ Weeks'' a year ago, newspapers reported Wednesday.
   They were charged for having reduced the 18-year age limit for
viewing the film in movie houses to 14, thus making it eligible to
be shown on TV.
   The film stars Mickey Rourke and Kim Basinger and focuses on
their heated sexual relationship.
   Rome's La Repubblica newspaper quoted prosecutor Alfredo Rossini
as saying that the lowering of the movie house age limit allowed TV
screening of ``sensually violent and erotic scenes'' to a potential
audience of all ages.
   The commercial Canale 5 network showed the film in prime time
Dec. 16, 1987.
   Newspapers said the court stepped in after receiving complaints
about the TV showing.
   The trial has been set for March 8.
