<HEAD>Museum Director Performs Beachfront Surgery on Wounded Turtle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual emergency operation was
performed this week on Maputo's beachfront, with the director of a
natural history museum performing surgery on a 220-pound giant sea
turtle.
   The turtle was dragged ashore Monday after becoming entangled in
a fishing net, and its neck was cut open by an anchor, according to
an account Wednesday in the daily newspaper Noticias.
   Onlookers called the natural history museum, and the director,
Dr. Augusto Cabral, came to the beach with some of his colleagues.
   They told the fishermen that the turtle was an endangered species
and should be returned to the sea, Noticias said. Cabral then
stitched the wound in the turtle's neck, and the animal swam off
into the Bay of Maputo after being dragged back to the water by some
of the crowd.
