<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     01-25 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saint-Laurent, Laroche Show Simplicity, Luxury, Wearability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yves Saint-Laurent brought back big shoulders and
plunging necklines Wednesday for his haute couture collection of
spring and summer clothes, displaying his flair for elegance and the
female form.
   Whether for day or evening wear, the broadened shoulders are set
off by deep decolletes and big round buttons. Hemlines stop above
the knee and pants abound, ending above the ankle.
   Even when skirts and dresses showed slits soaring high over the
thigh, the collection spelled class from start to finish.
   Saint-Laurent's 90 creations, modeled to the breathy singing of
Marilyn Monroe, got a warm reception from a packed house that
included French actresses Catherine Deneuve, a Saint-Laurent
regular, and Arielle Dombasle, along with ready-to-wear queen Sonia
Rykiel.
   While other high fashion houses earlier showed the soft and
rounded feminine lines of the 1930s, Saint-Laurent's day wear
flattered the form with his signature structured look.
   Suit jackets were shorter than in previous years, their spartan
style softened by oversized cufflinks and big round buttons.
Underneath were daring blouses in the sheerest of mousseline.
   Saint-Laurent's classic pants, both casual and formal, were the
ultimate in wearability, featuring the generous front and back darts
that hide the imperfections of most mortals.
   The most beautiful designs were the simplest, letting the body
speak for itself. One breathtaking dress appearing in several
different versions for day and night was a simple wrap that tied on
the hip. Others had big brassy buttons running up the bust, down the
buttocks and over the hips.
   Pert pillbox hats and large round earrings polished the look.
   Evening wear was a study in colorful bougainvillea floral
patterns in crepes and chiffons, worn long in draped dresses or
over-the-shoulder, floor-length capes.
   Saint-Laurent's tuxedos were as striking as ever, mixing navy and
black and worn with see-through chiffon blouses.
   Another successful design was an updated version of the sailor
middy shirt, presented in soft navy wools and crisp white linen.
   Guy Laroche also presented his collection Wednesday, and there
was something for everyone who likes to wear dresses.
   The colors exploded on the runway, with bright reds, sunny
yellows and juicy oranges melting into pastel pinks, blues and
gentle greens.
   Like Saint-Laurent, Laroche displayed big shoulders and spiced up
the simplest designs with sexy decolletes in front and back.
   Once the preserve of beachwear, the bustier is everywhere.
Laroche makes them in pink and yellow leather for daytime and in
silk and lace for evening.
   Except for a few cruise-line outfits with wide, flowing sailor
pants draped gorgeously at the waist, Laroche was all dresses, long
and short.
   In daytime wear, hemlines modestly skimmed the knee. There were
big-shouldered safari suits in orange shantung, light wool coat
dresses in Prince of Wales plaid and short leather suits with bolero
jackets.
   Laroche excelled in cocktail and evening wear, using drapery to
highlight hourglass waistlines and curvy hips. The lines were pure
and feminine, with lots of cut-out backs set off by elaborate
embroidery, ruffles and bows.
   Some cocktail dresses had such big bustles, sitting down would be
next to impossible. Others featured asymmetrical hemlines, rising to
midthigh in the front, brushing the floor in the back _ the design
also used in the collection's ``piece de resistance,'' the wedding
dress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
