<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayShootings     01-25 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Shootings,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shooting Reports Take Psychologial Toll On Drivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Motown, where cars are synonymous with life
itself for many, psychologists say a recent skein of reported
roadway shootings has shaken motorists' confidence in their cars as
rolling security.
   Since November, there have been at least 10 random highway
shootings in and around Detroit. Some were roadside snipers, others
stemmed from traffic disputes.
   ``You've got a lot of idiots out there with guns in their cars
and you put that together with publicity and people start taking
shots at each other,'' Assistant Oakland County Prosecutor James
Halushka said.
   ``It certainly makes people anxious and it affects people's
behavior on the road,'' said Emanuel Tanay, a professor of
psychiatry at Wayne State University in Detroit. ``The car has been
known as a sort of sanctuary but now, that's not the case.''
   The most serious incident occurred Nov. 22, when Michael Warner,
31, of Trenton, was shot and killed while sleeping in a car driven
by his wife on Interstate 75 in Southgate. Police have made no
arrests.
   Since then, there have been reports of shots shattering car
windshields. State police investigators subsequently discovered the
damage was caused by rocks. No serious injuries have been reported.
   It has happened before. In the summer of 1987, at least five
people were killed and 20 injured in an unrelated string of
shootings on Southern California freeways. Some of the incidents
stemmed from traffic disputes while others appeared to be random
sniper attacks.
   Los Angeles area authorities set up a highway violence hot line
to handle calls from worried drivers and special aerial freeway
patrols were established. The shootings later tapered off.
   Michigan authorities have no similar plans. State police are
trying to be more alert but lack the manpower to increase road
patrols, said Lt. David Werner, commander of the state police
freeway post in Detroit.
   Tanay said the media have given the Michigan incidents _ real and
imagined _ unwarranted attention, which has contributed to drivers'
anxiety.
   ``We live in a society where there's violence. Why is it so
shocking that it happens in a car? People die in car crashes
everyday,'' he said.
   Werner also criticized the heavy news coverage of the shootings.
   ``It's my feeling that copy catting always occurs in things of
this type,'' he said. ``I've tried to downplay things of this
nature, though.''
   Authorities say most people now are driving more cautiously to
avoid traffic disputes. But the extent to which driving behavior is
altered depends on the psychological makeup of the particular
individual, said Dr. William Birkhill of Southfield-based Couseling
Associates.
   ``It depends greatly on how much people use denial to protect
themselves,'' Birkhill said. ``Many deal with traumatic events by
denying them. Most people _ if it hasn't happened to them _ they are
able to dismiss the possibility of danger.''
   Catching a highway shooter is difficult, Werner said. ``In most
instances, there are no witnesses and we have few leads to go on.''
   Authorities hope the sentencing of John Rayes, 17, to eight to 20
years in prison for a highway shooting will be a deterrent. Rayes
pleaded guilty Jan. 3 to the shooting of 19-year-old Dawn Lamsa on
I-696 in Madison Heights. Lamsa was wounded in the neck and was
hospitalized for several days.
   Rayes told police he mistook Lamsa for someone he had argued with
at a carnival earlier in the evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
