<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Bomb     01-25 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Bomb,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Found, Defused at New Orleans Abortion Clinic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today defused a crude bomb outside an
abortion clinic.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the explosive
device found by a parking attendant at the Delta Women's Clinic,
said police spokesman John Bryson. The bomb was concealed by a
manila folder or envelope, he said.
   Police gave no details on the composition of the bomb or say how
powerful it was, but Bryson said, ``It was a makeshift bomb, very
crude.''
   Bryson didn't know how many people were evacuated from the
clinic. Toni Scott, clinic director, did not immediately return a
telephone call.
   The FBI and the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
were called in to investigate, Bryson said.
   Delta Women's Clinic has been the focus of several recent
anti-abortion demonstrations. More than 70 people were arrested Jan.
14 after blocking entrances.
   On Saturday, the clinic was the stopping point for a peaceful
anti-abortion march marking the 16th anniversary of the Supreme
Court decision legalizing abortion.
