<DOCNO> AP890125-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateNameChange     01-25 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Name Change,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>What's in a Name? North Dakota By Any Other Name Would be as Cold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Dakota's reputation for blizzards,
howling winds and subzero cold may partly be blamed on its name,
according to a legislative resolution that seeks to change it to
simply ``Dakota.''
   ``I have come to see the word Dakota as having a much more
poetic, romantic connotation than the term North Dakota,'' said
state Sen. Tim Mathern, who introduced two resolutions in the
Legislature Wednesday calling for the change.
   State tourism director Jim Fuglie called the idea ``wonderful,''
but South Dakota Gov. George Mickelson said it would forsake a
century's worth of history.
   ``If either of us wants to change our name now, we might as well
call ourselves Michigan or Tallahassee, because any name change now
would deny 100 years or more of our heritage,'' Mickelson said.
   North Dakota Gov. George Sinner said he hadn't thought about the
issue, but ``I certainly don't have any built-in opposition.''
   One of Mathern's two resolutions calls on Congress to amend
federal enabling legislation to permit the name change. The 1889 act
admitted North and South Dakota, Montana and Washington to the
United States.
   The second resolution calls for a statewide election to make the
necessary amendment to the North Dakota Constitution.
   North Dakota ``conveys an image of severe climactic conditions,''
according to the first resolution, while Dakota ``conveys an image
reflective of the pioneering spirit of the inhabitants of the
state.''
   Dakota, which means ``friend'' in the Sioux language, was the
name for the territory that later became North and South Dakota, as
well as much of Wyoming and Montana.
   ``This is a serious look at the name of our state during our
centennial year,'' said Mathern, a Democrat. ``It gives us a chance
to look at what we feel good about, and want to take with us into
our second century.''
   The idea is not new. Bob Saueressig, a Bismarck advertising
executive, said in 1983 he and others paid for a billboard that
proclaimed: ``Let's drop `North' and call it `Dakota.'''
   The proposal generated national publicity, but the idea didn't
fly. Some wags suggested dropping ``Dakota'' instead, and the
proposal ``basically got laughed down,'' Saueressig said.
   Mathern, however, said his suggestion was serious.
   ``For those people who, at some point, need to have some levity
with this, I can understand that,'' he said. ``For me, it is not a
joke.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
