<FIRST>r a AM-GatesofHell     01-25 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gates of Hell,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Senate Committee Approves Children's Home Reporting Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legislative committee has approved a bill
requiring children's homes to report certain information to the
state, a move sparked by widespread publicity on alleged abuse at a
fundamentalist Christian boarding home.
   The Senate Public Health and Welfare Committee approved the
measure Tuesday without substantive debate. Panel Chairman Robert
Huggins said he would likely call the bill up for debate before the
full Senate next week.
   ``It's the first time the Legislature has taken this bold a step
as far as regulation of these homes are concerned,'' he said. ``It's
been something that in the past has been so politically hot that no
one would touch it.''
   Sen. Jim Bean, chairman of the subcommittee that handled the
bill, said the proposal would not infringe on religious rights of
church-operated schools.
   The bill would require the homes to provide the state Department
of Health with:
   _ Names, guardians and nearest relatives of all residents.
   _ Proof of inspections by a local fire department or the state
fire marshal's office and the local health department.
   _ A statement that medical records are maintained on each child.
   The bill also would require the homes to file monthly reports
with the Department of Health and have on hand policies addressing
discipline and parent-child communication.
   Huggins said he would have preferred seeing the state Department
of Public Welfare as the agency receiving the reports rather than
the Department of Health.
   He said he believed political fallout from the Welfare
Department's raid on the Bethel Home for Children in Lucedale last
summer might have led to the Department of Health being the
designated agency.
   On June 10, the Welfare Department took temporary custody of 72
Bethel children based on allegations of abuse and neglect. Most of
the children taken from the home were released to parents or
guardians, but the state took custody of 17.
   The Rev. Herman Fountain, a fundamentalist Baptist minister and
founder of the controversial Bethel Home, has vowed to ignore any
legislation that becomes state law. He claims the home is part of
his church and is exempt from any kind of state regulation under the
U.S. Constitution.
</TEXT>
