<FIRST>r i AM-Carlsson     01-25 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carlsson,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tributes Paid to U.N. Commissioner Killed on Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats and lawmakers paid tribute Wednesday to
Bernt Carlsson, the United Nations commissioner for Namibia who was
killed aboard the Pan Am Boeing 747 that exploded over Scotland.
   Carlsson, 50, had been traveling to New York aboard Flight 103 to
attend the signing of an independence agreement for Namibia when the
jetliner was blown Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on
the ground.
   ``With his death, humanity has lost one of its great servants,''
opposition Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock told a memorial meeting
at St. James' Church in central London.
   Kinnock, who knew Carlsson personally, said the Swedish diplomat
had used his skills to help the persecuted and deprived, and ``he
had so much more to do in the world that needed him to do more.''
   Also present were representatives of the Swedish Embassy and the
South West Africa People's Organization, which has fought a
guerrilla war to wrest Namibia from South African control.
   In a message read to the gathering, U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar called Carlsson a true internationalist.
   ``We mourn Bernt Carlsson's death, but in doing so, also express
our gratitude to him for the shining example he set,'' the message
said.
</TEXT>
