<HEAD>Despite Politics, Khomeini Still Conducts Marriage Ceremonies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini still finds
time to marry couples despite his political responsibilities, Iran's
official news agency said Wednesday.
   His daughter, Zahra Mustafavi, said Khomeini set aside time to
conduct marriages in ``certain cases.'' She did not elaborate.
   Mrs. Mustafavi, made the comments in an interview published
Wednesday in the English-language Tehran Times daily, amid
persistent reports that Khomeini was in poor health. Her comments
were carried by the Islamic Republic News Agency, which was
monitored in Nicosia.
   She said a main question her father asks the couples he marries
was ``whether they have read the terms and conditions in the
marriage documents.''
   The 88-year-old revolutionary leader has been ailing since a
heart attack two years ago and rarely leaves his heavily guarded
residence in the northern Tehran suburb of Jamaran.
   Khomeini's 49-year-old daughter, who is married with two
children, said the last time she saw her father was Monday and he
was ``all right,'' IRNA reported.
   She said her father is very kind to all his children and never
interferes in their lives. ``He is more a listener than a speaker.''
   Mrs. Mustafavi is one of Khomeini's three daughters. He also has
two sons: Ahmed, 48, who is one of his closest advisors and Mustafa,
who died during Khomeini's exile in Iraq.
</TEXT>
