<SECOND>PM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0566,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Greets Steinbrenner, Iacocca After Being Heckled</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 4 grafs to add details. Pickup 4th pvs, `Before they...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II greeted American businessmen George
Steinbrenner, Lee Iacocca and Bill Fugazy today at the end of a
general weekly audience that was disrupted by a young man who
shouted at the pontiff.
   The three businessmen were seated in the front row of the Paul VI
Auditorium, said a Vatican spokesman, the Rev. Giovanni D'Ercole.
   The brief meeting was set up by the office of the New York
archbishop, Cardinal John O`Connor, said Frank Lattanzi, spokesman
for the U.S. Embassy to the Vatican. Steinbrenner is owner of the
New York Yankees, Iacocca is chairman of the the Chrysler Corp., and
Fugazy is a New York businessman.
   Lattanzi said the encounter lasted less than five minutes and
amounted to a handshake and introduction. He said Steinbrenner
brought some Yankee paraphernalia, such as warm-up jackets and
programs, and that the items were given to a Vatican official
afterward, not to the pope.
   Before they met, the pope's general weekly audience was briefly
interrupted when a young man stood up and began shouting at the
pope. Vatican guards took him out of the hall and the pope continued
with his address.
   The man abruptly stood up and yelled out in English, ``Speak
English,'' toward the end of the audience, when the pope reads
greetings in several languages following a religious speech in
Italian, a witness said.
   The man, whose nationality and name were not immediately known,
was being questioned by Vatican security.
   The pope stopped speaking at first when the man began shouting
but then resumed his speech and the audience applauded. However, the
pope was forced to pause during the commotion when the guards rushed
the man.
</TEXT>
