<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     01-25 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Promises No `Duck Hunting' for New Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle vowed Wednesday the
Bush administration won't go ``duck hunting'' for ways to hike
taxes, even as other administration officials talked of ways to
raise new revenues.
   Quayle made a play on President Bush's ``no new taxes'' pledge
and Budget Director-designate Richard Darman's explanation of taxes
to Congress in which he said, ``If it looks like a duck, walks like
a duck and quacks like a duck, it's a duck.''
   Quayle, in his first policy speech since becoming vice president
on Friday, said some people try to use the budget deficit as an
excuse to go ``duck hunting'' for new taxes for their ``pet spending
ideas.''
   ``Remember the code word as we go into this budget battle this
year _ no duck hunting, period,'' Quayle told a conference of the
Citizens for a Sound Economy Foundation. ``No hunting ducks, No
hunting for taxes.''
   Quayle made the comments as Bush told reporters at the White
House that he would entertain an idea raised by Treasury Department
officials to tax depositors who put money in federally insured
institutions.
   Bush said he sees the idea as an option. But he deflected a
question on whether that would not be considered a tax by asking
whether an entrance fee to national parks is a tax.
   The proposed depositor fee would be 25 cents on every $100
deposited in federally insured institutions and the money would be
used to help the ailing savings and loan industry. Accounts in
commerical banks and credit unions also would be subject to such
fees.
   Quayle reiterated Bush's support for a presidential line-item
veto of the annual budget, instead of the current system of
accepting or rejecting the entire budget package.
   He said also that Congress should be held accountable through a
vote when a president asks it to rescind appropriations for
unnecessary spending that has already been approved. Currently the
money must be spent unless Congress acts on a president's recission
request within 45 days. Quayle said Congress should ``be forced to
act within 15 days after a rescission request is sent to Capitol
Hill.''
   Such reforms would give the president ``a greater voice in how
Congress spends the taxpayers' money.''
   ``Congress itself has a duty to its consitutents to work with the
administration to spend our money more prudently and responsibly
than it has in the past,'' he added.
   Quayle noted a Roper poll released Wednesday by the Citizens for
a Sound Economy had said most Americans believe the government
should hold down spending, not raise taxes, to cut the federal
budget deficit.
   The in-person interviews with 1,947 adults nationwide found that
62 percent believed increased spending caused the deficit while 9
percent said inadequate revenues were the cause and 21 percent put
the blame on a combination of spending and revenues.
   Quayle said the poll shows ``a broadly based distrust of the way
our government operates in taxing and spending.''
   The poll, conducted Dec. 3-10, also found 73 percent of those
polled said the government should hold down spending to cut the
deficit while 5 percent favored raising taxes and 12 percent wanted
both options used.
   The poll also asked people their opinions on whether Social
Security payments should have cost of living increases even if
government spending were held to present levels for two years.
   Sixty-four percent favored Social Security increases in a
spending-freeze situation while 26 percent were opposed.
   On new government programs, 43 percent of the respondents said
they oppose creation of new government programs until the deficit is
eliminated, while 40 percent favor new programs even with the
deficit.
   Citizens for a Sound Economy is a conservative organization
focusing on research and educational activities in economic issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     01-25 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Says War Could Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister said Wednesday ``any
spark'' on the 730-mile border with Iran could rekindle the war that
was suspended in August after eight years and an estimated one
million deaths.
   Latif Nussayif Jasim, Iraq's information minister, said in an
interview the factionalized Iranian leadership does not seem capable
of negotiating peace and talks will remain deadlocked until that
changes.
   Special U.N. envoy Jan Eliason met with Iranian leaders Wednesday
in Tehran in an attempt to revive the negotiations, which began in
Geneva on Aug. 25, five days after a U.N.-supervised cease-fire took
effect.
   Eliasson is expected in Baghdad on Friday, perhaps with proposals
from Iran.
   Each side accuses the other of frustrating the negotiations.
Iranian television said Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told
Eliasson ``It is not acceptable that ... our territories are still
occupied due to Iraqi subterfuges and delaying tactics.''
   Iran claims Iraqi soldiers still occupy 260 square miles of its
territory. Iraq says Iran is stalling for time to rebuild its
military forces, which suffered several defeats last year and forced
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime to accept a truce. The Iraqis
accuse Iran of massing troops on the border.
   U.N. military observers say the cease-fire is holding, despite
claims by both sides of violations.
   Neither side has withdrawn from the truce line as stipulated by
the terms, and Iranian officials have said they see no point in
resuming the Geneva talks unless the United Nations can guarantee
progress.
   Jasim said: ``We believe Iran does not have the ability to make a
decision regarding peace. That's why they want to maintain the
no-war, no-peace situation.''
   His apparent reference was to divisions in the Iranian hierarchy
after Khomeini's decision last July 18 to accept a U.N. Security
Council cease-fire resolution,
   Without a stable cease-fire ``any spark could lead once again to
an unsolvable problem,'' the information minister said.
   He denied Western news reports that Iraq was willing to make
concessions on the Shatt-al-Arab, which is Iraq's only sea outlet
and was the prewar southern boundary between the Persian Gulf
neighbors.
   ``The Shatt-al-Arab is an Iraqi waterway,'' Jasim declared.
   The dispute over who controls the Shatt, formed by the confluence
of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, helped start the war in
September 1980.
   Iraq invaded Iran after weeks of border skirmishes. A few days
before the invasion, President Saddam Hussein abrogated a 1975
treaty drawing the boundary down the middle of the waterway.
   Before that treaty, the border had run along the eastern, Iranian
bank, putting the waterway in Iraq. Control of the Shatt is at the
center of the impasse in Geneva.
   Jasim said Iran must allow Iraq free navigation through the
Persian Gulf and its southern outlet, the Strait of Hormuz. Iraq
also wants the Shatt cleared of sunken ships and other debris under
U.N. supervision and negotiations on its status postponed until the
job is done.
   Iran would have full rights to use the waterway after a
settlement, Jasim said. He added that Iraq ``has no ambition for
Iranian territory'' and is eager to conclude a peace treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SniperTrial     01-25 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sniper Trial,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Jury Selected in Sniper Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusually large jury was selected
Wednesday to hear evidence against a man accused of terrorizing
Blackstone Valley residents with a series of sniper attacks two
winters ago.
   Selection of the 16-member jury was completed after a last-minute
appeal for more potential jurors. The original group of 25 jury
canidates was exhausted because many would-be jurors were familiar
with the sniper attacks, which received wide publicity.
   Juries normally contain 14 members, including two alternates, but
two additional alternates were selected because the trial of Peter
T. Trepanier is expected to take four to six weeks, said prosecutor
Eva-Marie Mancuso.
   Trepanier, 25, of Burrillville, is accused along with a high
school classmate of 35 counts, including multiple charges of assault
with intent to commit murder, arson, burglary, and conspiracy. The
arson charges carry a potential sentence of life in prison.
   The classmate, Russell J. Ducharme II, is scheduled to go on
trial after Trepanier's case is finished.
   The charges stem in part from eight of 11 nighttime sniper
attacks in December 1986 and January 1987 that forced Cumberland and
North Smithfield residents to huddle behind drawn curtains. The
attacks prompted Gov. Edward D. DiPrete to call out the National
Guard, which patrolled for about six weeks.
   Superior Judge Dominic F. Cresto said after the jurors were sworn
in Thursday they would tour the rural area where the sniper attacks
occurred. Opening arguments were tentatively scheduled for Friday.
   Two of the attacks occurred in Bellingham, Mass., where Trepanier
and Ducharme also face charges of assault with intent to commit
murder. Massachusetts authorities were waiting for the Rhode Island
trials to conclude before pressing those charges, said Catherine
Ferrone, a Bellingham police secretary.
   The men were arrested when Trepanier walked into the Woonsocket
police station on Oct. 8, 1987, and allegedly confessed to the
snipings and implicated Ducharme.
</TEXT>
