<HEAD>Oil Drilling Rig Sinks in Bad Weather; No Casualties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An offshore oil rig sank
Wednesday in stormy gulf waters off Abu Dhabi, but no injuries were
reported, shipping sources said.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the rig
was the JAKS 1, but they had no further details on its size or
capacity.
   The rig collapsed slowly, allowing for the workers to evacuate,
the sources said.
   The Abu Al-Bakoosh oil field is owned by the emirate of Abu Dhabi
and is operated by the Abu Dhabi National Oil Co. in conjunction
with the French oil company Total.
   It has a production capacity of 50,000 to 60,000 barrels per day.
It is about 120 miles north of Abu Dhabi.
   The field was the target of an air raid in a spillover of the
Iraq-Iran war into the Persian Gulf in November 1986. At least eight
foreign workers were killed.
