<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Massacre     01-25 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Massacre,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monument Planned As Probe Determines at Least 30,000 Killed in Forest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Byelorussian republic plan to
build a monument to the estimated 30,000 victims of political
executions carried out in a forest during Josef Stalin's rule, a
newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The government daily Izvestia quoted Nina Mazai, a deputy premier
of Byelorussia, as saying that 510 mass graves have been found in
the Kuropaty area near the republic's capital of Minsk.
   Ms. Mazai, who chairs a commission investigating the killings,
said six graves, each containing the remains of 50-60 people, have
been excavated.
   Workers have found cartridge cases, bullets and clothes, and
these objects have been analyzed using a laser, she told Izvestia.
   Ms. Mazai said at least 30,000 people were buried at Kuropaty,
down from previous estimates that more than 100,000 had been killed
there. The exact figure cannot be determined, she said.
   The mass executions were carried out by the secret police, which
at the time was called the NKVD, from 1937 to 1941, and the
commission is trying to determine the motive for the slayings and
the identities of the victims, the official said.
   A competition for design of a monument to the victims is being
organized by the Byelorussian Culture Ministry, the State
Construction Committee, Minsk city government and the unions of
architects and artists.
   In October, the weekly newspaper Moscow News reported that men
and women branded ``enemies of the people'' under Stalin were
brought alongside newly dug ditches at Kuropaty and made to stand in
rows. They were then gagged and shot, the newspaper said.
   The article said Soviet authorities tried to cover up what had
happened at Kuropaty.
   Under Stalin, millions of innocent Soviets lost their lives or
were imprisoned in a campaign of terror. Revalations of Stalin's
crimes have flooded the Soviet press since Mikhail S. Gorbachev took
power and instituted his campaign for openness four years ago.
</TEXT>
