<FIRST>r a AM-Sheriffs-Overcrowding     01-25 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sheriffs-Overcrowding,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriffs Plead For Funds To End Jail Overcrowding</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff brought 69 prisoners from his jail to
the state Capitol on Wednesday to dramatize the jail overcrowding he
and other sheriffs say the Legislature must remedy.
   DeKalb County Sheriff Pat Jarvis said he sent the prisoners back
to Decatur after he was threatened with arrest for criminal
trespassing. The prisoners never left the two jail buses, and Jarvis
said he never intended to take them into the Capitol, where groups
of schoolchildren toured.
   It was a part of a protest by sheriffs and their representatives
from across Georgia who are forced to house more than 4,100 state
prisoners because state prisons have no room.
   State prisons currently house about 18,700 prisoners, 43 percent
more than they were designed to hold.
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris ordered the buses away, calling the display
``totally irresponsible.'' Jarvis denied the charge, saying he had
informed Capitol security guards and Atlanta police they were coming.
   ``This is not a sideshow, this is business,'' Jarvis said of the
protest. He described the prisoners as non-violent.
   Jarvis said the demonstration was to support Senate Bill 149,
which would let counties decide whether they want to accept overflow
state prisoners for long periods.
   Jarvis, who said his jail leads the state with 250 overflow state
prisoners, was asked where the state should put them if it can't
require counties to house them.
   ``That's not my problem. Where am I going to put them?'' he said.
   Under current law, counties can be forced to accept the inmates.
They are paid $15 a day per prisoner, which Jarvis said is about
half the actual cost.
   Hall County Sheriff Dick Mecum, whose jail had a costly uprising
blamed on overcrowding during the Christmas holidays, said
legislative priorities are skewed.
   ``If Atlanta wants to build a stadium let them build a domed
stadium. But let them pay for it; leave us out of it,'' he said at a
news conference inside the Capitol. He was referring to legislation
that would pay for a domed stadium with hotel-motel tax revenues.
   The $7 billion-plus budget proposed by Harris for fiscal 1990
includes no money for more prisons, even though Corrections
Commissioner David Evans has asked for 7,100 new prison beds, said
John Jeffries of Clarke County, vice president of the Association
County Commissioners of Georgia.
   Many county jails have more state overflow inmates alone than
they have beds, said Sheriff Greg Coursey of Burke County, president
of the Georgia Sheriffs Association. He said his jail, with 22 beds,
has 44 inmates he was forced to accept from the state.
   He said sheriffs are being hit with lawsuits spurred by
overcrowding, poor hygiene and riots.
   Just this week, overcrowded jails in Colquitt and Turner counties
reported minor uprisings, and overcrowding was a factor in recent
disturbances at prisons in Milledgeville and Hall County.
   ``These things are going to continue to pop up as long as we've
got too many prisoners,'' Jarvis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
