<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Philip is to present Ronald Reagan with the
Churchill Award, given to those who ``epitomize the bold spirit'' of
Britain's wartime prime minister, Buckingham Palace said Wednesday.
   Other recipients of the award have included British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher and Averell Harriman, the former U.S.
ambassador in London and Moscow.
   The foundation was set up in 1954 by American friends and
admirers of Churchill to enable Americans to study and carry out
research at Churchill College in Cambridge University.
   The award will be presented in Los Angeles on May 17.
   The 67-year-old prince, husband of Queen Elizabeth II, will stop
off at Los Angeles on a trip to Quebec, Canada, to attend the United
Empire Loyalists Association convention.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Cleese won libel damages Wednesday from a
newspaper that claimed he had increasingly come to resemble Basil
Fawlty, the manic hotel owner he played in the hit television series
``Fawlty Towers.''
   His lawyer, Roderick Dadak, said Cleese did not tweak people's
ears or routinely fly into manic or irrational rages and ``the claim
that in real life he resembles Basil Fawlty is absurd.''
   In an out-of-court settlement approved Wednesday by the High
Court, Cleese, 49, accepted undisclosed ``substantial'' damages, to
be donated to a charity of his choice, from publisher Robert
Maxwell's Mirror Group Newspapers. The newspaper group also agreed
to pay Cleese's legal costs and publish an apology.
   The newspaper group's lawyer, Simon Gallant, said the article
should not have been published and apologized for embarrassing and
distressing Cleese.
   The Daily Mirror reported in August 1987 that Cleese, a founding
member of the Monty Python comedy troupe, had got into the habit of
painfully tweaking the ears of fellow cast members and flew into a
rage when they objected during the filming of ``A Fish Called
Wanda.''
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified ``friend'' who said
colleagues were complaining that Cleese had become increasingly like
the sour, abusive hotel keeper he created in the 1970s series
``Fawlty Towers.''
   Dadak said Cleese had actually gotten along very well with fellow
cast members. The film, which also starred Jamie Lee Curtis and
Kevin Kline, was released last year and became one of the year's
biggest hits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ilona Staller, Italy's porn star
parliamentarian better known as Cicciolina, was convicted Wednesday
of public obscenity and given a suspended sentence.
   Ms. Staller, who earlier called the charge ``absurd,'' waived her
parliamentary immunity in order to stand trial on the accusation
stemming from her September 1987 appearance in Venice's famed St.
Mark's square. She was given a five-month suspended prison sentence.
   The Italian news agency ANSA reported that witnesses testified
that Ms. Staller was topless and wearing only a see-through skirt
when she arrived at the square in a gondola.
   The witnesses said she blew kisses to admiring fans after she
climbed atop a plaster replica of one of the horse statues in the
square to be photographed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Falcon Crest'' lover boy Lorenzo Lamas
married actress Kathleen Kinmont, daughter of his former co-star
Abby Dalton, at a Las Vegas chapel last weekend, his publicist said
Wednesday.
   It was the third marriage for Lamas, 31, son of the late actor
Fernando Lamas and actress Arlene Dahl, and the first for Miss
Kinmont, who is in her early 20s, said Lamas' publicist, Eddie
Michaels.
   The couple exchanged vows Saturday at the Graceland Chapel in the
gambling resort. A.J., Lamas' 5-year-old son by his first wife, was
the ring bearer and their daughter, Shayne, 3, was the flower girl.
   The newlyweds skipped a honeymoon and Lamas returned to work.
   Lamas plays the grandson of scheming matriarch Jane Wyman on
``Falcon Crest,'' CBS' long-running nighttime soap.
   He has been romantically linked to several of his co-stars. He
was once engaged to actress Robin Greer, who appeared as his love
interest on the show. Actress Daphne Ashbrook, who also was on
``Falcon Crest,'' gave birth to Lamas' daughter, Paton Lee, last
September.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York University Medical Center was renamed
Tisch Hospital on Wednesday after Laurence A. Tisch, president of
CBS Inc., his brother, Preston Robert, and their families, who have
given $30 million to the facility, officials said.
   The family has contributed more than $45 million over the years
to New York University, which already has a Tisch School of the Arts
and a Tisch Hall at the College of Business and Administration.
   The hospital's name change was formalized Wednesday when a
temporary banner was draped across a canopy at the building's
entrance, the university said.
   ``We are so proud of how the university has emerged as one of the
great institutions in this country,'' said Laurence Tisch, 65,
president and chief executive officer of CBS Inc. and chairman of
Loews Corp.
   He graduated with honors from NYU at 18 and is chairman of the
university's board of trustees.
   Preston Tisch, 62, is president and co-chief executive officer of
Loews Corp. and is a former postmaster general.
   The latest Tisch gift will be used mainly to increase medical
researcher salaries so the university can compete for top scientific
talent, officials said.
</TEXT>
