<DOCNO> AP890125-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SenateBills     01-25 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Bills,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Bills Address Congressional Pay Raise, Poll Closing Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Congress Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate opened for business Wednesday, and
senators, like merchants at a bazaar, quickly lined up to offer a
dizzying array of legislative proposals.
   And like a bazaar, some of the offerings were shiny new, some
were somewhat shopworn and others were tired and battered and dulled
after years of legislative mauling.
   Among Wednesday's actions:
   _A bipartisan group of senators, opposed to a 50 percent
congressional pay raise, proposed legislation that would roll back
the increase if the House lets it become law by ducking a vote.
   The dozen sponsors, split evenly between Democrats and
Republicans, made clear they wanted to turn up the pressure on the
House _ which appears headed toward allowing the large increase to
become law automatically.
   Chief Senate sponsors Larry Pressler, R-S.D., and Charles E.
Grassley, R-Iowa, said the rollback provision of their bill would
keep the pressure on the House even if the pay raise becomes law
through House inaction.
   _A proposal for a uniform closing time for polls across the
country during presidential election years. The proposal, by Sens.
Brock Adams, D-Wash., and Donald Riegle, D-Mich., was designed to
eliminate television network projections of presidential races
before the polls are closed in Western states.
   _A bill from Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., that would provide
cost of living increases in compensation, rehabilitation, education
and training benefits paid to veterans who have service-connected
disabilities.
   _Legislation by Sens. William V. Roth, R-Del., and Wendell Ford,
D-Ky., that would put the federal budget on a two-year cycle instead
of the current yearly process.
   _A renewed effort from Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to raise
the nation's minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.55. The increase, which
would be the first in eight years, died in the closing days of the
100th Congress.
   _An ``ethics in government'' act proposed by Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., that was approved by the 100th Congress but vetoed by
President Reagan last November. The bill restricts former members of
Congress from lobbying the legislative branch and top executive
branch officials for 12 months after leaving government service.
   _A Republican campaign finance reform proposal that would, among
other things, restrict political action committees from giving more
than $1,000 to any one candidate, compared to $5,000 under present
law.
   _Another Republican bill, by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas, that would require a report from the president on what
foreign nations are aiding in the production of chemical weapons.
That bill would trigger sanctions against such companies,
prohibiting them from exporting goods into the United States.
   _Another Dole bill would gradually repeal the ``earnings test,''
which restricts the amount retirees under the age of 70 may earn
without losing a portion of their Social Security pension. The law
permits retirees under 65 to earn up to $6,480 a year without
penalty; those 65 to 69 may earn $8,880. For each additional dollar
earned, the beneficiary loses 50 cents of Social Security.
   _A proposal by Sen. Al Gore, D-Tenn., calling for an
``international alliance for environmental progress.'' The package
would include legislation designed to confront the so-called
greenhouse effect and promote global cooperation on environmental
issues.
   _An AIDS bill proposed by Cranston that would establish a grant
program to help communities develop coordinated systems of care to
people infected with the disease.
   _Also landing in the hopper was a bill to provide more than $1.7
billion to carry out programs contained in last fall's omnibus
narcotics law. Congress approved the drug bill last year but left
town without furnishing federal agencies with the funds to carry out
most of the programs.
   ``Congress is ready to work with the administration to stop the
scourge of drugs,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., in unveiling
the measure he is sponsoring with Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
and Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y. But he left uncertain exactly how
lawmakers would find the money and still remain within tight budget
constraints.
   _Gilman also vowed to reintroduce his 1988 bill to impose ``a
modest excise tax increase on beer, cigarettes and wine to raise
funding for our war on drugs.''
</TEXT>
