<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Cocaine     01-25 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Cocaine,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broken String Reveals Hidden Cocaine On Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A routine inspection of an Eastern Airlines jet
arriving from Colombia failed to reveal a cache of hidden cocaine,
but string holding the drug packets in place broke and the cocaine
dropped into view, authorities said Wednesday.
   Eastern employees spotted the hiding place on the L-1011
passenger jet Tuesday as it was moving from the international
terminal to the domestic departure area to continue its flight to
New York, the U.S. Customs Service said.
   Flight 50 from Cali landed at Miami International Airport just
before 4 p.m. and was routinely searched by Customs inspectors, who
found nothing, said Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   But the string holding the drug above a lavatory broke, and
packets fell through a ceiling panel, Customs agents said. A second
search revealed 47 pounds of cocaine above the lavatories and in two
exit doors.
   The placement seemed to indicate ``someone with extensive access
to the aircraft and extensive knowledge of its structure'' had
stored the drug, Customs said in a news release. No arrests were
made.
   The jet was released to Eastern, but the Customs Service is
investigating to determine if punitive measures will be taken
against the carrier.
</TEXT>
