<FIRST>r w AM-Fitzwater-Balloon     01-25 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fitzwater-Balloon,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rare public admission, White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday a news leak about a
bailout plan for the savings and loan industry was ``a trial
balloon'' floated by the administration to gauge reaction.
   But minutes later, Fitzwater made a speedy retreat, saying he had
been wrong.
   Fitzwater _ as well as President Bush and White House chief of
staff John Sununu _ were bombarded during the day with questions
after the Washington Post reported the administration was
considering imposing a fee on customers of savings and loan
institutions to help the federal government bail out the troubled
S&amp;L industry.
   After fielding numerous questions, Fitzwater finally told a
packed news briefing, ``What you're looking at today is a trial
balloon.''
   As laughter arose from the press, Fitzwater continued, ``And
we're willing to talk about it, willing to discuss it and we'll see
how it flies. But there will be other trial balloons and I trust
you'll all be here for those explanations, too.''
   When a reporter complimented him on his candor, Fitzwater
laughingly said, ``I wasn't sure it was a trial balloon till I had a
call at 6 a.m. this morning that said, `The story leaked last night
and the Secretary of the Treasury (Nicholas Brady) is on three
(television) talk shows this morning.'''
   ``That's a dead giveaway,'' the press secretary said.
   Shortly after his briefing, Fitzwater circulated through the
press room to change his story, saying he was ``back-pedaling on the
trial balloon.''
   He said he was wrong in suggesting Brady went on television to
sell the savings and loan plan. Instead, he said, Brady had
consented to the interviews to talk about leveraged buyouts, and was
hit with questions about S&amp;L plan in the wake of the Post story.
   ``It was not an intentional trial-balloon,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
