<HEAD>Ex-President's First Formal Post-White House Speech a Birthday Freebie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan is expected to command
more than $30,000 a speech on the lecture circuit, but his first
formal post-White House engagement will be a 78th birthday freebie.
   Reagan will address students at the University of Southern
California on Feb. 6, his birthday, and discuss his future, the
university announced. Free seats to the address will be allocated by
lottery.
   ``Mr. Reagan is looking forward to speaking with students and
revealing what he plans to do in the near future,'' Reagan spokesman
Mark Weinberg said Wednesday.
   Reagan hasn't disclosed his post-White House plans other than to
say he will be on the lecture circuit, pushing for conservatism. A
book deal for his memoirs was announced in New York on Wednesday,
and he is expected to sit on boards of several corporations.
   Reagan, as California governor, spoke at USC in 1977, and he was
president when he addressed students again in 1984. Then-Vice
President George Bush also addressed Southern Cal students that year.
