<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Flag     01-25 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Flag,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Flag Goes To Florida Veterans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Vietnam veterans on Wednesday
received a POW-MIA flag flown aboard last month's space shuttle
mission from Atlantis commander Robert L. ``Hoot'' Gibson.
   ``We were by far the most ideal crew, I'm sure, to be carrying
something like this,'' Gibson told about 20 camouflage-clad veterans
who gathered with their families for the presentation at Kennedy
Space Center.
   Members of Veterans of Vietnam War Post FL-3 in Crystal River
asked NASA to stow the black-and-white flag aboard the shuttle when
they realized Atlantis would be flown by an all-military crew, said
post commander Warren Stines.
   All the astronauts who flew the shuttle's secret mission in
December are military officers, and three of the five were fighter
pilots in southeast Asia during the Vietnam War. Gibson, a Navy
commander, was a ``topgun'' who flew combat missions from the U.S.S.
Coral Sea and the U.S.S. Enterprise.
   While the Atlantis astronauts were welcomed back from space with
parties and fanfare, Gibson said, Vietnam veterans ``faced a whole
lot different world.''
   ``When we all came back, there were no real celebrations, there
were no welcome homes,'' Gibson recalled. ``If we faced anyone, we
faced protesters and picketers.''
</TEXT>
