<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     01-25 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Aiming to Cut Role of Nuclear Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government wants substantial
cuts in the number of U.S. nuclear warheads in Europe as part of its
goal of reducing to an ``absolute minimum'' the role of the weapons
there, it was reported Wednesday.
   The ZDF network quoted from a position paper prepared by various
government ministries in Bonn and approved by the Federal Security
Council. It did not say when the document was approved.
   The government position still calls for ``effective'' nuclear
forces in Europe, despite the envisioned reductions, and views the
U.S. military presence as ``irreplaceable,'' according to ZDF.
   West Germany has been reassessing its stance on nuclear missiles
in hopes of improving ties with the Soviet Bloc. The missile issue
remains particularly sensitive in this country on the front lines of
the East-West conflict.
   For example, Defense Minister Rupert Scholz's statement earlier
this month that West Germany would agree to the replacement of 600
Lance short-range missiles sparked such a furor he later retracted
it.
   ZDF said that according to the document, ``the federal government
wants to cut the role of nuclear weapons to the `absolute minimum
necessary.'''
   ``The number of U.S. nuclear warheads stored in Europe should be
reduced unilaterally _ probably to less than 2,900 from the current
number of approximately 4,600,'' it quoted the document as saying.
   ``However, a necessary minimum needed for the credible deterrence
in Europe should be kept,'' ZDF said in reporting the government's
stance.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Lt. Col. Werner Widder said most of
the report already was public knowledge.
   However, Widder refused to confirm the federal government was
aiming to cut the number of U.S. nuclear warheads to less than 2,900.
   West Germans have applauded the removal of intermediate-range
nuclear missiles provided for in the treaty signed in December 1987
by the Soviet Union and United States.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher has been leading the
calls for further steps toward disarmament and for greater trust in
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   West German public opinion polls have shown a growing trust in
the Soviet bloc.
   A new survey presented by ZDF as part of its report Wednesday
said 88 percent of those polled do not feel militarily threatened by
Soviet bloc countries. It said only 10 percent were in favor of
replacing the aging Lance missiles pointed at East Germany and
Czechoslovakia.
   ZDF said the poll was conducted by an outside research institute
and surveyed 1,017 West German citizens. It did not provide a margin
of error.
</TEXT>
