<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Libya 2ndLd-Writethru a0529 01-25 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Libya, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0529,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Search Companies Suspected In Libya Chemical Plant Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT to three firms and 12 homes
searched, sted 14 companies. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Voegele said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OFFENBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today searched the
offices of three West German companies and the homes of 12 people
suspected of helping Libya build a chemical weapons factory,
authorities said.
   A spokesman for the prosecutor's office in Offenburg, Hubertus
Voegele, said one of the firms was Imhausen-Chemie in Lahr, which is
suspected of playing a major role in building and equipping the
Libyan plant.
   Voegele said the searches were conducted ``on suspicion that
export laws had been violated.'' He declined to name the other firms
whose offices were searched, but added they were located throughout
the country.
   The U.S. government says the plant at Rabta, 60 miles south of
the Libyan capital of Tripoli, was built to make poison gas. Libya
says it will manufacture medicine.
   Bonn officials initially dismissed the U.S. allegations, but have
now launched a criminal investigation to determine if
Imhausen-Chemie and other companies illegally shipped arms,
hazardous substances or components that can be used to produce them.
   The affair has deeply embarassed the West German government.
   On Tuesday, news reports said an Imhausen-Chemie employee had
confirmed allegations the company played a key role in building the
Libyan plant.
   The weekly Stern magazine said Imhausen-Chemie and a
government-owned company were aware that blueprints that were
supposed to be shipped to Hong Kong to build a pharmaceuticals plant
had ended up in Libya.
   The ARD television network late Tuesday reported that Klaus Hess,
a technical draftsman with Imhausen-Chemie, ``is said to have given
evidence that Imhausen shipped parts and chemicals to Libya, and
further that Imhausen employees helped build the facility in Rabta.''
   ARD did not disclose the source of its information, but said the
details were confirmed by the prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe. The
television also did not say if the employees traveled to Libya to
work on the plant.
   Imhausen-Chemie has denied accusations it was involved in the
Rabta plant.
   This week's Stern said an official at Imhausen-Chemie told
investigators that officials at Imhausen and the government-owned
Salzgitter Industriebau knew shipments of Salzgitter blueprints
ended up in Libya instead of Hong Kong.
   The magazine did not name the official and it was not known
whether it was the same person identified in the ARD report.
   Salzgitter officials acknowledged last week that the firm had
done business with Imhausen-Chemie, but said it involved
construction of a pharmaceuticals plant in Hong Kong. Salzgitter
officials late Tuesday denied any involvement in the Rabta project.
   In its report, Stern also said it had been clear to experts
working for Salzgitter that the Libyan plant was not designed as a
small factory for pharmaceuticals but as a ``large chemical plant
for the production of highly poisonous substances.''
   The magazine reported last week that Salzgitter, which
manufactures steel products and industrial equipment, delivered
blueprints for the Libyan plant.
   Voegele has confirmed that an Imhausen-Chemie employee had been
questioned but declined to reveal what that person told
investigators.
   Last week, Stern said the Hong Kong project, called ``Pharma
150,'' was devised to disguise involvement by Imhausen-Chemie in
helping build the plant in Libya, which has the same name.
   The magazine said this week that Siemens, the giant West German
electrical firm, sold switching and measuring equipment for ``Pharma
150.''
   Siemens spokesman Horst Siebert said the company had delivered
equipment to Hong Kong and said it had not done anything wrong.
   Stern telexed its report Tuesday to other news organizations in
advance of Thursday's publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
