<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AgentOrange     01-25 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agent Orange Studied Criticized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government science panel has dismissed as
``seriously flawed'' a study that concluded Vietnam veterans
suffered post-war physical problems due to exposure to the herbicide
Agent Orange.
   A report sent Congress on Wednesday concluded that data in the
study conducted for the American Legion ``do not support the
conclusions drawn by the authors.''
   The American Legion study was reviewed for Congress by the Agent
Orange working group of the Department of Health and Human Service's
Domestic Policy Council.
   ``The study is seriously flawed due to major problems in study
design and execution,'' the panel said in a memo written by its
chairman, Dr. Vernon N. Houk, director of the Center for
Environmental Health and Injury Control.
   The study, released last November, contradicted other studies by
the Veterans Administration and the federal Centers for Disease
Control. Their studies have found no significant health differences
among veterans of the Vietnam era, regardless of whether they
actually served in Southeast Asia.
   The Legion's study said there were ``significant dose-related
relationships between skin exposure to herbicides and subsequent
development of skin conditions such as rash with blisters and change
in skin color.'' It also connected Agent Orange exposure to benign
fatty tumors and risk for miscarriage among wives of von to Vietnam veterans
based on exposure to
Agent Orange.
</TEXT>
