<FIRST>r a AM-Westinghouse-Carlucci     01-25 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Westinghouse-Carlucci,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Defense Secretary Joins Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp., a major defense
contractor, said it elected former Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci to its board of directors Wednesday.
   About 20 percent of the company's annual sales of nearly $11
billion come from business with the Pentagon.
   Carlucci, 58, departed government service Friday with the
inauguration of George Bush and immediately became vice chairman of
the Carlyle Group, Washington-based takeover specialists whose
takeover bid was rejected last week by the space and defense
contractor Fairchild Industries.
   He also was vice chairman beginning in January 1983 and chairman
beginning in October 1984 at Sears World Trade Inc., an
international trading arm that the giant retailer Sears formed and
later shut down.
   Carlucci became defense secretary under President Reagan in
November 1987.
   ``We are extremely pleased to have a distinguished executive of
Mr. Carlucci's stature join the Westinghouse board,'' said Chairman
John C. Marous.
   Westinghouse set defense sales and profit records in 1987 with
the help of $3 billion in sales of radar for the F-16 fighter plane,
the largest single defense contract in the company's history.
   The Pittsburgh company also provides a variety of other types of
military radar, electronic countermeasures equipment, torpedoes,
naval propulsion systems and electricity generators.
</TEXT>
