<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0682,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Executes 16 Drug Smugglers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS one graf of background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen drug smugglers were hanged in Iran
on Wednesday, following a major anti-narcotics crackdown backed by a
draconian new law, Tehran radio reported.
   Ten key members of a large, armed gang were hanged in Tehran, two
smugglers were executed in neighboring Varamin, and four in western
Bakhtaran province said the broadcast, monitored in Nicosia.
   These deaths raised to 89 the number of drug smugglers executed
since the crackdown started Jan. 16. More than 1,000 people have
been arrested in the same period in what Iranian newspapers describe
as ``the biggest crackdown on drug smuggling in Iranian history.''
   The new anti-narcotics law, which went into effect Saturday,
carries the death penalty for possession of just over an ounce of
heroin and for 11 pounds of opium or hashish.
   The broadcast said those executed were responsible for smuggling
more than 17,380 pounds of opium, 237 pounds of heroin and 1,531
pounds of morphine.
   Police also seized weapons, ammunition and vehicles found in the
smugglers' hideouts.
   The broadcast did not say whether the smugglers brought drugs
into or out of Iran. Iranian smugglers often are involved both in
importing drugs from Pakistan and Afghanistan and exporting drugs
through Turkey and Persian Gulf countries.
</TEXT>
