<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Law-Glossary     01-25 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Law-Glossary,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defining Some Terms in British Courts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Law, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some terms used in British courts:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Barrister _ A lawyer who has been ``called to the bar,'' or
admitted to the Inns of Court. Barristers advise on legal problems
submitted through a solicitor, and present a case in the higher
courts. Barristers appear in court in wig and gown, and only
barristers may become judges.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Inns of Court _ four societies to which all barristers and senior
judges belong. The four are Lincoln's Inn, Inner Temple, Middle
Temple and Gray's Inn, reflecting legal practice dating at least to
the 14th century. The buildings now are largely used as offices
although some people are resident. The Inns are governed by judges
and senior barristers, who are known as ``benchers,'' and they
decide who will be admitted as students or called to the bar.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Lord Chancellor _ the top legal official in England and Wales.
The lord chancellor and the lords of appeal in ordinary, the
so-called ``law lords'' in Parliament, comprise the utlimate court
of appeal.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Solicitor _ A person trained in law who advises clients, draws up
legal documents and acts in many court cases. Solicitors handle
routine business such as home sales and wills. In court, solicitors
do not wear wigs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
