<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeathRow     01-25 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Death Row,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condemned Inmates Testify In Lawsuit About Death Row Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confining the 250 men on death row to
their cells creates dangerous suspicions among them, a convicted
murderer testified Wednesday as a hearing on a federal lawsuit
convened in San Quentin prison.
   Lead-off witness Rodney Alcala, convicted of kidnapping and
murdering a 12-year-old girl, called for allowing the prisoners to
mingle on tiers outside the cells, so ``you know what everybody's
attitude is, what's going on in everybody's head.''
   ``It's like if you live in a neighborhood and there's one guy who
never comes out of his house, you don't know what the guy's going to
do. ... That's pretty important in our situation.''
   The men awaiting possible execution in the San Quentin gas
chamber were called to testify in a lawsuit that claims state prison
officials are violating a 1980 court order on their housing and
treatment in an isolated wing of the institution.
   Among other things, the lawsuit contends the inmates are not
given adequate access to the prison law library, are improperly
prohibited from leaving their cells in the daytime, and are denied
some of the exercise equipment and personal items guaranteed by the
court order.
   The state agreed to abide by the order in 1980, but officials say
it has become obsolete and should be relaxed or repealed.
   State officials say the growth in death row population from 40 in
1980 to the current 250 has increased the cost and security risk of
complying with some provisions. They also say U.S. Supreme Court
rulings since 1980, broadening prison officials' leeway to determine
prison conditions, have made it clear that conditions at San Quentin
comply with the Constitution.
   The 1980 order is ``at best irrelevant to the dictates of the
law, and at worst a dangerous and extravagant interference with
professional prison management,'' Deputy Attorney General John
Donhoff said in court papers.
   Lawyers for the prisoners say the state has no legal reason for
violating the order, only a political motive to avoid appearing soft
on convicted killers.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Weigel, who signed the 1980 order,
assigned the hearing to his former law clerk, attorney Robert Riggs,
who acts as a monitor of the state's compliance with Weigel's orders
in several lawsuits over conditions at state prisons.
   Riggs, in a report filed before the hearing started last week,
found apparent violations of various provisions, including
requirements to furnish an adequate law library, allow condemned
prisoners out of their cells for meals and other activities during
the daytime, and provide a covered exercise yard.
   He ordered the state to show why it should not be held in
contempt of court for violating Weigel's order.
   The hearing began in San Francisco federal court last week and
was shifted across the bay to San Quentin for the inmates' testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
