<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     01-25 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostages No Longer Political Issue, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued captivity of 15 Western hostages
held mainly by pro-Iranian factions in Lebanon has lost its
political usefulness, the An-Nahar daily reported Wednesday.
   ``A diplomatic source says that the foreign hostages' issue has
lost its political importance and is being dealt with at the
humanitarian and financial levels,'' the respected daily said.
   The one-paragraph report did not elaborate.
   Nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a
Belgian are missing in Lebanon.
   American journalist Terry Anderson, 42, Chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, is the longest-held of the
captives. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   An-Nahar has been cautious in its hostage reporting and has not
made unfulfilled predictions or reported developments which later
turned out to be false.
   Iran has been trying to improve political and trade ties with the
West since last summer, when it agreed to a cease-fire in its
eight-year war with Iraq.
</TEXT>
