<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0698 01-25 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0698,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Experts Huddle, Planning Strategy for Joint Session</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, This time ..., to CORRECT to seven the number
of independent members attending meeting. Inserts new 10th graf, By midday
..., to UPDATE with closing prices. SUBS 15th graf pvs, The non-OPEC ...,
to ADD the Soviet Union and Yemen to list of observers. Subroto, one name,
is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from OPEC and independent oil-producing
nations huddled separately Wednesday to plot strategy for Thursday's
joint meeting over cooperation in supporting crude oil prices.
   Afterward, the independent group indicated support for OPEC's
attempt to limit production and stated both producer and consumer
nations would be served by stabilizing prices.
   A senior OPEC source said separately that he was hopeful the
cartel could reach agreement for output cuts by the independent
producers, but said that wasn't likely to happen immediately.
   ``Our unity is stronger now. Prices have strengthened and we are
ready'' for a cooperative agreement, said the senior OPEC source,
who requested anonymity.
   ``This is the first step in a step-by-step move'' to push up oil
prices, he said.
   A similar joint meeting was held last April, when six non-OPEC
producers met with representatives of the 13-member Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries and suggested they jointly cut their
exports by 5 percent. OPEC rejected that proposal.
   This time, some of the seven attending non-OPEC producers might
offer to cut their collective production by 5 percent, without
asking for reciprocal cuts from OPEC, non-OPEC sources have said
this week.
   The independents likely will want OPEC reassurance that the
cartel would not increase its own production if they went ahead with
their cuts.
   The spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely-traded
international crude oil, was $16.55 a barrel late Wednesday in
London, up 54 cents from late Tuesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate jumped 58 cents Wednesday to settle at $18.12 a
barrel, after closing 21 cents higher on Tuesday.
   OPEC experts from Algeria, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Indonesia,
Venezuela and Nigeria met for several hours Wednesday at the
Indonesian Embassy.
   At a brief news conference after the meeting, OPEC director
general Subroto described the gathering as a preparatory meeting of
cartel technicians.
   He said technicians for OPEC and the non-OPEC nations would meet
Thursday morning to exchange information ``and we will see the
market together and then what we can do together.''
   The groups planned to issue a joint statement afterward, Subroto
said.
   The non-OPEC group issued a communique afterward saying that
representatives of Angola, China, Colombia, Egypt, Malaysia, Mexico,
and Oman met with observers from the Soviet Union, Norway, the Yemen
Arab Republic and the Canadian province of Alberta and the U.S.
states of Alaska and Texas.
   ``The delegates unanimously share the desire to see the oil
market stabilize, an issue they consider of importance to both
consumers and producers of oil,'' the communique read. ``This shared
responsibility was perceived in spite of the variety of outlooks
represented at the meeting.''
   ``The delegates were satisfied that the OPEC conference held in
Vienna last November had produced very positive results and they
expressed the hope that those efforts would be sustained throughout
the first half of 1989,'' the communique read.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
