<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TradeViolation     01-25 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Violation,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Asks Congress to End Trade Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration asked Congress on
Wednesday to change U.S. trade rules that international panels say
violate an agreement with other trading countries.
   ``If we want other nations to eliminate... illegal trade barriers
when we win before a panel, we must be equally prepared to change
our actions and policies when we lose,'' said Judith H. Bello,
general counsel to the U.S. Trade Representative.
   She was testifying before the House Ways and Means Committee's
subcommittee on international trade.
   ``We must show we're not a scofflaw,'' Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla.,
agreed. He is chairman of the subcommittee and a major force in
trade policy.
   The accord is the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT),
which has nearly 100 governments as members. The GATT organization
sponsors the ``Uruguay round'' negotiations in which the U.S.
government has been trying unsuccessfully for a long-term agreement
on ending subsidies to farmers. These subsidies cost consumers and
taxpayers tens of billions of dollars a year.
   Ms. Bello said the rules she wants changed are more important
than they seem because there are widespread doubts among other
negotiators about U.S. intentions.
   At issue in Tuesday's hearing was a tax on imports of petroleum
and some petroleum products passed by Congress in 1986 to help
finance a ``superfund'' for cleaning up toxic waste. The tax on
imported products was 11.7 cents a barrel, 3.5 cents more than the
tax on U.S. production of the same items.
   In June 1987, an international panel ruled that the difference
was a discrimination against other countries and a violation of
GATT. Other governments threatened to retaliate against the United
States. To avoid that, the Reagan administration offered to
negotiate compensation with the countries affected. There have been
talks with Canada, Mexico and the 12 countries represented by the
European Economic Community, but no conclusion has been reached.
   The community estimates that the tax costs its member countries
$26.6 million a year. Ms. Bello said it would be preferable to get
rid of the differential.
   Also at issue is a ``user fee'' for work done by the U.S. Customs
Service, based on the value of products imported. Another
international panel ruled that also was a violation of the accord,
which says such fees should be based on actual cost to the Customs
Service.
   According to Ella Krucoff, press officer for the European
Community in Washington, its members paid $22.2 million in such fees
in 1987.
   ``The U.S. fee must be revised to tie it more closely to the
actual cost of processing particular entries,'' Ms. Bello said.
   The program brought in $787 million last year, according to Harry
W. Carnes, director of the U.S. Customs Service User Fee Task Force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     01-25 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets To Buy More Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has been given the go-ahead to
buy more U.S. grain than had been previous specified, including more
quantities of wheat at subsidized prices, the Agriculture Department
announced Wednesday.
   In one action, the Soviets were told they can now buy up to 20
million metric tons of grain in the 1988-89 year, up from 16 million
tons specified earlier. Purchases already total more than 12 million
tons.
   The department also said the Soviets have bought another 150,000
tons of soybean meal, which has a potential current market value of
about $36 million.
   Under a long-term grain agreement, the Soviet Union was
originally limited to 12 million tons of U.S. grain a year, but that
was increased to 16 million tons on Dec. 23. The agreement had
expired last Sept. 30 but was later extended through Dec. 31, 1990.
   Officials said the increase for 1988-89 ``takes into account
recent public confirmation by Soviet authorities'' that the Soviet
Union's grain harvest last year was below expectations.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg also announced that
Moscow has been authorized an additional 2 million tons of wheat
that it can buy under the department's Export Enhancement Program,
or EEP.
   Earlier this week, for example, the department announced an EEP
wheat sale to the Soviet Union of 635,000 tons, or about 23.3
million bushels. The subsidies shaved $23.05 per ton off the regular
market price, or about 63 cents per bushel.
   A metric tons is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sales of wheat and corn now total more than 11.6 million tons for
delivery in the sixth year of the agreement which began last Oct. 1.
That includes about 10.2 million tons of corn and 1.4 million tons
of wheat. In addition, the Soviets have bought 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.28 million tons of soybean meal, and 500,000 tons of
grain sorghums.
   Under the agreement, each ton of soybeans or meal counts for two
tons of grain.
   Only wheat is approved for sale to the Soviet Union under the EEP
subsidy arrangement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
