<FIRST>r a AM-MiamiHomeless     01-25 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Homeless,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelter Opens To Homeless Staying At Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of the homeless people staying at a
baseball stadium are being moved into the first permanent shelter
funded by the city, an official said Wednesday.
   Bobby Maduro Miami Stadium was opened in mid-December to homeless
people, including newly arrived Central Americans. But the stadium
is the spring home of the Baltimore Orioles, whose representatives
have arrived to begin preparations for ticket sales starting Feb. 10.
   The city and Dade County agreed to split the $175,000 cost of
renovating Beckham Hall Annex, a former youth facility that has been
converted into a 150-bed dormitory for the homeless.
   Mark Coats, assistant to the city coordinator of homeless
projects, said the move would be completed by Thursday. The city had
hoped to move the homeless sooner, but work at the annex was slower
than expected.
   At its peak as a homeless shelter, the stadium housed 413 people
a night. The Central Americans were placed by late last week in
housing partly paid for with $20,000 in donations to the city and
$76,000 raised by Spanish-language stations. The Roman Catholic
archdiocese opened a 171-bed shelter, and about 150 beds already
have been filled.
   But 150 homeless Americans remained at the stadium, meaning the
annex probably would be full as soon as it opened, Coats said.
   Dade County's homeless number 8,700 in summer and 10,000 in
winter, estimates Brother Paul Johnson, who operates the Camillus
House shelter and soup kitchen for the Brothers of the Good Shepherd.
</TEXT>
