<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0708 01-25 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Defense Subpoenas Two House Members for Iran-Contra Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Adds 2 grafs at end with Walsh supporting motion to quash subpoenas
for presidential documents; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fired National Security Council aide Oliver
North subpoenaed former House Intelligence Committee Chairman Lee
Hamilton and Rep. David McCurdy for North's upcoming trial in the
Iran-Contra case, one of the congressmen confirmed Wednesday.
   Also, North has subpoenaed records from three House panels that
tried unsuccessfully during 1985-1986 to determine what action he
was taking on the Contras' behalf. A House reply that sought to
quash portions of the subpoenas complained that he sought ``the
broadest imaginable range'' of documents.
   At a court hearing, U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell said the
matter of subpoenaing two congressmen must be approached with ``some
degree of accommodation'' and that ``we're not going to pull them
off the floor'' of Congress to testify at North's trial.
   North attorney Barry Simon didn't identify the two congressmen.
However, McCurdy, an Okahoma Democrat and a member of the House
Intelligence Committee, confirmed in an interview that he and
Hamilton had been subpoenaed by North. Hamilton, D-Ind., chaired the
committee during 1985-86 and is no longer a member of the committee.
   A hearing is scheduled for Friday to hear all objections to
North's subpoenas, including those seeking testimony from former
President Reagan and President Bush.
   Two House staff members also have been subpoenaed by North, Simon
said, and congressional sources identified them as House
Intelligence Committee employees.
   The House filed a 22-page motion seeking to quash large portions
of North's request for documents from the House committees on
intelligence, foreign affairs and armed services. The filing said
the House ``stands ready'' to provide all documents which are
``material and relevant for the trial'' which is scheduled to begin
next Tuesday.
   Nort, according to the House filing, hopes to show that the
committees in 1985 and 1986 already knew about his efforts on behalf
of the Contras from other sources, making it irrelevant whether he
misled or told the truth in responding to questions about his
activities from Capitol Hill.
   The former NSC aide ``asserts that what North was allegedly
concealing in 1985-86 chiefly by false statements and document
alteration and destruction House committees knew from other
sources,'' said the House filing.
   North ``reasons that hence no crimes occurred, for what the House
knew, North could not conceal from it.''
   North's ``dragnet subpoena'' is ``based on an amazing theory that
failure'' to obstruct Congress ``is a defense to an obstruction
charge,'' the House filing concluded.
   North's House document subpoenas require ``surrender of the
broadest imaginable range of privileged documents,'' said the filing
by Steven Ross, counsel to the House clerk.
   North is seeking everything the House committees have regarding
providing support to the Contras by private benefactors, third
countries, John Singlaub, North's courier to the Contras Robert Owen
and co-defendant Richard Secord, who North enlisted to run the
resupply operation.
   North subpoenaed the whole set of records of the intelligence
panel's probe of the Contra resupply operation, which began after a
Contra resupply plane with American crewman Eugene Hasenfus aboard
was shot down in Nicaragua in October 1986.
   Ross also disclosed that North's attorneys at one point delivered
to House counsel a subpoena for the House as a whole, asking ``for
records from the files of every member.'' North's attorneys were
told that House counsel wasn't authorized to accept service of such
a subpoena.
   North issued two subpoenas Dec. 28, for the intelligence and
foreign affairs committees, and issued two more subpoenas on
Inauguration Day, to the armed services and foreign affairs panels,
the House disclosed in its court filing.
   Four of the 12 criminal charges remaining against North are that
in 1985 he concealed from Congress his alleged efforts on behalf of
the Contras to raise funds, arrange arms shipments or offer tactical
advice. Another count says he concealed similar information at an
August 1986 meeting in the White House Situation Room with members
and staff of the House intelligence committee. North is charged
additionally with obstructing Congress in November 1986 by altering,
destroying and concealing documents on the Iran arms shipments and
aid to the Contras.
   Meanwhile, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh, in a court filing,
supported the government's motion to quash North's subpoena issued
while Ronald Reagan was still president for any presidential
documents concerning the arms sales to Iran and support for the
Contras. Walsh also supported quashing a separate North subpoena to
the executive office's custodian of records seeking videotapes and
audio tapes of speeches by Reagan or then-Vice President George Bush
supporting the Contras and documents on post-trip briefings for
Reagan or Bush on the Contras.
   Walsh said North's subpoenas for presidential documents are an
attempt to ``delay the start of trial by requiring the Government to
provide massive, unnecessary pretrial discovery.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
