<FIRST>u w AM-Libyan-Siemens 1stLd-Writethru a0730 01-25 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libyan-Siemens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0730,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Siemens Connections to Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 2nd graf to CORRECT to three firms and 12 homes searched,
sted 14 countries. Picks up 3rd graf bgng: Siemens has ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German investigators are exploring leads
that the giant Siemens technology firm assisted in the construction
of a chemical plant in Libya by providing electronic control
equipment and telephone gear, a U.S. government source said
Wednesday.
   The offices of three West German companies and the homes of 12
people suspected of assisting Libya in violation of export laws were
searched Wednesday, authorities in Offenburg said. Only one of the
firms, Imhausen-Chemie, was identified by a spokesman for the
prosecutor's office.
   Siemens has denied any wrongdoing.
   The U.S. government source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the control equipment apparently was shipped to Libya under an
expired license while 10 tons of telephone equipment was mislabeled
as being bound for the Hong Kong telephone exchange.
   He said some investigators believe Siemens' role in advancing the
plant project could grow larger as the probe proceeds.
   Siemens spokesman Horst Siebert said the Munich-based company had
delivered switching and measuring equipment for a project in Hong
Kong, but denied any wrongdoing or involvement with a Libyan
enterprise.
   The State Department spokesman, Charles E. Redman, said he had no
comment.
   The investigation now is centered mostly on Imhausen-Chemie and
its alleged role in constructing the plant at Rabta, some 60 miles
south of Tripoli, and also on Intec, another West German firm that
reportedly helped Libya convert transport planes into tankers to
refuel French-built jets in midair so they could reach Israel.
   The idea was to bring the Western Wall in Jerusalem, other Jewish
holy places in the capital, and Tel Aviv, the most populous city in
Israel, within range, the source said.
   Siemens and also Saltzgitter, a wholly state-owned company that
reportedly supplied plans for the plant, are getting increased
attention. Saltzgitter has denied its employees worked on the Rabta
factory.
   The West German government initially disputed findings by
separate U.S., British and Dutch investigations that linked West
German firms to the project, but subsequently acknowledged there was
compelling evidence to support the allegations.
   Officials in West Germany are conducting a criminal investigation
to determine if Imhausen-Chemie and other companies illegally
shipped arms, hazardous substances or components that can be used to
produce them. The affair has deeply embarrassed the West German
government.
   A former Imhausen-Chemie manager who had buried damaging
documents is cooperating with the investigators, said the source. He
described the ex-employee as a ``canary.''
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has denied the plant was designed
to produce chemical weapons and has offered to open it to
international inspection. Former Secretary of State George P.
Shultz, who led the U.S. campaign to deny Libya useful technology,
said before leaving office last week that the plant had not reached
the point of production _ and might not get there if Western firms
heeded U.S. warnings.
   Gadhafi contends the plant is designed to eventually produce
pharmaceuticals.
</TEXT>
