<FIRST>r a AM-MinutemanLaunch     01-25 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minuteman Launch,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Launches Unarmed Minuteman Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force launched
an unarmed Minuteman III missile Wednesday that successfully reached
its target in the Pacific Ocean 4,200 miles away, officials said.
   The missile blasted off at 5:57 a.m. and splashed down as planned
30 minutes later in the Kwajalein Missile Range in the Marshall
Islands, said Capt. Teresa V. Waddell.
   The launch was the 473rd Strategic Air Command test launch of a
Minuteman missile from this base 140 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   The window for the launch, or the time during which the Western
Test Range is secured and cleared of sea vessels and aircraft, began
at 5 a.m. The flight was delayed 27 minutes by ``minor unexpected
events,'' said Lt. Gary Morey of the Vandenberg-based 1st Strategic
Aerospace Command Division. He would not elaborate.
   Morey said the lift off was monitored on the ground by a crew
from Malmstrom Air Force Base in Montana, where the missile was
stationed before being transferred to Vandenberg.
   The launch was the first from Vandenberg since reports surfaced
two weeks ago that the flight recorder from a similar July 1987 test
involving a Minuteman II missile may have been recovered by the
Soviet Union.
   That missile was carrying a flight recorder for the U.S.
Department of Energy, which manufactures and tests this nation's
nuclear weapons. Although that recorder contained no classified
information, it could provide valuable information to an adversary,
said Chris Sankey, Energy Department spokesman.
   However, the Minuteman III carries no flight recorder and instead
radios down information to U.S. tracking stations while it flies,
said Tech. Sgt. Alan Dockery, speaking for SAC headquarters near
Omaha, Neb.
</TEXT>
