<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     01-25 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0571</SECOND>
<UNK>New Effort to End Shiite Militia Fighting After Cease-Fire Broken</UNK>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's foreign minister is expected here
Thursday to try again with Syrian officials to stop a nine-month war
between the Shiite Moslem militias they sponsor in Lebanon.
   The Syrian-backed Amal and the fundamentalist Hezbollah,
supported by Iran, are fighting for supremacy among Lebanon's 1
million Shiites, the largest sect in the war-ravaged nation.
   More than 500 people have been killed and 1,500 wounded since
April. The latest round of battles has taken 172 lives since Dec.
31, and 337 people have been reported wounded.
   A truce was announced Wednesday morning under a ``preliminary''
peace agreement, but an hour-long battle broke the truce later in
the day.
   Iran said Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati would visit
Damascus on Thursday to make the deal final. He also was in the
Syrian capital Tuesday.
   Syria supported Iran in its eight-year war with Iraq, in which a
cease-fire was reached Aug. 20. But their interests compete in
Lebanon, where Syria stations about 40,000 troops and has been the
main power broker.
   Amal and Hezbollah, which means Party of God, reached the peace
agreement during three days of negotiations in Damascus mediated by
Syria and Iran.
   A Syrian Foreign Ministry statement issued Wednesday after
night-long negotiations said the rival militias agreed to end their
war in south Lebanon and the south Beirut slums, but a battle with
mortars and machine guns began later in south Lebanon.
   Police said five militiamen were wounded in the hour-long battle
in the shattered orchards of Iklim el-Tuffah, or Apple province,
which was a land of abundance before Lebanon's sectarian civil war
began in 1975.
   Several earlier Amal-Hezbollah truces also have failed.
   Elsewhere in south Lebanon, the Israeli army and allied
militiamen expelled 40 Lebanese men, women and children from its
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' just north of the border, police
reported.
   They said the expulsion from the Sunni Moslem village of Shibaa
inside the zone occurred after inhabitants refused to cooperate with
an Israeli-sponsored local administration. A police spokesman said
130 soldiers and militiamen, with 20 armored personnel carriers,
surrounded Shibaa during the night.
   U.N. spokesman Timur Goksel said two 155mm howitzer shells landed
at the U.N. peacekeeping force headquarters in the border town of
Naqoura but did not explode.
   He told reporters they were fired from around Marjayoun,
headquarters of the South Lebanon Army, the Israeli-backed militia
that operates in the security zone.
   According to the Syrian statement, the peace agreement between
Amal and Hezbollah provided for an immediate cease-fire and an end
to hostile propaganda campaigns by both sides.
   It said the militias would continue negotiations for a
``comprehensive reconciliation agreement.''
   Syrianofficials would not comment on the cease-fire violation.
   Velayati, the Iranian foreign minister, met in Damascus on
Tuesday with President Hafez Assad, Foreign Minster Farouk
al-Sharaa, Amal leader Nabih Berri and Hussein Musavi, leader of
Hezbollah.
   Hezbollah seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon, but the more secular and nationalist Amal wants government
in which Moslems would share power equally with the once-dominant
Christians.
   Hezbollah advocates guerrilla attacks on Israel, but Amal seeks
only to get the Israelis out of the border zone. It opposes
cross-border raids because they provoke retaliation against the
predominantly Shiite population of south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
