<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearReactor     01-25 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Reactor,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Blames Reactor Accident on Poor Supervision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accident that caused several valves to
rupture at a nuclear reactor in South Carolina resulted in part from
poor supervision and a neglect of safety procedures, Energy
Department officials said Wednesday.
   Troy Wade, acting assistant secretary for defense programs, told
a Senate hearing the accident was disturbingly similar to an
incident last August in which operators of another reactor at the
Savannah River Plant bypassed standard procedures in attempting to
restart the reactor, causing a dangerous power surge.
   ``It does have some unfortunate parallels to the August incident
when you talk about operator attitude,'' Wade told the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee.
   Department officials at Savannah River said Wednesday it was too
early to say whether the accident Sunday would delay a planned
restart of the three-reactor complex. Savannah River is the nation's
only source of tritium, a perishable gas vital to the production of
nuclear warheads.
   The complex has produced no tritium since last spring, due to
technical and safety problems. Department officials have said they
hope to have the reactors running again by the end of 1989, although
no firm target date has been set.
   Gary Pitchford, a department spokesman at Savannah River, said
all testing, maintenance and other operations at the K reactor were
halted after the accident and would remain on hold at least for a
few more days. He said investigators would make a detailed
assessment of the damage.
   Pitchford said preliminary indications were that this shutdown of
reactor operations ``will not have any significant impact'' on the
timetable for restarting the K reactor.
   The Pentagon has said production of tritium must be resumed
before the end of the year to avoid a weakening of the nation's
nuclear weapons program. It has not said exactly when the tritium
supply would reach a critical level.
   Pitchford said it appeared it would take ``a few weeks'' to
complete the investigation of Sunday's accident.
   Department officials said the reactor operators were performing a
test involving running water through the reactor's backup cooling
system and monitoring the pressure in pipes. Operators were unaware
that a valve had been left open after a similar test last week, and
pressure did not rise to expected levels.
   In what Pitchford called a violation of standard procedures, the
operators started another pump, causing pressure inside the pipes to
rise suddenly. The valve that had been left open then slammed shut,
causing a surge of pressure that damaged other valves.
   Wade recalled that after the August incident, an extra reactor
crew was added at Savannah River so that one full complement could
always be in training. ``That hasn't helped'' improve safety
procedures ``as we thought it would,'' he said.
   He added that if the damage from Sunday's accident turns out to
be ``the worst case,'' it will have some effect on plans for
restarting the reactor.
   ``We will not restart until we are satisfied with worker training
and worker attitude,'' he said.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, who has led congressional inquiries into
problems at the nuclear weapons complex, told Wade the latest
incident seemed to indicate that procedures to assure safety at
Savannah River had not improved since last summer.
   Meanwhile, governors from states with nuclear weapons plants
urged President Bush on Wednesday to commit more money to cleaning
up radioactive and chemical pollution at government-owned bomb
factories.
   ``As the governors of the states most affected, we implore you to
take the initiative in working with Congress to establish cleanup as
a national imperative,'' said a letter from Govs. Richard Celeste of
Ohio, Booth Gardner of Washington, Roy Romer of Colorado, Cecil
Andrus of Idaho, Ned Ray McWherter of Tennessee and Bob Miller of
Nevada.
   ``As an urgent critical first step in this process we urge you to
include substantially increased funding for waste cleanup and
disposal work at (Energy Department) facilities in your fiscal year
1990 budget proposal,'' said the letter, delivered to the White
House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
