<DOCNO> AP890125-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     01-25 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Accelerator Technology Not `Mature' Enough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy has concluded that
linear accelerator technology is not ``mature'' enough that
accelerators rather than nuclear reactors can be used to produce a
key ingredient for atomic weapons, a top department official said
Wednesday.
   ``It is a giant step from where we are today to the kind of
accelerator and size of accelerator we would need,'' Troy Wade, the
department's acting assistant secretary for defense programs, told
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
   Scientists at the Los Alamos and Brookhaven national laboratories
and the Westinghouse-Hanford Co. in Washington state have written
that an accelerator could produce tritium more cheaply, quickly and
safely than a nuclear reactor.
   Some of the scientists also believe that an accelerator could be
used to change highly radioactive waste into less hazardous
substances.
   Last July, the department recommended construction of two new
nuclear reactors to produce tritium, one at the Savannah River
complex in South Carolina, and the other at the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory in Idaho Falls.
   The reactors, which would cost an estimated $6.8 billion and take
at least 10 years to finish, would replace the aging
tritium-producing reactors at Savannah River. The existing Savannah
River reactors have been plagued by safety problems and are
currently shut down.
   ``We have looked at accelerator technology,'' Wade told the
committee. ``It is not mature technology. We would continue to
pursue the accelerator technology, but at the moment it is not as
mature as fission reactors.''
   The department provided $300,000 in funding for the initial
accelerator research, but no money was provided to continue the
research in the current fiscal year.
   Also on Wednesday, an aide to Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., said the
senator may ask the General Accounting Office to review the
accelerator proposal.
   An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic
particles are whipped at high speeds until they crash into a target,
in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision
produces tritium, a radioactive gas used in nuclear weapons.
   The accelerator would take massive amounts of electricity to
operate, roughly the output of an entire nuclear power plant. The
scientists who have studied the accelerator have suggested the
Hanford nuclear reservation in Washington state as one possible site.
   The Pacific Northwest has the cheapest electric rates in the
nation and the Bonneville Power Administration has indicated it
would have enough electricity available in the 1990s to power an
accelerator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Dali     01-25 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dali,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Artist Gets Surrealistic Sendoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD LORANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FIGUERAS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvador Dali was buried on Wednesday
inside a museum filled with his surrealistic artwork next to a
shower-equipped Cadillac and a painting of a woman's torso.
   Thousands watched as four workers wearing Dali-designed uniforms
carried his coffin through the arched door of the Theater-Museum
Dali, a converted municipal theater where the artist, then 14, held
his first exhibition 71 years ago.
   Dali was eulogized earlier Wednesday in the Sant Pere Roman
Catholic parish church, then carried across a square bearing his
name to the museum he founded in the city where he was born.
   After weaving past Dali's ``Rainy Taxi'' _ a 1938 Cadillac with a
coin-operated interior shower system _ pallbearers helped lower the
black lacquered coffin into a marble-lined hole that was covered
with a light gray slab of stone.
   A giant painting of a woman's nude torso with an image on its
stomach of a gaping doorway topped by an olive tree looked down from
the wall behind the coffin.
   On one side was a white plaster group sculpture of an orchestra
and on was ``Lincoln in Dali Vision,'' a giant painting of Dali's
late wife, Gala, that turns into a portrait of Abraham Lincoln when
viewed from a distance.
   The funeral service and burial were broadcast live on Spanish
national television.
   ``Since he was an infant, he searched for beauty,'' Rev. Narciso
Costabella said of Dali. ``Salvador, now that you have found
authentic beauty in which you can revel forever, we wish you perfect
rest and peace.''
   Police said more than 20,000 people visited the Dali's Galatea
Tower residence, where his body lay in state for 31 hours.
   The painter died in Figueras on Monday, leaving an estate
estimated at $87.7 million by some accounts.
   Dali's will reportedly divides his estate among the governments
of Figueras, Catalonia and Spain. Under Spanish law, it cannot be
read until 15 days after his death.
   Funeral mourners included one of Dali's few living relatives, his
cousin Montserrat Dali, who sat in the front row along with longtime
Dali collaborators, including painter Antoni Pitxot, French
archivist and Dali's principal merchant Robert Descharnes and
attorney Miguel Domenech.
   Across the aisle sat Spanish Culture Minister Jorge Semprun,
Catalonian regional government president Jordi Pujol and Figueras
Mayor Mariano Lorca.
   The owners of the Dali Museum in St. Petersburg, Fla., A.
Reynolds and Eleanor Morse and Italian collector Giuseppe Alboretto
also attended the funeral.
   His death has left a dispute over the reproduction rights to his
artwork.
   Morse, who owns the largest private Dali collection outside
Spain, said earlier he would not discuss legal issues until after
the mourning period.
   ``I'm here because of a 45-year-old friendship, to pay my
respects to a dear friend and that's all,'' he said.
   Alboretto, who owns more than 500 Dali works, said he had
prepared legal action against Decharnes, who administers Demart Pro
Arte, an Amsterdam-based company that has reproduction rights for
Dali's work through 2004.
   A founder of the surrealist movement in the 1930s, Dali was the
last of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that included
Pablo Picasso and Joan Miro.
   After living in Madrid, Paris and the United States, Dali
returned for good to Catalonia in 1948.
   In later years he was known as much for his outrageous
personality and theatrical interviews as for his paintings.
   He went into seclusion after his wife, manager and muse Gala died
in 1982.
   He had a history of heart problems and had been confined to a
wheelchair and fed through a tube since he suffered burns in a 1984
fire.
   Dali was admitted to Figueras Hospital on Monday because of
severe heart trouble aggravated by pneumonia. It was his third trip
to the hospital since late November.
</TEXT>
