<FIRST>u i AM-PLO-US     01-25 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-US,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says US Can Bring Peace, Bush Should Act Fast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat urged the Bush
administration Wednesday to move quickly in its Middle East peace
efforts and persuade Israel to take part in peace talks.
   ``We hope the new U.S. administration will contribute in
pressuring Israel to bow to the voice of peace,'' Arafat said,
appealing for worldwide backing for his peace initiative.
   Arafat wants the Palestine Liberation Organization to have equal
footing with Israel in peace negotiations, a demand Israel has
refused.
   ``The present year is important for such an American decision
after George Bush has taken over the presidency, and before
Washington is taken up with other international issues,'' he said.
   Arafat was addressing a news conference in Muscat before leaving
after a three-day visit, his first ever to Oman. He has been
enlisting the efforts of Sultan Qaboos in his quest for wide-scale
diplomatic backing for the peace initiative.
   ``Peace is not up to Israel but up to the United States. The
Israel decision lies in Washington and not in Tel Aviv,'' Arafat
said in other interviews while in Oman.
   ``The question now is whether the international community will
force Israel to respond to peace or not,'' Arafat said. ``Will the
world leave the powder keg in the Middle East aflame because of
Israeli intransigeance?''
   More than 360 Palestinians have died in the 13-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel
seized from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. Fifteen
Israelis have also been killed.
   Arafat renewed a proposal to place the occupied territories under
U.N. trusteeship for ``a transitional period of a few months''
during which the Palestinian inhabitants would exercise their right
to self-determination.
   In Palestinian language this means a referendum in which these
inhabitants would decide whether to be an independent state, or to
confederate with Jordan.
   Bush, in a pre-inauguration interview, recommended confederation
as the basis for a Palestinian settlement.
   The Bush administration is about to resume formal sessions of the
dialogue with the PLO that the Reagan administration initiated in
December after Arafat explicitly recognized Israel and renounced
terrorism.
   Abu Dhabi's state-run newspaper Al-Ittihad referred to an
informal meeting in Tunis on Monday between PLO Executive Committee
member Farouk Kaddoumi and U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau Jr.
   It said Kaddoumi pressed for Washington to reopen the PLO
information office in the American capital, closed after
congressional charges of terrorism by the guerrilla organization.
   Mahmoud Abbas, a PLO executive committee member, said the
movement will insist that Washington clearly define what it
considers Palestinian rights when PLO-U.S. talks resume.
   ``So far, we have had only one meeting with the Americans with
only one topic in the agenda, terrorism. We have not discussed
anything related to Palestinian leaders or institutions,'' he said
in a lecture Tuesday night in Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates.
   Abbas also scotched reports the United States demanded the PLO
disband guerrilla groups and expel PLO figures Washington considers
terrorists.
</TEXT>
