<FIRST>r p AM-Dorgan-Detectives     01-25 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dorgan-Detectives,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Close Books on Dorgan Shadow Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators said they cannot
determine whether politics was behind private detectives who
shadowed Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., in 1986 and have closed the
books on the case, according to documents released Wednesday.
   The Federal Election Commission's general counsel said it can't
sort out whether the detectives were hired to influence the 1986
election or were only looking into the lobbying activities of
Dorgan's wife, Kimberly, who represented Canadian timber interests.
   Dorgan alleged that the detectives were trying to dig up
information for a Washington lawyer, Bert Rand, who is a friend of
former Sen. Mark Andrews, R-N.D. At the time, Andrews viewed Dorgan
as a potential rival in his race for re-election to the Senate.
   Dorgan said he was disappointed but not surprised at the
commission's decision to drop the case.
   ``Even a blind hog can find an acorn now and then, but the FEC
has been consistently unwilling to investigate these things,''
Dorgan said. ``The Federal Election Commission is a political body
which seems to have a political antenna in these cases which is
always out.''
   Andrews, who denied any involvement in the matter, said the
commission's decision was a vindication, although he acknowledged
that political fallout from the incident probably contributed to his
losing the election.
   ``The original complaint against our campaign committee was
politically motivated and totally without substance,'' Andrews said.
   That complaint was filed one week before the 1986 election by
Dorgan and Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., who went on to win a narrow
victory over Andrews.
   The complaint originally was against Andrews' re-election
committee, the state Republican Party, the private detective agency
and a handful of lawyers.
   The commission decided to drop the investigation last fall, but
that decision and the case record remained sealed until Wednesday.
However, the central issue remained unresolved.
   ``There is conflicting evidence as to whether the activity in
question was undertaken for the purpose of influencing a federal
election,'' the commission's general counsel wrote.
   Rand, who told the commission he was working on behalf of Wendell
Wyatt, a former Republican congressman from Oregon, hired two other
lawyers, one of whom hired a Bismarck, N.D., private detective
agency to gather information on Dorgan.
</TEXT>
