<FIRST>r w AM-PentagonProbe     01-25 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Probe,410</SECOND>
<NOTE>Air Force Starts Action Against Cohen</NOTE>
<NOTE>By NORMAN BLACK</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Military Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Wednesday it had begun legal
proceedings to suspend a top contracting official who has been
implicated in the Pentagon fraud investigation.
   The service said Dr. Victor D. Cohen, the deputy for tactical
systems in the office of the assistant secretary for acquisition,
had been served on Tuesday with a ``Notice of Proposed Indefinite
Suspension.''
   Cohen has seven days to contest the Air Force personnel action.
   ``This action is based primarily on an FBI affidavit which became
available to the Air Force on Dec. 28,'' the service said in a
prepared statement.
   ``The action is based on a reasonable cause to believe that he
has committed a crime for which a sentence of imprisonment can be
imposed.''
   If an indefinite suspension is imposed, Cohen would be forced
into a non-pay status ``for an indefinite period of time, penking
resolution of the criminal process.''
   Cohen is currently suspended from his job but is drawing pay.
   Cohen, unlike one Navy employee who was suspended earlier this
month, has not been indicted by the federal grand jury that is
conducting the investigation.
   Cohen was named in a government affadavit filed by prosecutors
investigating bribery and corruption in the Pentagon's
$150-billion-a-year procurement business.
   The affadavit, based on telephone taps, showed by Cohen used his
official position to help consultant William Galvin or his clients
in exchange for payments and other gratuities. Galvin has been
indicted by a federal grand jury in the Pentagon case.
   The affadavit that names Cohen cites an example of Cubic Corp.,
of San Diego, a client of Galvin's and a maker of shells that house
electronic gear, called pods.
   Sometime before April 1, Galvin asked Cohen to award an
unidentified pod contract to Cubic on a sole source basis so that
Cubic would be the only supplied, the ducment said.
   In a tapped phone conversation on May 15, 1987, Cohen told Galvin
that he wouldn't award the contract to Cubic as a sole source. But
he said he planned to have the Air Force issue the request for
proposal with a required delivery scheduled that Cubic's competitor
couldn't meet, the affidavit says.
   ``Cohen assured Galvin that by doing it this way, the procurement
would appear to have been completed when, in actuality, Cubic would
be guaranteed the award of the contract,'' the document said.
</TEXT>
