<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     01-25 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Chief: No Peacekeepers Allowed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Hun Sen of Cambodia on Wednesday
rejected proposals for an international peacekeeping force in his
country and asked other nations to stop supporting guerrillas
seeking to topple his government.
   Cambodian guerrillas, meanwhile, demanded that Vietnam come up
with a timetable for withdrawing its occupation forces from the
country.
   Hun Sen had a ``frank discussion'' with Thai Prime Minister
Chatichai Choonhavan and other Thai leaders on Wednesday, said Thai
government spokesman Suvit Yodmani.
   Yodmani stressed the two-hour talk did not constitute Thai
recognition of the Vietnam-backed government in Cambodia.
   Chatichai ``just wants to get to know Hun Sen because Hun Sen
later on most likely will be involved in a coalition government,
hopefully when there is peace'' in Cambodia, Suvit told reporters.
   He said both sides agreed that all warring Cambodian factions
must attend the second session of Cambodian peace talks scheduled
Feb. 19-21 in Indonesia.
   Participants in the first session in July included Vietnam, Laos,
the warring parties in Cambodia and the members of the non-communist
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   ``The conclusion is that up to now, anyway, (Cambodia) would like
Thailand to try to get the four sides together and to face one
another and talk frankly,'' said Suvit, referring to Hun Sen's
government and the three parties in the Cambodian resistance
coalition.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in 1978 and toppled the brutal regime of
the Khmer Rouge, who killed hundreds of thousands of people during
their three-year rule.
   Thailand has shunned the Phnom Penh government since then and has
backed the three-party guerrilla coalition fighting Vietnamese and
Cambodian government troops.
   Before meeting with Chatichai, Hun Sen told reporters that he
rjected an international peacekeeping force for Cambodia and also
opposed other parts of the peace proposal by guerrilla coalition
leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Hun Sen also reiterated calls for a cessation of all military aid
to Cambodian resistance groups opposed to his government.
   He said Sihanouk's proposals would lead to the return to power of
the Khmer Rouge, one of the parties in the guerrilla coalition.
   Hun Sen also said he was ready to discuss with the United States
the question of Americans missing in action in Cambodia from the
Vietnam war, saying the discussions could take place in Bangkok.
   The United States, which lists 83 Americans as missing in action
in Cambodia, also does not recognize the Hun Sen government.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw by 1990 but said it may pull
its forces from Cambodia by September if a political solution can be
achieved.
   In Beijing, China's official Xinhua news agency quoted Cambodian
guerrillas as demanding a specific timetable for a Vietnamese
withdrawal.
   Xinhua quoted the guerrillas' Radio Democratic Kampuchea as
saying Vietnam's withdrawal should take place under international
supervision.
   The guerrillas' main international sponsor, China, has made a
similar demand. East European sources said a timetable was discussed
during meetings last week in Beijing between Vietnamese Vice Foreign
Minister Dinh Nho Liem and Chinese officials.
   Vietnam's embassy in Beijing later said the two sides reached
some agreements, but did not say if those included an agreement on a
timetable. China earlier called Vietnam's statement that it could
pull out by September ``a step forward.''
</TEXT>
