<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Anderson     01-25 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Anderson,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Public Works Subcommittee Chairmen Trading Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Glenn Anderson, chairman of the House
Public Works Committee, is giving up the chairmanship of the panel's
surface transportation subcommittee after his colleagues objected to
his retaining both posts, Capitol Hill sources said Wednesday.
   As a result, a three-way swap of subcommittee chairmanships has
been worked out by lawmakers in which Anderson, D-Calif., would take
charge of the committee's weaker and less visible investigations and
oversight subcommittee.
   Rep. James L. Oberstar, D-Minn., who has chaired the
investigations panel, would instead head the committee's aviation
subcommittee. And Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., the current aviation
chairman, would chair surface transportation.
   Anderson, 75, became chairman after his predecessor, Rep. James
Howard, D-N.J., died after a heart attack last March. He has
remained relatively obscure in Congress despite a 20-year House
career, in contrast to the more colorful and outgoing Howard.
   According to three sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
Anderson wanted to continue as chairman of the full committee and
the surface subcommittee. But other panel members, citing a
long-standing committee tradition, argued that the committee
chairman should not also chair a subcommittee.
   The lawmakers' objections also reflected unhappiness by some of
the panel's younger members that subcommittee chairmanships are not
opening up for new people, the sources said.
   Anderson finally agreed to give up the surface panel, which
controls billions of dollars in highway and mass transit projects
and is the most sought-after subcommittee, in exchange for the
investigations chairmanship. The investigations subcommittee does
not initiate legislation, but it does conduct inquiries into various
subjects.
   The swaps are all subject to approval by the committee's 31
Democrats, who will vote on the jobs on Feb. 1.
   Mineta issued a statement Wednesday saying he would seek the
surface transportation job. Committee spokesman David Smallen, asked
about the three-way swap, said, ``I have no comment on that.''
</TEXT>
