<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Wright-Ethics     01-25 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Ethics,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stokes Blasts Conservative Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former chairman of the House Ethics Committee
has blasted as ``jury tampering'' the attempts by two conservative
groups to lobby a GOP member of the ethics panel in the case of
House Speaker Jim Wright.
   ``The brazen effort is closely akin to jury tampering in a court
of law,'' said Rep. Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, in a letter to House
colleagues. ``This clearly amounts to a flagrant politicization of a
process that was specifically created to be above partisan
politics.''
   The letter was evidence of growing partisan tensions as the
Ethics Committee nears the end of its seven-month probe of Wright
and the time when its 12 members _ six Democrats and six Republicans
_ must vote on the speaker's guilt or innocence.
   Wright is accused in a six-count resolution of abusing his office
for financial gain and improperly intervening with federal
regulators on behalf of constituents.
   The controversy began last month when a conservative newsletter
published a brief bit of speculation that the ethics panel would
ultimately avoid a 6-6 tie vote on the Wright case because committee
member Rep. Chip Pashayan, R-Calif., would side with the Democrats
to exonerate the speaker.
   In response, two groups _ the Conservative Campaign Fund and the
National Right to Work Committee _ launched an effort to lobby
Pashayan to be tough on Wright.
   Peter Flaherty, director of the Conservative Campaign Fund, said
he already had doubts about the independence of the investigation of
Wright by outside counsel Richard J. Phelan. After the newsletter
item appeared, his group sent 300 pieces of mail to contributors in
Pashayan's district urging them to contact their congressman and
urge him not to side with the Democrats.
   ``There is enough information on the public record to require
strong action'' against Wright, the group's letter argues. ``All of
the members of the committee are under pressure, both subtle and
overt,'' from the speaker, it states.
   At about the same time, the right-to-work group mailed letters to
1,500 of its supporters in Pashayan's district asking that the
lawmaker ``stand up to ... the awesome power of Speaker Wright.''
   Pashayan has received about 100 calls and letters from
constituents on the issue, but the flow of contacts has dwindled
this week, and the ethics panel member professed to be
``impervious'' to the lobbying effort. But he acknowledged that
tension over the Wright case has grown as it nears its conclusion.
   Phelan is in the process of drafting his final report, consulting
occasionally with committee members, and is expected to be ready to
present it to the panel for discussion and a vote sometime in
February.
   ``As the former chairman of that committee, I feel certain that
nothing of this kind has ever previously intruded in such a way upon
the committee's deliberations,'' Stokes wrote in his letter to all
House members.
   ``Republican members of the committee, the speaker himself, and
the House as an institution deserve far better than this shabby
attempt to undermine the integrity of our processes,'' Stokes wrote.
   Efforts to contract spokesmen for the groups for a response to
Stokes' letter were unsuccessful.
</TEXT>
