<FIRST>u p AM-Democrats 3rdLd-Writethru   01-25 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0754,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown `At the Threshold of Victory' for Democratic Chairmanship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 6 with two new grafs to update with Jones comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney Ronald Brown, who directed Jesse
Jackson's operations at the 1988 Democratic National Convention,
claimed victory Wednesday in the race for the party chairmanship
after he received the endorsement of his chief rival in the
four-candidate race.
   ``I am ending my campaign today and I am endorsing Ron,'' said
Rick Wiener, the Michigan Democratic Party chairman, widely regarded
as Brown's principal competitor.
   Brown immediately issued a statement thanking Wiener and saying,
``I now have more than enough votes to win the chairmanship of the
DNC.
   ``I am very, very pleased and look forward to leading a united
party for the next four years. My first priority is to reach out to
all Democrats. Our strength as a party depends on our ability to
appeal to Americans in every region with a message of strength and
hope.''
   Two other candidates _ former Reps. Jim Jones of Oklahoma and
James Stanton of Ohio _ remained in the race, but Brown and Wiener
were considered the two contenders with the largest blocs of support.
   Jones said his aides were calling Wiener supporters to see how
many would support the Oklahoman.
   ``I believe in making a decision based on reality and real
numbers,'' he said. ``Until we get them, I'm not going to decide''
whether to continue his campaign.
   Stanton had no immediate comment.
   The Democratic National Committee will meet in Washington on Feb.
10 to elect a successor to Paul G. Kirk Jr. who is completed a
four-year term as head of the party.
   Many party leaders urged Kirk to seek a second term to avoid a
potentially divisive fight for the chairmanship, but he opted to
step aside.
   Some of the strongest opposition to Brown came from southerners
concerned about his ties to Jackson and the liberal wing of the
party.
   In his campaign for the chairmanship, Brown received the support
of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, as well as
the endorsement of the AFL-CIO.
   ``Ron is probably the most qualified guy in the race,'' said
Florida Democratic Party chairman Charles Whitehead. ``But the
perception in this state is that Ron is Jesse's and Ted's and
labor's guy. ... It poses me a political problem a little bit in
Florida.''
   Brown served as Jackson's convention manager and was widely
credited with helping to end the convention on a note of unity the
night that Michael Dukakis accepted the presidential nomination and
then was joined on the podium by Jackson and his family.
   A former vice chairman of the party, Brown had worked for Kennedy
as general counsel and staff director of the Senate Judiciary
Committee. He was deputy campaign manager for Kennedy's unsuccessful
bid for the 1980 presidential nomination.
   After the 1988 Democratic convention, Brown served as a senior
adviser to the Dukakis presidential campaign.
   Wiener ended his campaign shortly after the four contenders
appeared at a closed meeting of the House Democratic Caucus.
   ``It wasn't that exciting,'' said Rep. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts, a supporter of Brown. ``Since we don't have a vote,
it wasn't exactly clear what was supposed to be happening.''
   A former party vice chairman, Brown was working hard to create a
bandwagon mood that would swing more votes his way.
   ``Ron Brown continues to move closer to winning the chair of the
DNC,'' said his campaign manager Carl Wagner as he announced that 45
committee members from Western states were endorsing the Washington
attorney.
   ``We're at the threshold of victory,'' he said.
   One House Democratic source, who asked not to be identified, said
that during the meeting with the caucus, Brown assured House members
he would remain neutral in the race for the 1992 Democratic
presidential nomination _ a year when Jackson is considered likely
to make his third bid for the nomination.
   Brown also emphasized that his role in party affairs began years
before May 1988 when he agreed to join the Jackson campaign as
convention manager.
   One vocal opponent of the black attorney, Alabama Party chairman
John Baker, said his opposition had nothing to do with Brown's race
or his role in the Jackson campaign.
   Baker said he objected to turning the party leadership over to
someone he described as part of the ``ultra liberal'' wing of the
party.
   ``I can't help the fact that he's black,'' said Baker. ``I can't
help the fact that he was Jesse Jackson's campaign manager.''
</TEXT>
