<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-PressFreedom     01-25 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Press Freedom,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Lawyer Argues in Supreme Court for Right to Take Notes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American lawyer argued in an unusual hearing
before the full Supreme Court on Wednesday that Japan should end
restrictions on taking notes in courts.
   Lawrence Repeta of Seattle charged that the ban on notetaking by
spectators in most criminal trials restricts freedom of reporting,
since only members of exclusive judiciary press clubs generally are
allowed to take notes.
   In Japan's controversial press club system, most government
agencies give preferential access to information to members of
semi-official press clubs. The clubs generally exclude foreign
journalists and Japanese reporters who work for smaller newspapers
and magazines.
   While attending a tax trial in 1983-84 as part of his research on
Japanese tax law, Repeta was repeatedly denied permission by the
judge to take notes. With support from the Japanese Civil Liberties
Union, he lodged a complaint, which was rejected by both the Tokyo
District Court and the Tokyo High Court.
   ``It's a very important international issue,'' Repeta said in an
interview. ``You can't take notes unless you are in a press club,
and no foreign reporters are members of the press clubs. If we win,
that will change.''
   Repeta's Supreme Court appeal hearing Wednesday was unusual
because foreigners seldom address the court, and it is rare that all
15 Supreme Court justices hear a case.
   Speaking in Japanese, Repeta urged the judges to ``set a
democratic standard of openness that will ultimately be followed by
other branches of the Japanese government.''
   In an interview, he said: ``The big question is this: What is the
standing of Japan in the world and what kind of model will Japan
give the rest of the world?
   ``Japan's national government has been very slow in adopting any
changes that would increase the openness of information. If the
Supreme Court doesn't show an example of openness, we can't expect
much from the Diet (parliament) or other government agencies,'' he
said.
   The Tokyo High Court said in rejecting Repeta's appeal in
December 1987 that if ``there is even a slight possibility that
influence may be exerted upon the fair and smooth conduct of a
trial, restrictions on taking of notes are unavoidable.''
   Although members of court press clubs are allowed to take notes,
they do not have access to court documents and can take photographs
only before the actual start of a trial, said Takeshi Maezawa,
ombudsman of the Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest newspaper.
   ``We Japanese journalists should place importance on matters
affecting freedom of the press, freedom of information and the
exchange of information between Japan and the rest of the world, and
understand the greater implications of this case with regard to
those matters,'' he wrote in a column.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
