<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-25 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain, Snow, Sleet Falls From Louisiana West to Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wet weather extended Wednesday from northern Louisiana to the
Rockies, while most of the Southeast enjoyed temperatures in the 70s.
   Snow was expected through Wednesday night in the White Mountains
of eastern Arizona. Snowfall overnight Tuesday in Arizona included 7
inches at Pinetop, 5 inches at McNary, and 2 inches at Show Low.
   Blowing and drifting snow continued Wednesday across the upper
Yellowstone Valley of south-central Montana.
   Snow, freezing rain and sleet fell in the western Oklahoma
Panhandle.
   Snow showers extended from much of Minnesota across northern
Wisconsin into Upper Michigan, across eastern South Dakota,
northeast through southwest Nebraska, western Kansas, Colorado, and
northern New Mexico. Snow and freezing rain reached from northern
Iowa into southern Minnesota.
   Rain showers drenched northern Texas, Oklahoma, northern
Louisiana, Missouri, western Illinois and the remainder of Iowa.
Thunderstorms were scattered among the rain showers from northeast
Missouri to north-central Texas.
   Rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST included 1} inches
at Tulsa, Okla., almost an inch at Joplin, Mo., and about
three-quarters of an inch at San Antonio. Snowfall during the same
six hours included 3 inches at Pueblo, Colo., and an inch at
Lincoln, Neb., and Omaha, Neb.
   Temperatures remained warm over much of the Southeast. Noontime
temperatures were in the 70s from South Carolina across Florida,
over much of the central Gulf of Mexico states, Louisiana and the
eastern quarter of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees below zero at Idaho Falls, Idaho, to 81 degrees at McAllen,
Texas. The low temperature for the nation Wednesday morning was 48
degrees below zero at Wilson, Wyo.
   The forecast for Thursday was for snow in Upper Michigan and from
New England across much of inland New York, mixed with freezing rain
in northeast Pennsylvania and south-central New York. Rain was
predicted from southeast and western New York across the remainder
of Pennsylvania, Virginia, the Ohio Valley, lower Michigan, the
Tennessee Valley, much of Illinois, the southeast two-thirds of
Missouri, Arkansas, northern through western Louisiana, eastern
Oklahoma and the northeast third of Texas. Rain showers, and snow in
higher elevations, were expected in Arizona into southeast
California.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the teens in northern
Maine, 20s and 30s in New England, New York, the upper Great Lakes
region, Minnesota, northwest Missouri, northern and central Plains,
much of Oklahoma, the Rockies, the upper Missouri Valley, the
northern Plateau and the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah.
Highs should be in the 60s and 70s from the Virginias across central
Florida, from the Tennessee Valley across the central Gulf of Mexico
states, and over Louisiana. Temperatures may reach the low 80s in
southeast Texas and southern Florida.
</TEXT>
