<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Letelier 1stLd-Writethru   01-25 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Letelier, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0781,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Chilean Ambasador Says General Ordered Letelier Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with Contreras denial; picks
up 3rd pvs: Letelier and...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former diplomat said on Wednesday he was
told the chief of the military government's secret police ordered
the assassination in Washington of dissident Chilean politician
Orlando Letelier.
   Jose Miguel Barros said in sworn testimony the mastermind was
identified to him as Gen. Manuel Contreras Sepulveda. The United
States has tried for years to extradite the former secret police
chief and his assistant, Col. Pedro Espinoza, both now retired.
   Contreras denied the accusations Wednesday night. ``Neither I nor
any official of the intelligence agency were involved'' in the
killing, he said on Santiago's Channel 13.
   Letelier and American aide Ronnie Moffitt were killed Sept. 21,
1976, when a remote-controlled bomb blew up their car. He had been a
Cabinet minister and ambassador to the United States for the
government overthrown by Gen. Augusto Pinochet in 1973, and was
among Pinochet's most influential critics abroad.
   Barros was one of seven former officials questioned last week at
the request of the U.S. Justice Department. Newspapers carried his
testimony in Wednesday's editions and Barros confirmed the accounts
to The Associated Press.
   He told testified to Judge Julio Banados that air force Gen.
Enrique Montero told him during a meeting in the late 1970s ``this
genius of intelligence mounted an operation to assassinate
Letelier.''
   Barros said Montero, then undersecretary of the Interior Ministry
in the Pinochet government, identified the ``genius'' as Contreras,
head of the National Intelligence Directorate secret police at the
time of the assassination.
   In his testimony, Barros said another participant in the meeting,
former Foreign Minister Miguel Schweitzer, told him Pinochet did not
know of the plot.
   Schweitzer said Pinochet ``asked Contreras three times privately
and two more times in front of witnesses whether he had something to
do with the Letelier case and Contreras said no,'' Barros testified.
   Pinochet later ordered administrative sanctions against Contreras
``for lying to the president,'' the former ambassador said.
   The Supreme Court rejected the U.S. extradition request in 1979
on grounds of insufficient evidence that Contreras and Espinoza were
involved.
   An American employee of the general's secret police, Michael
Townley, confessed in Washington to planting the bomb on the order
of superiors.
   Army Maj. Armando Fernandez Larios, who fled Chile in 1987 and
surrendered to U.S. authorities, confessed to being an accomplice
and implicated Contreras and Espinoza.
   U.S. officials say Chile has not cooperated, and they invoked a
1914 bilateral treaty this month calling for international
arbitration of disputes that cannot be resolved by other means.
Under it, the dispute would go to a commission associated with the
World Court in The Hague, Netherlands.
   ``We energetically reject the implicit pressure in an affair that
we are handling seriously and professionally,'' Foreign Minister
Hernan Errazuriz declared Tuesday. He said the government had not
decided on a response.
</TEXT>
