<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Steinberg     01-25 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stalled Jury in Steinberg Case Goes Three Days without A Verdict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the Joel Steinberg murder trial ended
three days of deliberations without a verdict Wednesday, and a
defense lawyer said he was ``guardedly optimistic'' about an
acquittal on the main charge of murder.
   The jurors, who recessed at 8:55 p.m., indicated the day before
they were sharply divided when they asked the judge whether they
could move to the lesser homicide counts against Steinberg if they
were not unanimous on the top count, second-degree murder.
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax repeated what he told
the six men and six women before they got the case Monday: That they
must unanimously acquit Steinberg of murdering 6-year-old Lisa
Steinberg before moving down to first-degree manslaughter,
second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide.
   Deliberations were scheduled to resume at 10 a.m. Thursday.
   Defense lawyer Ira London said the questions the jurors asked
Tuesday and the length of their deliberations had made him
``guardedly optimistic'' about Steinberg being acquitted on the
murder charge.
   ``This is an extremely intelligent jury,'' London said. ``If they
can't resolve the murder charge, they're going to say, `We're not
going to sit here and look at each other,' but they're not going to
permit a mistrial, either.''
   London said he expected the panel to exercise what is known in
legal circles as ``jury nullification.'' This means they would
disregard the judge's legal instructions and do what they feel is
right.
   The jurors sent out no notes during the morning session
Wednesday, and shortly before 6 p.m. asked for a rereading of
testimony by pathologists who testified for the prosecution and the
defense.
   The first was Dr. Douglas Miller, a neuropathologist at New York
University Medical Center and a prosecution witness. He said the
force that caused Lisa's head injuries was equivalent to a
three-story fall and could have been inflicted by a man the size of
Steinberg, who is 6 feet tall and weighs 180 to 190 pounds.
   The jury also asked to rehear the testimony of Dr. John Plunkett,
a coroner from St. Paul, Minn., and the defense pathologist. He
agreed with Miller that Lisa was the victim of a homicide but
testified her injuries could have been caused by a woman the size of
Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's former companion.
   In addition, the jurors asked to rehear Plunkett's testimony on
the CAT scan of Lisa's brain. The CAT scan, he said, showed that
less force had caused Lisa's injuries than Miller had testified.
   The jurors said that after rehearing the testimony they would go
to dinner and retire for the night.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged in the fatal
beating of Lisa, the girl he obtained at birth from an unwed Long
Island teen-ager and raised as his own but never legally adopted.
   The child was comatose when taken from Steinberg's Greenwich
Village apartment on Nov. 2, 1987, to a hospital where she died of a
brain injury three days later.
   London said he believes Ms. Nussbaum, the prosecution's star
witness, is the center of the jury's deliberation difficulties.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former children's book editor, testified that
Steinberg told her in bed, after they smoked cocaine and while Lisa
lay comatose on their bathroom floor, that he had ``knocked Lisa
down and she didn't want to get up.''
   Steinberg's lawyers charge that Ms. Nussbaum fatally beat the
child in a jealous rage.
   The prosecution maintains that Ms. Nussbaum, against whom murder
charges were dropped after she agreed to be a prosecution witness,
was too physically and emotionally disabled by 12 years of living
with Steinberg to have harmed Lisa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SpyInterviewed     01-25 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy Interviewed,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walker Says U.S. Secrets Easy To Steal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Navy secrets are easier to steal than
toothpaste from a department store, former navy radioman and
convicted spy John A. Walker said in an interview broadcast
Wednesday night.
   ``I have to say that K-Mart security is better than anything the
Navy would have. I mean K-Mart protects their toothpaste better than
the Navy protects their top secrets,'' said Walker, who was a chief
warrant officer with top secret clearance.
   Walker spoke in an interview filmed in the federal prison in
Marion, Ill., where he is serving life for running a Soviet spy
ring. The commercial Channel 4 television program, ``Dispatches,''
calling him America's ``most notorious spy,'' said it was the first
time he had been interviewed.
   Walker said the lax security enabled him to photograph decoding
material and technical manuals at U.S. Navy bases and on warships,
from which the Soviets were able to build copies of the latest
cryptographic machines.
   He said when offered some of the material, the Soviets told him
not to bother, indicating they had other spies at work. ``They were
probably paying for the stuff five times,'' Walker said.
   Walker said he was interviewed by the National Security Agency
and ``the boys went pale'' when he told them the Soviets wanted
nothing on machines that went into service in the early 1980s with
the U.S. Navy and NATO, indicating they already had what they needed.
   The program said Walker's spying activities would have
compromised secret material of all the navies in the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization. It said the Soviets ``read millions of
secret messages'' exchanged between the various navies.
   The balding, bespectacled and bearded spy looked relaxed and
confident and was smoking a pipe. The program said he insisted on
being interviewed in civilian and not prison garb.
   Walker said his espionage even included updating his own security
clearance and inserting it in his Navy records.
   ``The fact of the matter is I did perfect work for both
governments at the same time. My work for the U.S. Navy was
extraordinary, exemplary. My work for the Soviets was also
exemplary,'' he said.
   The program said the Soviets paid Walker $1 million for supplying
them with code-breaking information over 18 years.
   Walker showed no remorse in the interview and often smiled and
laughed but he said at the end, ``I'm very sorry, sorry for the
Navy, for the country.
   ``The Walker spy ring is behind bars, but there are still more
than 4 million Americans cleared for access to more than a trillion
classified documents. In the past eight years alone, 40 traitors
have been caught trying to sell secrets,'' the program said.
   Walker said in conclusion: ``You have to assume they are not
arresting everybody. What percentage do you think they are arresting
_ half, a third, 1 percent? I don't know.''
</TEXT>
