<FIRST>r a AM-Gays-CIA     01-25 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gays-CIA,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Revives Discrimination Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Wednesday revived
a lesbian's lawsuit against the CIA for denying her a security
clearance.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said a claim that the CIA
has a policy of rejecting clearances for any homosexual _ an
allegation the agency denies _ should not have been dismissed
without a trial.
   The CIA's explanation for its actions in this case suggests the
agency ``considers all persons who engage in homosexual activity to
be unacceptable security risks,'' the court said in a 3-0 decision.
   The ruling allows Julie Dubbs, an openly lesbian employee of a
military contractor on the San Francisco Peninsula, to go to trial
on her claim that the CIA unconstitutionally denied her a high-level
security clearance in 1981.
   Attorney Richard Gayer, noting that his client received a similar
clearance from the Army, said the decision, ``gives us a chance to
embarrass the CIA'' by forcing it to justify its practices. He said
he was disappointed the court required her to prove discrimination
before the federal judge who had previously thrown out her case.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown would not comment on
behalf of the government.
   Dubbs of Santa Clara maintains she needed the clearance to
advance in her job as a senior technical illustrator for SRI
International of Menlo Park.
   The CIA turned her down in a letter that gave two reasons: she
had not volunteered information about her homosexuality during an
initial security investigation, an action that an agency official
described as showing a ``willingness to engage in deceptive
behavior;'' and, although her current lover was also an open
lesbian, Dubbs might have a future partner ``who is not an open
homosexual and who fears public exposure.''
</TEXT>
