<FIRST>r a AM-BoeingWiring     01-25 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing Wiring,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing 737 Inspections Turn Up No Wiring Problems, Company Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No cross-wiring problems have been found in the
engine-monitoring systems of 495 Boeing airplanes inspected as a
result of a crash in England earlier this month that killed 44
people, Boeing Co. says.
   The Jan. 8 crash of a British Midland 737-400 airliner occurred
after one of its two engines caught fire, and the pilot shut down
the wrong engine.
   Pilots' union officials have suggested that faulty wiring to
engine monitors, rather than pilot error, could have caused the
crash.
   Boeing said the engine fire detection, overheating and vibration
monitoring systems of 479 model 737-300s and 16 of the
stretch-version 737-400s were checked, and no problems were found.
Reports were not yet in from the remaining nine 737-300s in service
around the world, the company said Tuesday.
   The inspection recommendation was put together by Boeing, engine
manufacturer CFM International, the Civil Aviation Authority of the
United Kingdom and the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration.
</TEXT>
