<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Union     01-25 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Union,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Charges Union Head With Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has charged the jailed boss of
the powerful Oil Workers Union with homicide in the 1983 shooting of
a local labor leader, the Attorney General's Office announced
Wednesday.
   It was the second murder charge brought against Joaquin Hernandez
Galicia, who for years was the de facto head of the union.
   Assistant Attorney General Javier Coello Trejos told a news
conference that Hernandez Galicia, 66, ordered the Sept. 8, 1983,
slaying of Oscar Torres Pancardo, a local oil union official and
former congressman.
   Coello said that Hernandez Galicia ordered his own bodyguards to
kill Torres. Coello did not cite possible motives for the killing.
   Torres was killed by a bullet in the head.
   ``This crime has been investigated since it occurred, but
Hernandez Galicia gave us the details,'' Coello said in response to
questions as to why it took so long to identify those responsible
for the slaying.
   Coello identified Mauro Estrada Cruz as the bodyguard who planned
the killing. Estrada was arrested along with Hernandez Galicia on
charges of homicide, weapons possession and resisting arrest.
   Estrada is a former commander with the Federal Judicial Police in
the northeast state of Tamaulipas.
   Four other bodyguards are being investigated in connection with
Torres' killing, Coello said.
   Hernandez Galicia was arrested after a shootout with federal
agents at his home on Jan. 10 in Ciudad Madero, Tamaulipas, 340
miles northeast of Mexico City.
   Hernandez Galicia, Estrada and seven other detainees were charged
with homicide in connection with the death of a federal agent killed
in the gunfight.
   About 37 other union leaders and associates have been indicted on
charges that include illegal weapons possession and resisting arrest.
   Hernandez Galicia has consistently denied wrongdoing.
   Salvador Barragan Camacho, the union's former secretary-general,
is under arrest at a Mexico City hospital where he is being treated
for heart problems. He also faces corruption and weapons charges.
   Coello also said that another of Hernandez Galicia's bodyguards
has been arrested in connection with drug trafficking but that
Hernandez Galicia has not personally been connected to the case.
</TEXT>
