<FIRST>r a AM-SisterShot     01-25 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sister Shot,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0816 to change category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-year-old girl died Wednesday after being
shot in the head by her 8-year-old brother with a gun their
grandmother had purchased for protection against burglars, officials
said.
   The incident occurred during an after-school argument while the
two were home alone, police said.
   The girl had been declared brain-dead following the Monday
afternoon incident, but she was on life-support machines at Fairfax
Hospital. She died after those machines were turned off, hospital
officials said.
   The shooting occurred after the two children returned home from
school, according to police in this Washington, D.C., suburb.
   Police did not release the names of the children. The shooting
occurred at the home of the children's grandmother, Dorothy Bea,
where they had moved last year after their parents separated.
   The incident began when the boy, a second-grader, began playing
with a .32 pistol Mrs. Bea kept in a dresser drawer in her bedroom.
His sister, who was in the first grade, scolded him for playing with
the gun and he responded by shooting her, police said.
   The shooting occurred after the children had returned home from
school, which ended at 1:10 p.m. They were normally alone in the
home until 3 p.m., when an uncle came home, officials said.
   Fairfax County Commonwealth's Attorney Robert F. Horan Jr. said
he probably will not file charges against the girl's brother unless
it can be proven the attack was deliberate.
   Horan said police must have evidence that the boy was ``capable
of forming criminal intent'' when he pulled the trigger. ``Does he
know right from wrong? That would be determined by a lot of
things,'' he said.
   Although the shooting was termed deliberate by police, they
weren't sure about the boy's state of mind.
   ``When we say `deliberate,' we mean it was not an accidental
thing,'' said police spokesman Warren Carmichael. ``He did point
(the gun) and he did pull (the trigger). Whether he realized what
would happen ... we're just not in a position to say.''
   Mrs. Bea said she doesn't believe her grandson intended to harm
his sister.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it was an accident,'' she said. ``He's
just eight. He couldn't have known.''
   Mrs. Bea said she bought the gun 18 months ago for protection
against burglars.
   Neither of the children knew she owned a gun until the boy began
rummaging through the dresser drawers after Christmas, Bea said the
boy told police.
</TEXT>
