<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0798 01-25 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Stage Raids In Probe Of Base Attack; Arrest Total Increased
to 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATE with Alfonsin signing decree to create
National Security Council, one woman arrested in raids, arrested commandos
being interrogated. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police staged more than 20 raids
around the capital Wednesday, seeking evidence connected to an
attack on a base that left 36 people dead and at least 68 wounded,
Attorney General Andres D'Alessio said.
   Also Wednesday, President Raul Alfonsin signed a decree creating
a National Security Council to investigate the attack and prevent
subversion.
   Alessio said three of the civilian commandos identified belonged
to radical leftist groups, supporting the government's contention
that the attack was leftist-inspired. He also said the attackers
identified so far are Argentine.
   In all, 17 men and two women between the ages of 19 and 35 were
being held at police headquarters in downtown Buenos Aires,
D'Alessio said. A 20th person was hospitalized with wounds and may
or may not be involved with the commandos, he said.
   Previously, the government acknowleged only 14 people were under
arrest.
   He also said the commandos included five women, two of which were
killed and three arrested.
   Shortly after dawn Monday, about 50 heavily armed civilians burst
through the main gate at the 3rd infantry regiment at La Tablada on
the outskirts of Buenos Aires. By Tuesday afternoon, at least 28
were dead and perhaps 10 others escaped.
   Seven soldiers and a policeman also were killed, officials said.
   The attorney general said police raided between 20 and 25 places
in the capital and its suburbs as part of an investigation of the
base attack. One woman was arrested. D'Alessio declined to give any
further details.
   D'Alessio offered little information about the commandos' motives
and ideology, but the identities of three lent support to the
position of President Raul Alfonsin that the group was comprised of
radical leftists.
   Among the dead were Jose Luis Caldu, a former member of the
Castro-inspired Peoples Revolutionary Army, and Jorge Manuel Banos,
a leader of a spinoff group known as Movement Everyone for the
Country. Banos recently denounced alleged plans by rightists in the
military to overthrow the government and install Peronist
presidential candidate Carlos Menem.
   At least 18 bodies remain to be identified, D'Alessio said.
   ERP, as the People's Revolutionary Army is called by its Spanish
acronym, formally disbanded in 1980 after years of battling with
soldiers in open clashes, and being decimated in the process. The
Movement is a small, little-known organization that includes ex-ERP
militants.
   Under arrest is another Movement leader, Juan Manuel Burgos.
   Pamphlets and statements found among the commandos indicated they
called themselves the Popular Resistance Front, which government
sources say was composed of former members of the ERP, the Movement
and other groups.
   The propaganda indicated the commandos saw themselves as acting
to prevent an imminent right-wing coup.
   There was little indication what the group intended to do at the
base or achieve by the attack; or whether it had links to similar
groups.
   A congressional source with close ties to the left said the
attackers hoped to carry out a lightning raid to demonstrate their
militant opposition to right-wing elements in the army and to
attract popular support, and that they did not intend a shootout.
   Alvaro Alsogaray, presidential candidate of the Center Alliance,
said the government must make sure the attack is an isolated
incident and not the leading edge of a wave of attacks like those
that plagued the country 15 years ago.
   Alfonsin, in a nationwide speech Tuesday night, said resolving
the symptoms if not the causes of subversion ``is the last test of
my government'' and pledged to establish a National Security Council.
   The council, over which Alfonsin personally is to preside, will
include the ministers of defense, interior and foreign relations;
the heads of Argentina's army, navy and air force, and others the
president might choose later.
   The immediate goals are to figure out what happened in Monday's
base attack, determine whether other potential threats exist,
develop strategies of prevention and coordinate information.
   Alfonsin's election in 1983 replaced a military dictatorship. He
will step down in December after national elections in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
