<SECOND>AM-Airport Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0826,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out In International Arrivals Building At JFK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE number of injured to 36; details of
fire; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-alarm fire broke out Wednesday in a snack
bar storeroom in the John F. Kennedy Airport International Arrivals
Building, injuring 36 people and forcing 600 to evacuate,
authorities said.
   The injured included civilians, Port Authority police officers
and firefighters and at least two were believed to be in serious
condition, said Capt. Mark Rothstein of Emergency Medical Services.
   Rothstein said 18 people were treated at the scene for smoke
inhalation and the rest were taken to hospitals for treatment of
smoke inhalation.
   The cause of the three-alarm blaze was not immediately known. It
began on the second floor of the building's west wing, in a snack
bar-souvenir store and storage area, said Efrain Parrilla, a Fire
Department spokesman.
   ``It centered in the ceiling of the storage area for the
restaurant,'' said Mark Marchese, a Port Authority spokesman.
   The snack bar is located between Gate 33, which was being used by
Air France at the time of the fire, and Gate 34, which El Al Israel
Airlines was using, said Armando Arrastia, another PA spokesman.
   Air France, El Al, Air Afrique and Royal Air Maroc flights were
delayed because of the fire, Marchese said. No passengers were
aboard the planes but aircraft were moved away from the building
during the fire, he said.
   About 170 firefighters fought the blaze, which was reported at
7:26 p.m. and went to three alarms at 8:21 p.m., said Firefighter
Aaron Foxx, a department spokesman. It was declared under control at
8:49 p.m., he said.
   Chief of Department Homer Bishop said damage to the building was
light but damage to its contents was heavy.
   The fire was under investigation but had not been ruled
suspicious, Parrilla said.
</TEXT>
