<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's embattled nominee as secretary
of health wooed and won the support of a cadre of conservative
anti-abortion senators Wednesday and got a fresh endorsement from
the president.
   ``He has supported my position 100 percent,'' Bush told two
newspaper reporters in an interview, saying the chances were
``none'' that he would withdraw the nomination of Louis W. Sullivan
to head the Department of Health and Human Services.
   ``I've not heard anyone suggesting that he will not be
confirmed,'' Bush said.
   Bush's chief of staff, John H. Sununu said Sullivan had suggested
that the key position of under secretary be given to Constance
Horner, well known for her anti-abortion views. She is director of
the Office of Personnel Management. Horner's appointment was
expected to be announced soon.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a quarter of the Senate sponsored
legislation Wednesday that would reject a proposed 50 percent
congressional pay raise, and would roll back the increase if the
House lets it become law by ducking a vote.
   The senators, 10 Democrats and 13 Republicans, made clear they
wanted to turn up pressure on the House, which appears headed toward
allowing the increase to become law automatically.
   Sens. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., and Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa,
