   Japan's Economic Planning Agency chief has resigned,
becoming the third Cabinet minister in less than two months to fall
victim to a major stock-trading scandal.
   In another blow to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who had
reshuffled his Cabinet on Dec. 27, Ken Harada stepped down Tuesday
after news reports said he had received regular political donations
from Recruit Co., the company at the center of the stock scandal.
</TEXT>
