<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   01-25 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mid-January Car, Light Truck Sales Fall 11.5 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies making cars and light trucks in the
United States reported sales dropped 11.5 percent in mid-January
compared with unusually strong results last year.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. all
reported double-digit sales declines, led by GM's 21.9 percent drop
and followed by Ford's 13.6 percent decline and Chrysler's 10
percent fall.
   The seven companies making cars in this country reported Tuesday
they sold vehicles at a daily rate of 28,584 during the Jan. 11-20
period this year compared with an average daily rate of 32,292
during the same time last year.
   But last year's numbers were unusually high, said analyst
Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New
York.
   ``Last January was the highest seasonally adjusted (sales) rate
in the last 20 years,'' she said. ``And it will continue into
February, too.''
   During the first part of last year, automakers were worried about
the fallout from the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash. To bolster
sales, they put incentives on their vehicles, a move that may have
proven unnecessary.
   ``The automakers didn't really realize that the underlying demand
was there,'' Heaney said. ``So, consumers were going to buy anyway
and then the incentives pushed them up more.''
   The U.S. automakers said they sold cars at a daily rate of 17,330
during the period this year, compared with a daily rate of 20,709
during the same time last year. There were nine selling days in both
periods.
   Sales of U.S.-made light trucks dropped 2.8 percent in
mid-January to a daily rate of 11,254 from a rate of 11,583 during
the same time last year.
   During the first two 10-day periods this year, sales of U.S.-made
cars and light trucks were down 5.2 percent, to a daily rate of
27,288 from a rate of 28,775 last year. There were 16 sales days in
both periods.
   Among the Big Three U.S. automakers, GM car sales dropped 21.9
percent in mid-January to a daily rate of 7,861 from a 10,066 rate
during the same period last year. GM's light trucks sold at a 4,306
daily rate during the Jan. 11-20 period this year, down 4 percent
from 4,488 daily during the same time last year.
   Ford Motor Co. cars sold at a daily rate of 5,842 during the
period this year, down 13.6 from a rate of 6,766 last year. Ford
light trucks sold at a rate of 3,968 during mid-January this year,
down 5.5 percent from a rate of 4,202 during the period last year.
   Cars sales by Chrysler Corp. dropped 10 percent during
mid-January this year, to a daily rate of 2,462 from a rate of 2,736
last year. Light trucks sold at a daily rate of 2,634 this year, up
0.8 percent from the 2,613 rate during the period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
