<FIRST>r f PM-EconomyRdp     01-25 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Comments Boost Stock Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: May be led with existing home sales reports scheduled for mid-morning
release.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan says the risk of
inflation is great enough to keep boosting interest rates to
restrict growth, and his comments were credited with helping fuel
rallies in stocks and bonds.
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 38.04 points on Tuesday to
finish at 2,256.43, closing above its pre-Black Monday level for the
first time since the October 1987 crash.
   After closing at 2,246.74 on Oct. 16, 1987, the Dow Jones
industrials lost an unprecedented 508 points in the Black Monday
market collapse on Oct. 19.
   Testifying before the House Banking Committee on Tuesday,
Greenspan warned that strains on factory capacity and a tight labor
market, particularly in the Northeast, likely would keep inflation
pressures high, so the central bank's monetary policy should
continue on the tight side.
   ``The long-run costs of a return to higher inflation, and the
risks of this occurring under current circumstances, are
sufficiently great that Federal Reserve policy at this juncture
might well be advised to err more on the side of restrictiveness
than of stimulus,'' he said.
   Greenspan told Congress he wants to keep a lid on economic growth
and continue to slowly boost interest rates to avoid higher
inflation, which was 4.4 percent in 1988.
   The Labor Department, meanwhile, reported that wage gains of 4.1
percent last year lagged behind inflation rate while employment
costs, at 5 percent, rose faster than inflation.
   Wage and salary gains are closely watched as signals of a
possible inflationary spiral. The increase for 1988 was much closer
to inflation than the 3.3 percent wage hike reported for 1987.
   The Labor Department figures indicated that continued low
unemployment has forced employers to compete for available workers,
often by increasing pay.
   Greenspan said the unemployment rate, at 5.3 percent in December,
has hit a 14-year low, well within the range of what most economists
consider to be the natural rate of unemployment, leaving little room
for further improvement without inflation.
   In other economic news Tuesday, automakers reported that sales of
U.S.-made cars in mid-January plummeted 16.3 percent _ led by
General Motors Corp.'s 21.9 percent decline _ from a relatively
strong year-earlier period.
   A year ago, automakers were offering some buyer incentives amid
continued uneasiness about the strength of the automobile market
following the stock market crash. Eventually, the concern about the
market proved to be unwarranted as automakers posted the third-best
model year in history in 1988.
</TEXT>
