<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-25 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Up Against Yen, Stocks Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher today against the
Japanese yen, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index inched up
to another record high.
   The dollar ended at 127.65 yen, up 0.70 yen from Tuesday's 126.95
yen close. It opened at 127.86 yen and ranged between 127.37 and
127.88 yen.
   The dollar's higher opening followed a remark Tuesday by U.S.
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan that he would tighten
monetary policy to fight inflation.
   After buying the dollar in early trading, speculative investors
then started selling the currency for position adjustments, said
Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank.
   ``We already knew that the United States would tighten its
monetary policy and keep interest rates high, but Greenspan's
comment still prompted the buying because Japanese investors have
been looking for market-affecting incentives,'' he added.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make the dollar more
attractive to foreign investors.
   Other dealers said investors were reluctant to push the dollar
higher for fear of another round of dollar-selling intervention by
central banks.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at
31,567.79, a new high just 10.11 points, or 0.03 percent, higher
than the previous record of 31,557.68, set on Tuesday.
   The index's rally in early trading followed rising prices on
overseas markets overnight. It began falling as investors grew
concerned about the index's rapid increase, but managed to keep the
marginal gain, said a dealer with Nikko Securities in Tokyo.
   Trading became directionless as investors floated from one issue
to another while trying to keep the index from rising too high, said
the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Investors are expecting the Nikkei to rise continuously, but
they get cautious if prices rise too quickly,'' the dealer said.
   He predicted that the Nikkei would continue upward in view of
recent stability in foreign exchange rates and oil prices.
</TEXT>
