<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     01-25 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up against most major
currencies in light European trading early today, spurred by Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's declaration to fight
inflation.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the dollar's surge could prompt renewed
dollar-selling by central banks, and said fear of intervention was
already preventing the dollar from rising faster.
   ``The market is waiting to see whether the central banks come
in,'' said a dealer at a bank in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Greenspan told Congress on Tuesday that the risks of inflation
were great enough that the Fed ``might well be advised to err more
on the side of restrictiveness than of stimulus.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.70 Japanese yen to a closing 127.65 yen. Later, in
London, it slipped back to 127.55 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8414 West German marks, up from 1.8395; 1.5640
Swiss francs, up from 1.5523; 6.2660 French francs, up from 6.2335;
2.0760 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0680; 1,347.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,340.50; 1.1828 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1866.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7710 from $1.7700 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $404.80 a troy ounce,
down from $407 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $404.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $404.60, down from $407.10 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.42 to close at a bid $406.57.
   Silver fell sharply in London to a bid price of $6.12 a troy
ounce, down from $6.21 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
