<FIRST>r f PM-Kirkland-Deficit     01-25 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kirkland-Deficit,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirkland Says Deficit Panel Hobbled by Lack of Bush Commitment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Economic Commission will be
remembered as a ``missed opportunity'' in deficit-reduction efforts
because it lacks the White House commitment necessary to negotiate a
settlement, a panel member says.
   ``I think it had the potential of being a worthwhile exercise
(but) I think up to now at least a couple of the essential
ingredients of an important role for the commission are lacking,''
AFL-CIO president Lane Kirkland said Tuesday.
   The panel has been meeting since last May and is scheduled to
submit a report to President Bush by March 1. Bush decided against
extending the deadline six months.
   ``The prospects of a unified report, I think, are doubtful but I
don't want to make any premature judgments,'' said Kirkland, one of
14 members of the panel.
   Missing, he said, was a commitment from the White House, and to a
lesser extent congressional leaders, that the commission's work
would be seriously considered and that the panel would be used as a
forum to find a compromise among various deficit-reduction proposals.
   Kirkland said such a commitment and a sense of urgency were
essential to the work of a 1982-83 commission that studied the
Social Security system. Kirkland also served on that panel.
   ``Those were the circumstances that I think were necessary for
this committee to serve its purpose,'' he said. ``They may yet
evolve, I don't write off that possibility, but as yet it's not
visible.''
   Asked who was to blame, Kirkland said:
   ``I would suppose if you want to lay it at the door of any one
factor it is the constraints that have been expressed by the
president, both before his election and since, as to the options
that were available to deal with the problem. ... He seems
preferenced to advance his own programs, his commitment to the
so-called flexible freeze.''
   Kirkland, during a meeting with reporters at his office, said
congressional leaders also have not given the commission the stature
it needs to convince the various interest groups involved in
deficit-reduction efforts to make concessions.
   ``Absent that, you see, members of the commission, certainly like
myself, find no real reason to yield on any of our positions,'' he
said. ``If there were serious negotiations with the major players
and the ultimate package or the ultimate shape of the resolution
were otherwise acceptable, as a citizen and as a patriot and as one
concerned with resolving it, I'd be disposed to go along with some
things that might otherwise prove distasteful.''
</TEXT>
