<FIRST>r f PM-TraderVic's     01-25 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trader Vic's,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Says Vic's is Tacky, Closing It Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trader Vic's, that citadel of ersatz Polynesian
cuisine whose defenders include former President Richard Nixon, has
gotten ``tacky'' and has no place in the Plaza Hotel, Plaza owner
Donald Trump says.
   Trump, who recently bought the Plaza, wants to revamp the hotel
into a five-star institution and says the restaurant _ with its
thatched roofs and dugout canoes _ ``does not fit in with the image
of the hotel I want to achieve.''
   So instead of a Polynesian-style bar where customers could order
a Samoan Fog Cutter or a Dr. Funk of Tahiti, there'll be a health
club and a restaurant serving Japanese and Chinese food.
   But, perhaps to console patrons who feel they've been forsaken,
there'll be a bar, run by Trump, that will serve tropical drinks.
   That's small consolation to such loyal patrons as Nixon, who
dined there while president in 1972.
   ``My entire family will be very sorry to see it close,'' Nixon
said Tuesday through a spokesman. ``It was always our daughters'
favorite restaurant, and it quickly became mine, too.''
   Trump, who bought the Plaza last year for $390 million, said
construction on the Oriental restaurant and the health club will
start in about three or four months.
   The restaurant section of Trader Vic's, which has been in the
Plaza basement for 25 years, has been closed for more than year. But
the bar has remained open.
   Clint Wade, a Trader Vic's spokesman, said the company wants to
run the new Oriental restaurant at the hotel but noted that Trump
has ``no intention of keeping Trader Vic's'' at the Plaza.
   ``The Trumps want to get a new looking restaurant and that is
also what we want,'' Wade said. ``Sure, Trader Vic's has gotten
tacky, but that's because nothing has been done to it in 12 years.''
   Trader Vic's, which began in San Francisco, still has more than
20 restaurants across the United States and in West Germany, Japan
and Canada, Wade said.
</TEXT>
