<FIRST>r f PM-CellularPhones-McCaw     01-25 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cellular Phones-McCaw,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw And AT&amp;T Get Government Cellular Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cellular Phones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. of
Kirkland and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. have signed an
agreement that gives McCaw the federal government's
cellular-telephone business.
   The immediate impact of the AT&amp;T-McCaw subcontracting agreement
is likely to be small in financial terms at first, but could mean
big business if the federal government expands its use of cellular
phones.
   McCaw already is the nation's largest provider of cellular
service.
   The agreement comes under a contract awarded by the General
Services Administration last month to AT&amp;T for 60 percent of the
contract for the government's multibillion-dollar FTS-2000 network.
The new network will replace a 24-year-old federal
telecommunications system.
   ``Including cellular services in AT&amp;T's package would give the
government an excellent new wire-free communications technology,''
said Loren Kragh, a McCaw vice president. ``For the first time,
government personnel away from the office, on field assignments or
responding to emergencies will have continuous access'' to the
government phone system.
   If the government decides to make extensive use of cellular
telephones, ``it could be a great deal for McCaw,'' said Tom
Friedberg, an analyst for Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. in Seattle.
   McCaw, which has been aggressively buying cellular franchises in
major cities, already serves areas with populations totaling about
48 million people in 25 states.
   Last week, McCaw announced it will sell 22 percent of its stock
to British Telecom, Britain's largest telecommunications company,
for $1.5 billion.
</TEXT>
