<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe-Farmers     01-25 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe-Farmers,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Shakes Confidence in Markets, Farm Leader Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Commodites Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Illinois Farm
Bureau, citing wavering confidence in the Chicago commodity markets,
is urging a speedy conclusion to an FBI probe of alleged fraud at
the city's two futures exchanges.
   John White Jr. warned of serious consequences from a prolonged
probe of allegations that as many as 100 traders and brokers at the
Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange defrauded
customers of millions of dollars.
   ``These are not just Chicago markets _ these are world markets
and these are my markets,'' White, a Kane County grain farmer, said
Tuesday in a telephone news conference.
   ``The public must feel that traders on the floor of the exchanges
are working honestly and in an open environment,'' he said.
   Some grain and livestock farmers use the futures markets to
guarantee prices for the crops and herds they are raising by
entering into contracts for future delivery of their products at a
specified price. Futures prices also influence cash prices for the
commodities.
   White said confidence in the integrity of the futures industry
was crucial to farmers' participation in the markets. Farmers also
must have trust in the independent traders who create liquidity in
the market by accepting producers' risks in hope of making a profit.
   ``That confidence has been diminished by the current probe,''
White said. ``Our analysts feel that liquidity has already been
diminished.''
   He said it was too early to know whether the growing scandal had
set back the efforts of some farm leaders to encourage farmers to
use the futures markets.
   ``If the investigation uncovers a major violation, it's a major
setback,'' he said. ``If it turns out to be nitpicking ... I think
it would be a short-term thing that can be overcome.''
</TEXT>
