<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computer     01-25 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Earnings Up Half-Percent At Unisys; Prime, Apollo Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. said Wednesday it managed a
half-percent increase in fourth-quarter earnings to end what it
called ``a tougher year than we and most of the industry originally
expected.''
   Among other computer makers, Prime Computer Inc. said it lost
money in the quarter because of a one-time charge, and Apollo
Computer Inc. said it managed a profit after two quarters of losses.
   Unisys, the nation's third-largest computer company, said its
quarterly earnings edged up to $218 million, or $1.05 per share,
from last year's figures of $216.9 million, or $1.09 per share.
Revenue for the fourth quarter was up slightly over the same period
last year _ to $2.87 billion from $2.8 billion.
   For all of 1988, Unisys said net income rose 18 percent to $680.6
million, or $3.27 per share, from last year's figure of $578
million, or $2.93 per share. Revenue rose to $9.9 billion for the
year from 1987's figure of $9.71 billion.
   Unisys, which has headquarters in Blue Bell, Pa., and Detroit,
said it expected its earnings in the current quarter ``will be very
weak'' because of lower production levels, inventory reduction
programs and the transition to a new line of mainframe computers.
   Prime, the Natick, Mass.-based minicomputer company, said a
pre-tax charge of $45 million in the fourth quarter produced a net
loss of 14.4 million, compared with a profit of $21.3 million, or 44
cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue jumped 61 percent to $431
million from $267 million a year earlier because of the Feb. 5,
1988, acquisition of Computervision Corp.
   Prime's one-time charge covered costs for a reorganization and
cuts of 1,200 jobs as well as the expense of fighting off an ongoing
takeover attempt by MAI Basic Four Inc. Without the charge, earnings
would have been $18.4 million.
   For the full year, Prime said its earnings after the one-time
charge fell to $19 million, or 39 cents a share, from $64.8 million,
or $1.32 a share, a year earlier. Revenue jumped to $1.59 billion
from $960 million.
   Apollo, the computer workstation maker based in Chelmsford,
Mass., said it earned $3.2 million, or 9 cents a share, in its
fourth quarter, helped by a $1.9 million gain on the repurchase of
debt. Although the earnings were off 68 percent from $10 million a
year earlier, they were a reversal of losses in the second and third
quarters. Revenue rose 13 percent to $184 million from $163 million.
   For the full year, Apollo said its earnings fell 90 percent to
$2.1 million, or 6 cents a share, from $20 million, or 56 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 18 percent to a record $654
million from $554 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
