<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today, pausing after
Tuesday's runup to its highest level since the crash of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 38.04 points on
Tuesday, slipped back 1.61 to 2,254.82 in the first half hour today.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 549 up, 404 down and
523 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 29.70 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said the market lately has appeared to be emerging from
the long shadow cast by the crash.
   The Dow Jones industrial average's rise Tuesday to its highest
level since before Black Monday Oct. 19, 1987 was widely seen as a
big step in that direction.
   The market also has been helped by a rising dollar in foreign
exchange and falling interest rates in the long-term bond market.
   With all that, however, brokers said there remained many
skeptics, expecting a slowing economy, who were unwilling to chase
after stocks at their current levels.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Merck rose } to 62| and
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph gained \ to 30}, while International
Business Machines fell | to 123|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .03 to 162.02. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .52 at 319.26.
   On Tuesday advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than 2
to 1 on the NYSE, with 1,014 up, 467 down and 479 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 189.62 million shares, against 141.64
million in the previous session.
