<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher in Active Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher in active trading at
midday Wednesday, although off the best levels, amid what dealers
called a renewed confidence in financial markets.
   Shares bounded 26 points higher at the opening, on a combination
of bullish sentiment from Wall Street's 38-point surge Tuesday, a
perception that British interest rates might fall before the March
14 budget and a perception that U.S. President George Bush might be
more successful than originally thought in tackling the U.S. budget
deficit.
   In addition, dealers said a large program trade was activated
early in the session, which contained a hefty chunk of buy orders.
   Shares trimmed their advance by midday in what one dealer called
``orderly profit-taking.''
   By about noon the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 14.1 points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,955.2, also the session's
low point. The index hit its peak of 1,967.1 at the start of
official dealings.
   Volume came to 614.2 million shares by midday compared with 342
million shares at the same time Tuesday.
</TEXT>
