<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Lower in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grains and soybeans were lower
today in early trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures were weighed down by the rainy weather forecast for
the Great Plains growing areas and a slackening of U.S. wheat
exports, said Dale Gustafson, a grains analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Soybean prices pulled back because European markets didn't follow
through with Tuesday's rally in Chicago and it appears the recent
surge of commercial buying has ended, said Gustafson.
   Corn futures were lower in sympathy with the decline in wheat and
soybeans, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents to 8} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.34{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 2\ cents lower, with March at $2.70} a bushel; oats were 2\ cents
to 3 cents lower, with March at $2.32\ a bushel; and soybeans were \
cent to 4 cents lower with March at $7.65 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures rose in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .15 cent to .28 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in February at 72.92 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .05 cent to .30 cent higher with January at 83.60
cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .40 cent higher with
February at 43.37 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .72
cent to .97 cent higher with February at 40.12 cents a pound.
   On Tuesday, livestock and meat prices finished mixed to mostly
lower.
