<FIRST>u f PM-NuclearPlants 1stLd-Writethru f0034 01-25 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Plants, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0034,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Find Safety Problems Persist at Colorado Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 14-15, The Washington Post, with new grafs 14-16,
to change attribution; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal inspection of safety at a nuclear
weapons plant near Denver found serious lapses caused in part by
inadequate worker training, but significant improvements are under
way, Energy Department officials said.
   The outlines of a report on the inspection, conducted by a team
of 20 safety experts last November and December, were presented
Tuesday to members of a committee advising the government on how to
correct technical and managerial problems at its nuclear weapons
complex, which has been crippled in recent months.
   The full report was not disclosed.
   A key finding by the inspectors was insufficient training of
workers at the Rocky Flats plutonium processing facility. This was
in part due to a practice by the plant operator, Rockwell
International Corp., of letting workers switch to job assignments
outside their area of expertise, officials said.
   Oliver Lynch, a department safety official, cited an instance of
workers in a low-level waste evaporator building reading the
newspaper instead of monitoring safety indicators.
   ``This struck home the need for a greater (Department of Energy)
presence in the facility,'' said Richard W. Starostecki, deputy
assistant secretary of energy for safety, health and quality
assurance.
   He and other department officials stressed, however, that
Rockwell managers had shown a much greater willingness to improve
safety procedures at the plant, which reprocesses plutonium from old
nuclear weapons for use in new ones. He said this change in
Rockwell's attitude had emerged over the past year.
   Rockwell has made a ``noteworthy first step'' toward meeting
Energy Department concerns, he said, by developing a comprehensive
long-term strategy for safety improvements.
   The plant, situated about 16 miles from Denver, was shut down by
federal authorities last October after an incident in which three
employees were accidentally exposed to plutonium particles.
   Starostecki also reaffirmed to the advisory panel that a phased
and closely monitored restarting of the Rocky Flats plant had begun
last week. He said the plant could be in full operation as early as
late March.
   At the same briefing to the advisory panel, Starostecki said more
study will be needed to determine the severity of numerous cracks in
the cooling systems of a South Carolina reactor complex that
produces key ingredients for nuclear weapons.
   The Savannah River Plant, near Aiken, S.C., is the nation's only
source of tritium, a perishable and increasingly scarce gas vital to
making nuclear warheads.
   The three-reactor complex has not been producing tritium since
last April, when the Energy Department shut down the last active
reactor for safety reasons.
   Starostecki said an accident Sunday during testing at the
Savannah River Plant indicates ``a lack of control over what's going
on in the reactors.''
   Federal officials said there was no leakage of radiation or other
hazardous material from the incident. The operator, E.I. du Pont de
Nemours &amp; Co., estimated damage at $20,000.
   Du Pont disclosed earlier this month that it had discovered and
was monitoring 27 cooling system cracks, including 15 in the K
reactor, which it hopes to restart by the end of this year.
   John Ahearne, chairman of the Energy Department's advisory
committee on nuclear facility safety, said Starostecki told his
panel the cracking problem was ``probably not as serious as has been
suggested, but it's still an open question.''
   If the cracked pipes need to be replaced, the work could cause
further delays in restarting the reactors.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890125-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PayRaise 1stLd-Writethru f0029 01-25 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Try to Prevent 50 Percent Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with bill introduced; picks up pvs 8th graf
bg'ng, On Tuesday ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of 12 senators unveiled
legislation today that would reject a proposed 50 percent
congressional pay raise, and roll back the increase if the House
lets it become law.
   The rollback proposal is designed to give Senate pay-raise
opponents a better weapon than a simple resolution to turn down the
increase. It could keep the issue alive even if the raise goes into
effect.
   Senators are expected to overwhelmingly reject the pay raise,
while at the same time knowing that a House vote appears unlikely.
Unless both chambers reject the pay plan recommended by former
President Reagan, the raise would become law automatically on Feb. 8.
   Reagan, following the advice of a commission, recommended that
congressional salaries rise from $89,500 to $135,000 for
rank-and-file lawmakers.
   The recommendation would allow the House speaker to receive
$175,000 instead of $115,000; and would pay $155,000 to the
president pro tempore of the Senate and the majority and minority
leaders of each house _ all of whom now earn $99,500.
   Reagan also recommended 50 percent increases for top political
appointees in the executive branch and for judges.
   Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., a main sponsor of the new
legislation, said the rollback was the key provision. If the Senate
approves the legislation and sends it to the House, House opponents
of the raise could keep trying to tack it on to other bills after
Feb. 8.
   The legislation also would require a vote on all future pay
raises.
   Senate sponsors accused the House leadership of trying to duck a
vote. Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, has been non-committal, while
Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, has promised a
Senate vote.
   ``It's ridiculous not to have a vote on the pay raise,'' Sen.
Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, told reporters. ``Not only is the
amount outlandish, but it sets a pretty bad example. The public
hates the pay increase and the way it's approved.''
   Any rollback also would affect 50 percent raises for top
executive branch officials, which also were part of Reagan's
recommendation. Raises for judges were in Reagan's package also, but
cannot constitutionally be cut back once they take effect.
   The Senate sponsors of the legislation are Sens. Pressler;
Grassley; Harry Reid, D-Nev.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; John McCain,
R-Ariz.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Paul Simon, D-Ill.; Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H.; David Boren, D-Okla.; Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.;
Strom Thurmond, R-S.C. and Howell Heflin, R-Ala.
   On Tuesday, 35 House members wrote Wright to demand a vote ``out
of respect for the American taxpayer.''
   The letter, written by Rep. Robert C. Smith, R-N.H., was signed
by 30 Republicans and five Democrats. Wright had no comment.
   ``The prospect of an increase in congressional salaries has
prompted a broad range of comments, but there is one theme that is
constant,'' the letter said. ``The American people are firm in their
conviction that regardless of the legislative form, there must be a
vote on this enormous pay raise.''
   The letter said that ``avoiding this issue is not the answer.''
   Signing the letter were Democrats Mike Synar, Okla.; G.V.
``Sonny'' Montgomery, Miss.; W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, La.; Timothy J.
Penny, Minn.; and Peter A. DeFazio, Ore.
   Republicans: Thomas J. Tauke, Iowa; Robert F. Smith, Ore.; Cass
Ballenger, N.C.; Howard C. Nielson, Utah; Jim Courter, N.J.; Robert
C. Smith, N.H.; Jim Bunning, Ky.; Bob Stump, Ariz.; Peter Smith,
Vt.; Olympia J. Snow, Maine; Bill Emerson, Mo.; John J. Rhodes III,
Ariz.; James M. Inhofe, Okla.;
   Helen Delich Bentley, Md.; Dan Schaefer, Colo.; Clyde C.
Holloway, La.; Norman D. Shumway, Calif.; Jim Leach, Iowa; Larry E.
Craig, Idaho; Patricia F. Saiki, Hawaii; Virginia Smith, Neb.; Lamar
S. Smith, Texas; Craig T. James, Fla.; Michael Bilirakis, Fla.;
Chuck Douglas, N.H.; Denny Smith, Ore.; Thomas J. Ridge, Pa.; Hank
Brown, Colo.; Robert J. Lagomarsino, Calif.; and Benjamin A. Gilman,
N.Y.
