<FIRST>u f PM-TexasEastern     01-25 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Eastern,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Prepares For Visits With Possible Buyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp. officials said today they have
begun scheduling appointments with possible buyers and denied that
their claims of more than 50 suitors are meant to stall a Coastal
Corp. takeover attempt by boosting stock prices.
   ``The process is well under way,'' said Texas Eastern spokesman
Fred Wichlep. ``We have set up data rooms here in our building and
have already started making appointments with representatives of
other companies to come in and review our data and to hear
presentations by officers of the company.''
   Trading in Texas Eastern stock was suspended briefly Tuesday on
the New York Stock Exchange after a company lawyer told U.S.
District Judge Lynn N. Hughes that the natural-gas company might use
a ``white knight'' to block Coastal's $2.6 billion takeover bid.
   Texas Eastern attorney Ewing Werlein told Hughes that the company
has a list of more than 50 possible buyers.
   Officials of Coastal, another Houston-based natural-gas company,
later suggested that the comment was designed to inflate Texas
Eastern stock prices to make Coastal's offer appear inadequate.
   Texas Eastern officials said the number is legitimate and was
provided only to inform Hughes of their actions, but they
acknowledged they are trying to maximize their stock price.
   ``This is a bona fide effort in our ongoing process to determine
the maximum value of Texas Eastern stock,'' Wichlep said this
morning.
   Texas Eastern stock closed at $48.25 Tuesday, down from its
record $48.50 close Monday. Trading was suspended at 11:20 a.m.
because of an imbalance of shares on the buy side, but resumed at
12:09 p.m.
   Coastal has offered $42 per share for all outstanding Texas
Eastern shares. The company already owns 4 percent to 5 percent of
Texas Eastern's stock.
   During the three-hour hearing, Hughes denied a Texas Eastern
request to delay a Feb. 7 hearing in a Coastal lawsuit designed to
prevent Texas Eastern from using its poison pill plan and other
anti-takeover measures.
   ``It was a major victory,'' James R. Paul, Coastal's president
and chief operating officer, said today in a statement. ``Texas
Eastern's effort at delay is nothing more than a stall designed to
deny their stockholders the right to ultimately determine the
disposition of their stock.''
   Paul said his company has asked Texas Eastern for information
that would justify a higher bid, but said the only response has been
``rhetoric and a stonewall meeting last Sunday.''
   The meeting between executives of the two companies was the only
face-to-face contact since Coastal announced its takeover bid Jan.
16.
</TEXT>
