<FIRST>u f PM-ArcticRefuge 1stLd-Writethru f0030 01-25 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arctic Refuge, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0030,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Environmentalist But Favors Some Development of Arctic
Refuge</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New thruout to UPDATE with comments from Bush interview; No
Pickup; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that while he's
determined to be an environmentalist, he favors ``prudent
development'' by oil companies in the Arctic wildlife refuge.
   Commenting on an issue environmentalists say will be a litmus
test of his intentions, Bush said he believes ``we can find the
balance between environmental interests and national security
interests'' to permit some development of oil and gas resources in
the refuge.
   Environmentalists have been trying to enlist Bush's support to
keep oil companies out of the vast refuge.
   For years there has been a fierce debate in Congress and between
environmentalists and the oil companies over whether a
1.5-million-acre coastal strip of the Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge in northeastern Alaska should be opened for oil drilling.
   In the final days of the Reagan administration, Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel formally urged Congress to clear the way for
oil and gas development in the refuge and proposed a land swap deal
as the best way to do it.
   A dozen of the leading environmental and conservation groups,
including some of the movement's biggest names, urged Bush in a
letter Tuesday to review Interior's position with an eye toward
reversing the department's recommendation to Congress.
   ``We have strenuously opposed this proposal as a shortsighted
sacrifice of a national treasure for a few months of energy that is
readily procurable elsewhere,'' the groups said.
   But in an Oval Office interview with a small group of reporters
today, Bush said that brought to mind similar arguments made about
the Alaska oil pipeline.
   ``I remember the pipeline. I remember the arguments against it,''
he said. ``And I also know the effect it did not have on the
caribou.''
   Bush has said his administration intends to be a strong defender
of the environment, but also has indicated in the past that he
favors expanded oil drilling in the Arctic.
   ``I'm in favor of prudent development there,'' he said today. ``
... I think I'm determined to be an environmentalist. I am one, and
I'm concerned that we not do irreparable damage to the environment.''
   But Bush also said that ``we have some national security
interests at stake here'' in terms of making the country less
reliant on imported energy supplies.
   Congress must approve opening up any of the 19-million-acre
wildlife refuge in northeastern Alaska for drilling, and it didn't
take long for the issue to surface this year.
   On the first day of the 101st Congress, legislation was
introduced with 38 co-sponsors in the House to declare the
1.5-million-acre coastal strip of the Arctic wildlife refuge a
protected wilderness. On the same day, other legislation also was
introduced in the House to open the same land for oil and gas
development.
   The oil industry ``would like to move this fast'' and ``create a
sense of national emergency'' before environmental groups can
mobilize, suggested George Frampton Jr., president of the Wilderness
Society.
   Hodel's action last week at the end of his tenure as interior
secretary infuriated the environmental movement, which has vowed to
fight any attack on the refuge _ home for the Porcupine caribou,
polar bears and millions of birds.
   Michael Fischer, executive director of the Sierra Club, called on
Bush to intervene in ``the rush to trample the Arctic'' and said the
president's actions on Arctic development will be ``the test of this
administration'' on whether it is serious about protecting the
environment.
   Earlier in the week, many of the environmental leaders met with
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, to voice their
concern about the wildlife refuge.
   Frampton questioned the need to open the Arctic region now for
drilling when there is no need for the additional petroleum. In
future years, he suggested, technology might be developed to protect
the environment better.
   ``We can postpone the decision and have it both ways _ wilderness
and oil,'' he said.
   Other groups that signed the letter to Bush were the National
Wildlife Federation, the Izaak Walton League of America, the Natural
Resources Defense Council, National Audubon Society, National Parks
and Conservation Association, Friends of the Earth, Environmental
Policy Institute, Defenders of Wildlife and the Environmental Policy
Institute.
</TEXT>
