<DOCNO> AP890125-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-BoutiqueBeer Adv28-29   01-25 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boutique Beer, Adv 28-29,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Jan. 28-29 and thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Local Beers Gaining In Popularity Nationwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is an hour wait on weekends for a table at
the 140-seat restaurant of the Great Lakes Brewing Co. as patrons
jam the bar to guzzle European-style beer brewed on the premises.
   ``We're brewing around the clock and selling it as fast as we
make it,'' said Daniel Conway, 27, who owns the bar with his brother
Patrick.
   The brothers restored Cleveland's first tavern last September and
started brewing beer, part of a growing nationwide brewing trend as
local brewers apply their craft in ``brewpubs'' and
``microbreweries,'' offering a variety of beers to local clientele.
   Great Lakes patrons can choose from three different brews at
$2.20 a glass with names such as Eliot's Amber, named for Eliot
Ness, who frequented the bar and ran for mayor of Cleveland before
gaining fame as a lawman, said Daniel Conway.
   Brewer Thaine Johnson, who worked for Cleveland's former
Christian Schmidt Brewing Co., was persuaded to come out of
retirement and apply his skills on a smaller scale.
   Great Lakes can brew 750 to 1,000 31-gallon barrels of beer a
year, a typical amount for brewpubs which offer beer for on-premise
consumption.
   Microbreweries brew and bottle beer for regional consumption,
though the City of Angels Brewing Co., Santa Monica, Calif., which
operates a 250-seat restaurant in a revamped furniture store, hopes
to offer their ale both ways.
   ``We are hoping to offer people small plastic, resealable kegs so
people can take it home,'' said bar manager Jim Lucitt, adding the
brewpub has attracted a number of celebrities since it opened a year
ago.
   ``Michael Keaton stops in every now and then. Wilt Chamberlain
was in the other night and Magic (Johnson) stops by,'' Lucitt said.
   At the start of 1986, there were only 29 microbreweries,
breweries which produce less than 15,000 barrels a year, and
brewpubs in North America, according to the Association of Brewers,
Boulder, Colo.
   Since then, the number has doubled each year. At the start of
1989, there were 120 brewpubs and microbreweries operating in North
America, said Charlie Papazian, who founded the association in 1978
and edits the association's magazine titled Zymurgy, the branch of
chemistry dealing with fermentation.
   At the Rooster Court Bar and Grill in Northampton, Mass., patrons
can try a brown ale named Old Brown Dog or, in the summer, a light,
wheat beer, said Peter Egelston, a co-owner of the brewpub.
   ``The novelty of the beer is enough to bring people in the first
time, but not enough to bring them back,'' Egelston said.
   In Hartford, Conn., The Chester Fife &amp; Drum Corps will help usher
in Connecticut's new brew Feb. 1 when John Foley, president of the
Connecticut Brewing Co., rolls out the first barrel of Nathan Hale
Lager.
   Foley, 26, developed his interest in beer at the University of
Notre Dame where he reviewed the history of brewing for a seminar.
   After graduation, he worked in New York in invesment banking but
continued to study the market for beer and, after raising $500,000,
founded the brewing company, basing his beer on a recipe that dates
to colonial America.
   ``It's a renaissance back to pre-prohibition days when Manhattan
had over 100 breweries,'' Foley said. ``There were 4,000 breweries
in the United States in 1870 but by 1980, there were only 40 in the
country.''
   But the brewing giants of the country need not fear competition
from the new upstarts.
   The Boulder brewers' association reports microbreweries and
brewpubs brewed a total of 100,000 barrels of beer in 1987, or about
one-half percent of all beer brewed and sold in North America. That
figure increased to 120,000 in 1988 and Papazian said the
microbreweries and brewpubs may hit the 180,000-barrel mark in 1989.
   The large breweries continue to dominate the domestic beer
industry which in 1988 brewed and sold 188 million barrels of beer
in the United States, about the same amount as the year before, said
Jerry Steinman, publisher of Beer Marketer's Insights, which tracks
trends in the brewing industry from West Nyack, N.Y.
   ``You are obviously not talking about a major impact on the
industry,'' said Steinman. ``In the Northwest, some microbreweries
may have an impact on some imports and superpremiums but they are
not hurting the beer industry.''
   Beer from microbreweries and brewpubs, generally more expensive
than domestic beer, attracts the same consumers as import beers and
could have an impact on overall sales of foreign-brewed beer which
accounts for about 5 percent of beer sold in the United States,
Steinman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv weekend editions Jan. 28-29.</NOTE>
</DOC>
