<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Greenspan-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0033 01-25 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenspan-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Upbeat About Economic Prospects</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 6 grafs new with Bush quotes on economy, Federal Reserve;
picks up pvs 3rd graf bg'ng, As a ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he believes the
economy is ``reasonably stable'' and hopes the Federal Reserve Board
won't overreact to inflationary fears by driving interest rates up
further.
   Bush said in an Oval Office interview with two newspaper
reporters that he had not yet read comments that Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan made Tuesday to a House committee.
Greenspan voiced concern about inflation and said the board would
keep a tight grip on the money supply.
   Asked about this today, Bush said, ``I must say that I'm
encouraged that the markets, at least recently, have been saying
that things are reasonably stable. ... There's no signals out there
in the markets that this economy is in real trouble.''
   The president said, ``I haven't talked to Alan lately, but I
don't want to see us move so strongly against the fear of inflation
that we impede growth. We have to keep expanding opportunities for
the working men and women of this country.''
   Bush said, however, that he preferred not ``to get into
commenting on'' Greenspan's testimony.
   Greenspan told the House Banking Committee he was worried that
strains on factory capacity and a tight labor market, particularly
in the Northeast, are likely to keep inflation pressures bubbling in
the near term.
   As a result, the central bank's monetary policy should continue
on the tight side, he said.
   ``The long-run costs of a return to higher inflation, and the
risks of this occurring under current circumstances, are
sufficiently great that Federal Reserve policy at this juncture
might well be advised to err more on the side of restrictiveness
than of stimulus,'' he said.
   But, in response to questions, Greenspan also indicated that the
central bank would like to lower interest rates if it can be done at
some point without causing an acceleration in price increases.
   ``Obviously we would prefer interest rates to be lower rather
than higher all the time,'' he said.
   The stock market surged higher Tuesday, pushing the Dow Jones
industrial average for the first time back to the levels it held
just before the October 1987 market crash. Market watchers said
investor optimism about Greenspan's comments helped fuel the rally.
   ``The market reaction read it, No. 1, in the short term the Fed
will continue to tighten to ensure that inflation is under control,
but more importantly, in the longer run Greenspan leaned more in the
direction of lower interest rates,'' said John Wilson, chief
economist of the Bank of America.
   However, Greenspan's accompanying contention that economic growth
must dip below 3 percent could spell serious trouble for the
administration of President Bush, who is counting on high growth and
lower interest rates to bring the budget deficit down.
   The growth generates more tax revenue for the government, while
lower interest rates reduce the carrying costs on the $2.7 trillion
national debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
