<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Tobacco     01-25 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Tobacco,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Reports 28.5 Percent Drop In 4th-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. said Wednesday its earnings rose 26.9
percent in 1988 but fell 28.5 percent in the fourth quarter because
of a $348 million pre-tax charge to cover a restructuring at General
Foods.
   Philip Morris, the New York-based cigarette, food and brewing
giant that completed the purchase of Kraft Inc. last month, said it
earned $342 million, or $1.48 a share, in the quarter, down from
$478 million, or $2.02 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 19.9
percent to $8.64 billion from $7.2 billion.
   For the full year, Philip Morris said its earnings rose to $2.34
billion, or $10.03 a share, from $1.84 billion, or $7.75 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose 12.6 percent to $31.7 billion from $28.2
billion.
   The charge at General Foods USA and General Foods Worldwide
Coffee &amp; International covered the closing of a Jell-O plant in
Lafayette, Ind., and other streamlining moves, including layoffs.
Excluding that charge, fourth-quarter earnings would have risen 15.9
percent.
   Philip Morris said its acquisition of Kraft on Dec. 7, 1988,
reduced its earnings by about $28 million, including financing costs
and amortization of goodwill. But adoption of a new method of
accounting for income taxes boosted net earnings for 1988 by $213
million.
   Kraft contributed $821 million in operating revenue to Philip
Morris since its early-December acquisition. However, the Kraft
purchase also boosted Philip Morris's debt by $10.6 billion,
including $1 billion that was on Kraft's books.
   ``As was the case when we acquired General Foods three years ago,
we are assuming large additional debt,'' Hamish Maxwell, the
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
   ``We are confident of our ability to service this
acquisition-related debt and to pay it down over the next few years,
as well as to sustain a good growth in earnings, volume and market
shares in 1989 and beyond,'' Maxwell said.
   Among individual market segments, Philip Morris said revenue rose
11.3 percent to $8.5 billion at Philip Morris USA; rose 15.4 percent
to $8.1 billion at Philip Morris International; rose 9.8 percent to
$3.8 billion at General Foods USA; rose ``slightly'' to $4.4 billion
at General Foods Worldwide Coffee &amp; International; rose 5 percent to
$2.3 billion at Oscar Mayer Foods; and rose 5.1 percent to $3.3
billion at Miller Brewing Co.
</TEXT>
