<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Amex     01-25 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Amex,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Express Reports Profit For Quarter, Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. reported Wednesday that it
made a profit in the fourth quarter following a year-earlier loss
while earnings for all of 1988 nearly doubled.
   The company attributed the improvement to record income in the
divisions that run its credit card and financial services businesses
and to a rebound in earnings from its bank following an easing of
the Third World debt crisis.
   However, its brokerage firm, Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings
Inc., lost money in the final quarter and suffered a decline in
annual income.
   American Express said net income totaled $231 million, or 54
cents a share, in the three months ended Dec. 31, compared with a
$104 million loss in the 1987 quarter. Revenue jumped 34 percent, to
$6.3 billion from $4.8 billion.
   The 1987 quarter included a $350 million after-tax provision for
loan losses at American Express Bank and $46 million in tax benefits
from new accounting rules.
   For the year, American Express netted $1.04 billion, or $2.43 a
share, compared with earnings of $533 million, or $1.20 a share, in
1987. Revenue totaled $22.9 billion, up 30 percent from $17.7
billion in the previous year.
   Chairman James D. Robinson III said the latest quarterly and
annual results ``demonstrated our leadership position in travel and
financial services.''
   ``Two of our four business units reported record income for the
year,'' Robinson noted in a statement. ``Travel Related Services led
the way with record earnings in 1988, capping a decade in which
profits compounded at more than 17 percent a year.''
   At the Travel Related Services division, which runs the credit
card and travelers checks business, quarterly earnings climbed 18
percent to $184 million from $155 million. For the year, it earned a
record $773 million, up 18 percent from 1987 income of $655 million.
Revenue in 1988 rose 22 percent to $7.4 billion.
   During the year, credit-card charge volume climbed 18 percent to
a record $89 billion, partly reflecting additional services offered
to cardmembers.
   Travelers checks sales also rose in 1988, to $23.5 billion from
$22 billion.
   IDS Financial Services posted a 20 percent jump in quarterly
earnings to a record $41 million from $34 million, American Express
said. For the year, the division netted $148 million, up 19 percent
from $124 million earned in 1987.
   The company said sales of securities, annuity and investment
certificates led the increase.
   American Express Bank earned $47 million in the quarter, compared
with a loss of $296 million in 1987, when it added to its loan-loss
provision to cover shaky Third World debt. For the year it earned
$149 million, compared with a previous-year loss of $625 million.
   The company said that last year it reduced its exposure to Third
World loans by about 46 percent.
   American Express had reported Tuesday that Shearson Lehman
narrowed its fourth-quarter loss to $13.5 million from $95 million
in the 1987. Its annual income totaled $96 million, or 81 cents a
share, down 5 percent from $101 million, or $1 a share, in 1987.
   The company said the unit was still faced with expenses from the
acquisition of E.F. Hutton Inc. in January 1988.
</TEXT>
