<FIRST>r f BC-Norway-Statoil     01-25 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Norway-Statoil,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Statoil To Cut Jobs, Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAVANGER, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway's government-owned oil company,
Statoil, Wednesday proposed an early retirement program and a
continued hiring freeze in an effort to trim 2 billion kronor, or
$300 million, from its annual operating costs.
   The company said it also may reduce and defer investments ``and
is considering whether to sell or exchange offshore equities.''
   The proposals were prepared for a meeting of the board of
directors, a company statement said.
   ``Such cuts are in line with what we expected,'' said Oil and
Energy Minister Arne Oeien, welcoming the company's move.
   Statoil, which has been hit by the fall in North Sea oil prices,
said its three-year goal was to reduce manpower by 1,500 man-years,
or about 14 percent.
   It also would reduce the work given to outside consultants or
temporary employees. Retirement will be offered to anyone who has
turned 60 by this year.
   The layoff of personnel will depend on how successul the
cost-cutting program is, the statement said.
</TEXT>
