<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grains and soybeans were mostly
lower Wednesday at the close on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``There was no significant business in Japan or Europe to cause
any buying today,'' said Jerry Zusel, manager of CBOT floor
operations for Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Soybean prices pulled back _ as much as 14{ cents on the spot
March contract _ because European markets didn't follow through with
Tuesday's rally in Chicago and it appears the recent spurt of
commercial buying has been completed, said Dale Gustafson, a grains
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Wheat prices were weighed down by the rainy weather forecast for
the Great Plains growing areas and a slackening of U.S. wheat
exports, said Gustafson.
   Corn futures were lower in sympathy with the decline in wheat and
soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was } cent higher to 2} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.38{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 2} cents lower, with March at $2.70 a bushel; oats were 9{ cents
to 10 cents lower, with March at $2.25\ a bushel; and soybeans were
2\ cent to 14{ cents lower with March at $7.53 a bushel.
