<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-StockProbe     01-25 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Stock Probe,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Investigating Possible Stock Market Drug Connection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is investigating reports that
Mexico's stock market has been involved in laundering drug money, a
top official said Wednesday.
   Assistant Attorney General Javier Coello Trejos said the
government is looking into the movement of a reported $20 million in
drug money through banks in Mexico and the United States. He did not
name any banks.
   ``We will be implacable in finding all of those who launder money
for drug traffickers. It's dirty money. It's money made by poisoning
humanity. We are investigating daily,'' he told reporters.
   Last June, the director of the stock exchange and its operations
chief resigned in a scandal in which $7 million in investors' money
vanished through what were called administrative irregularities.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo was quoted in
Wednesday's editions of the Mexico City daily La Jornada as saying
his department would investigate whether drug money was involved in
last year's stock market scandal.
</TEXT>
