<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Disney     01-25 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Disney,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney's Quarterly Profit Up 48 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. said Wednesday its
quarterly profit rose 48 percent, bouyed by sales of ``Cinderella''
in home video and by strong performances at its amusement parks.
   Disney said it earned $148.3 million, or $1.08 a share, in its
first quarter, ended Dec. 31, up from $100.4 million, or 73 cents a
share, in the same period a year earlier. Sales in the quarter were
$1.04 billion, up from $734.6 million a year earlier.
   The Burbank-based entertainment company said both the profit and
sales figures were a record for its first quarter.
   First-quarter sales in Disney's theme parks and resorts division
rose to $511.6 million from $385.7 million a year earlier.
   Disney won't disclose attendance figures at Disneyland and Disney
World, but said results in the division were boosted by ``excellent
attendance'' and higher per-guest spending at its amusement parks
and resorts.
   First-quarter revenue in Disney's filmed entertainment segment
rose 38 percent, to $409.9 million from $297.8 million a year
earlier. The company attributed the rise to the popularity of such
movies as ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' and particularly to strong
sales of ``Cinderella'' in home video.
   The consumer products segment, growing as the company opens more
stores to sell Disney toys, clothes and memorabilia, had sales of
$122 million, up from $51 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
