<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped against most major currencies
Wednesday after the Federal Reserve again cut short a modest rally
with a round of dollar-selling.
   The Federal Reserve apparently acted alone, traders said, in
contrast to previous trading sessions in which the big European
central banks also sold dollars.
   The single-handed intervention, executed near the end of Europe's
trading day, was nevertheless successful in keeping the dollar in
check.
   ``It seemed to have a lot of effect for what was actually done.
The market has gotten edgy lately. Central banks have managed to
create an attitude of apprehension amongst traders who otherwise
would have been buying new dollars,'' said Frank Watson, a vice
president at Swiss Bank Corp. in New York.
   Some traders who are bullish toward the dollar said they would
wait for Friday's publication of U.S. preliminary gross national
product figures for the fourth quarter before attempting to bid up
the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.70 Japanese yen to a closing 127.65 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 127.75 yen. In New York the dollar fell to
127.43 yen from 127.70 yen late Tuesday.
   In London, the British pound rose against the dollar to $1.7710
from $1.7700 late Tuesday. Later in New York the pound rose to
$1.7708 from $1.7690 Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8405 West German marks, down from 1.8415; 1.5630
Swiss francs, up from 1.5607; 1.1841 Canadian dollars, up from
1.822; 6.2553 French francs, down from 6.2617; and 1,345.5 Italian
lire, down from 1,347.5.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.8435 West German marks, up from 1.8395; 1.5670 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5523; 6.2715 French francs, up from 6.2335; 2.0820
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0680; 1,350.50 Italian lire, up from
1,340.50; and 1.1840 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1866.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $404.25 a troy ounce from
$407 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold fell to a bid
$404.25 from $407.10 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.42 to close at a bid $406.57.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed unchanged at $406 an ounce. Later, Republic National
Bank of New York said gold bullion edged up to $405.25 from $404.80.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market, where the metal
was trading at a late bid of $6.12 a troy ounce, compared with $6.21
bid late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $6.17 a troy ounce from $6.13 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
