<FIRST>u f AM-Champion-Dana 2ndLd-Writethru   01-25 0915</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Champion-Dana, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0945</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dana To Buy Champion Spark Plug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 13-20, Echlin Inc. ..., to include reax from
Echlin and industry analyst; UPDATES grafs 7-8 with final stock prices.
Note that Champion stock price in pvs version was NYSE only, sted consolidated.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dana Corp., a giant auto parts company, would
buy 82-year-old Champion Spark Plug Co. for about $600 million in
cash and stock under an agreement between the companies' managements
announced Wednesday.
   Investors pushed Champion's stock above Dana's offering price,
indicating the belief that a higher offer might emerge from Dana or
another bidder.
   The deal, which must be approved by Champion's shareholders,
would end the independence of the spark plug maker that has been
controlled by the Stranahan family since its founding in 1907.
   The two Toledo-based companies said the merger would unite
Champion's famous name with Dana's far-flung distribution system.
   Although not as well known as Champion, Dana is a bigger company,
with 1987 sales of $4.9 billion. It makes a variety of automotive
parts, including drive-train components, engine parts and chassis
products.
   Champion had sales of $554 million through the first nine months
of 1988.
   Champion's stock, already boosted by speculation of a merger,
rose 25 centsre in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading to
$18 a share, above Dana's offering price of $17.50 a share in cash
and stock.
   Dana fell $1.37{ a share in consolidated NYSE trading to $38.37{
a share.
   Under terms of the deal, Dana will make a $17.50-a-share cash
tender offer by Feb. 1 for 17.3 million shares of Champion common
stock, or about 50.1 percent of the stock on a fully diluted basis,
Champion spokesman Anthony Mougey said.
   After the merger the rest of Champion's stock would be exchanged
for cash or Dana stock with a value of $17.50 a share, with an
overall limit that no more than half of Champion's shares will be
bought for cash, the companies said.
   ``The combination of Dana and Champion will allow us to serve the
automotive, industrial and aviation markets with a unique
combination of well-recognized brand names and a distribution system
which is second to none,'' said Southwood Morcott, president of
Dana, a Toledo-based automotive parts company.
   O. Lee Henry, Champion's president and chief executive officer,
said the sale will strengthen both companies.
   ``Dana brands are very well respected in the marketplace, and the
Dana distribution system is state-of-the-art. We are looking forward
to working together and capitalizing on the strengths we each bring
to the combination,'' Henry said.
   Echlin Inc., a Branford, Conn. automotive parts company, had
reportedly made a bid to buy Champion last week, a rumor denied by
both companies. Echlin three years ago said it was interested in
purchasing Champion.
   Paul Ryder, Echlin's director of investor relations, declined
comment on whether the company would make an offer to buy Champion.
   ``Even if we were considering it I wouldn't be able to disclose
that information,'' he said.
   William Prebe, an auto industry analyst and former Dana vice
president and corporate economist, said the $17.50-a-share offer is
below what he believes the company's worth.
   ``We were looking for something in the neighborhood of $20, up to
$22-a share offer. The price suggests that it was a very friendly
composition between Dana and Champion,'' he said.
   Prebe said it is possible another company would make an counter
offer to buy Champion.
   ``You still have the bulk of the shares still traded on Wall
Street. If somebody wants to come in and get the remaining shares,
it would be a dirty fight that would raise the stock,'' he said.
   ``Now is the nervous time for the guy sitting on the sidelines.
He is thinking, `Should I take the $17.50 or go along with something
higher?' If nothing higher comes along and he hasn't taken the
$17.50, it may drop the stock down to $14, $15 dollars-a-share,'' he
said.
   Market interest in Champion increased with reports that members
of Chinook Partners L.P., holder of 35 percent of Champion's common
stock, might dissolve the partnership.
   Chinook was founded three years ago when descendants of the
company's founders, Frank and Robert Stranahan, decided to pool
their holdings to maintain a dominant voice in Champion's affairs.
   The Stranahan family members set an expiration date for the
partnership of April 1, 1989, and analysts speculated that the
younger generation of the family was pushing to divest some of their
holdings.
   Champion's board of directors met in Toledo on Friday to discuss
what it would do if the Stranahans dissolved their family
partnership. The Chinook members met afterward. Neither group would
comment on the meetings.
   David Kubicki, a United Auto Workers union international
representative, said he was surprised by the deal.
   ``It's difficult to really digest what has taken place and what
the outcome and the future is going to be between the two parties,''
said Kubicki, a former UAW unit chairman at Dana's Toledo plant,
which has 340 workers.
   Champion earned $14.5 million, or 41 cents a share, on $554
million in sales during the first nine months of 1988, compared to
$12.9 million, or 34 cents a share, on sales of $535 million in the
same period of 1987.
   Champion, which makes spark plugs and other automotive products,
employs about 10,000 people worldwide, including 2,250 workers at
its five U.S. and Canadian plants.
   Dana has 700 operations in 27 countries and employs about 35,000
workers.
</TEXT>
