<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Oil     01-25 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Oil,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shell, Texaco Report Modest Fourth-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s 1988 fourth-quarter earnings rebounded from a
multibillion dollar loss a year earlier, and Shell Oil Co.'s
fourth-quarter earnings tumbled 51.4 percent from a year earlier,
the petroleum giants said Wednesday.
   Texaco reported net income of $296 million, or $1.21 a share, in
the period, vs. a $4.67 billion in losses a year earlier attributed
to a restructuring and the settlement of a lawsuit with Pennzoil Co.
   Shell said earnings fell to $212 million in the quarter, down
from $436 million in the same 1987 period. The company does not
release per-share figures because it is a subsidiary of Royal Dutch
Shell based in The Netherlands.
   Shell President Frank Richardson said a recent rise in crude oil
prices helped exploration and production performance but put
pressure on refining and marketing costs.
   For the quarter ending Dec. 31, Texaco reported revenue of $8.47
billion, down 9.6 percent from $9.36 billion in revenue in the 1987
quarter.
   For the full year, the nation's third-largest oil company
reported earnings of $1.3 billion, or $5.35 a share, on revenue of
$35.1 billion, compared with losses of $4.14 billion on revenue of
$35.3 billion in 1987.
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., said results from
exploration and production in 1988 were hurt by low crude prices for
most of the year and the loss of production in the North Sea after a
July platform explosion and fire.
   But financial results linked to oil refining and marketing were
positive because of lower crude oil acquisition costs, Texaco
President James W. Kinnear said.
   Houston-based Shell, the nation's sixth-largest oil company, said
revenues for the quarter were $5.5 billion, down 7.2 percent from
the $5.9 billion for the same year-ago period.
   For the year, Shell had net income of $1.24 billion, a slight
increase from the $1.23 billion in 1987. The annual earnings
included a positive $35 million cumulative effect from prior years
for accounting changes made in 1988, primarily for income taxes and
capitalization of interest.
   Revenues for all of 1988 were $21.4 billion, compared with $21.2
billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
