<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f AM-U-Haul Adv29   01-25 1068</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-U-Haul, Adv 29,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Jan. 29 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sibs Battle For Move-It-Yourself Empire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Harvard-educated brothers are
struggling for control of the U-Haul rental empire founded by their
father, who pioneered the self-trucking idea at the end of World War
II and parlayed it into one of the country's biggest family-run
businesses.
   The squabble has made Samuel W. ``Sam'' Shoen and Edward J.
``Joe'' Shoen look like the Bobby and J.R. Ewing of do-it-yourself
moving. Both have allies among their 10 siblings and have sued each
other in state and federal courts.
   At stake is the destiny of an operation with about 13,000
employees, $1 billion in annual revenue and a rental fleet of more
than 100,000 trailers and 64,000 trucks, emblazoned with the
orange-and-gray U-Haul logo commonly seen on interstates nationwide.
   The faction led by Joe Shoen, a 40-year-old attorney with a
Harvard MBA, currently runs U-Haul and its parent company, Amerco,
which also has interests in other rental equipment, self-storage
facilities and insurance. The company is incorporated in Nevada but
most of its operations are based in Arizona.
   Joe Shoen and his allies won control via a stock maneuver last
summer that gave them 53 percent voting power, partly through the
issuance of shares to non-family executives who were on their side.
   The rival faction is led by Sam Shoen, 43, a physician who also
has an MBA from Harvard. He quit as company president last summer
because of frustration with family squabbling.
   He has since challenged the legality of his younger brother's
stock maneuver, calling it a shabby move that cheated him and other
shareholders.
   Sam Shoen's group is supported by patriarch Leonard S. Shoen, 71,
who had always wanted his eldest son to run U-Haul and has expressed
dismay at what is happening to his family and the business under Joe
Shoen's hand.
   He now believes the entire company should be sold and knows of a
buyer willing to pay $1 billion, he said in an interview. He
wouldn't identify the buyer.
   ``My son Joe, I think, is incompetent,'' the U-Haul founder told
The Associated Press by telephone this past week from his home in
Las Vegas. ``I'm not very pleased with his behavior.''
   Sam Shoen said in an interview that his father was a genius who
had taken the company through four decades of impressive growth,
only to be undone by his children's rivalries.
   ``There's nothing very mysterious here,'' Sam Shoen said. ``I'm
not going to imply that anybody has these particular problems, but
the problems are power, control and greed.''
   He said Leonard Shoen's weakness was the generosity that had
prompted him to give each of his 12 children shares amounting to 95
percent of the stock in Amerco.
   ``My father had a dream, and his dream was that he would create
this company, which he did, pass it on to his children, which he
did, and that the children would work together, which they did for a
time, and that it would be passed on to his grandchildren.
   ``It was a wonderful dream, but I don't know of a single case
where it's ever worked, not with the kind of ownership dispersion we
have,'' Sam Shoen said.
   The company's leadership is now so convoluted, he said, that he
also wants to sell it despite what he called the sentimental value
attached to his father's American success story.
   Gary V. Klinefelter, Amerco's secretary and general counsel,
declined to arrange interviews with Joe Shoen or other members of
the controlling faction until the outcome of court proceedings. But
Klinefelter claimed Joe Shoen's move to take control was crucial for
the company's survival.
   Leonard Shoen struck a responsive chord in the American psyche in
1945, introducing a fleet of rental trailers about the time many
soldiers and sailors were returning home and looking for jobs around
the country.
   For many years U-Haul grew with almost no competition, operating
out of franchised service stations. In 1968, Shoen moved from
Ridgefield, Wash., where he started U-Haul, to the Southwest, basing
the key operations in Phoenix.
   Things started to get tougher for him in 1973, when the oil
crisis crimped vehicle use. Meanwhile, the U-Haul fleet was aging,
zoning laws began restricting the location of rental trailers, and
competitors began muscling in on the company's dominance.
   Complicating matters were the Shoen descendants themselves, who
by this decade had started vying for voices in the company. Unable
to control it anymore, the father retired in the fall of 1986. Some
say he was forced out by vindictive children.
   In Klinefelter's view, Joe Shoen helped save the business by
reducing the average vehicle age to 7 years from 17 years, doubling
the number of North American dealers to 7,500, scrapping a
money-losing, full-service moving van venture and introducing a new
1-ton Toyota pickup truck rental.
   The parent company is en route to record profits of $50 million
on $1 billion in revenues for the 1988 fiscal year that began last
April 1, Klinefelter said.
   The Shoen family ties had eroded long before the squabbling
turned legal, he said.
   ``This has been a very decentralized family,'' he said. ``The
range of ages of these children is 21 to 43, with two different
mothers. Then there is a minor child by a third mother.''
   Sam Shoen said his brother's group had done nothing unusual or
innovative. He claimed their father started the modernization.
   ``The whole thing is a process,'' he said. ``It's just replacing
older vehicles with newer ones.''
   The underlying dispute, he said, ``is whether a minority of
shareholders can issue stock to disenfranchise a majority. It's that
simple.''
   Despite the Shoen family feud, the company hasn't been hurt, at
least not yet, securities analysts who follow transportation
companies say.
   ``I don't think there is any linkage between the family squabbles
and the company's customer bases and demand for their product,''
said Thomas Trantum, who follows a key U-Haul competitor, Ryder
System Inc., for the J.C. Bradford &amp; Co. investment concern.
   ``Customers are interested in the state of the equipment and the
price,'' Trantum said. ``They just want to move from here to there.
You just go to a couple of outlets, check the prices and give the
tires a kick. Then you take the best deal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Jan. 29</NOTE>
