<FIRST>r f AM-NewsweekPresident     01-25 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newsweek President,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Resigns as President of Newsweek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Newsweek Inc., Christopher M.
Little, has resigned unexpectedly to become president of Cowles
Magazines Inc., which publishes history magazines and books, it was
announced Wednesday.
   Little, 47, had been president of Newsweek for the past 2{ years,
and said he is taking the new job because of his interest in history
and the chance to live closer to his Virginia farm. His resignation
is effective March 1.
   The Washington Post Co., parent of Newsweek, named no replacement
for Little.
   ``I am surprised and disappointed to lose this able manager and
colleague who has accomplished so much for Newsweek,'' said Richard
D. Simmons, president of Washington Post Co.
   Simmons said operating profits at Newsweek, a weekly
newsmagazine, rose dramatically in 1988 and that circulation is at
the highest level in history. Newsweek circulation rose to 3.315
million in 1988, up from 3.097 million when Little took over as
president.
   Little joined Washington Post Co. in 1976 as a lawyer for the
Washington Post newspaper, and later became publisher of The Herald,
the company's newspaper in Everett, Wash.
   He moved to Newsweek as chief financial officer five years ago
and was named president of Newsweek in 1986, succeeding Mark
Edmiston who resigned.
   Simmons said Gerard Smith, Newsweek vice chairman, and Howard W.
Smith, publisher, would report to him.
   Cowles Magazines, based in Harrisburg, Pa., publishes 14
magazines, including 10 history titles with combined circulation
exceeding 1 million. It also owns National Historical Society, which
publishes history books.
   Cowles Magazines is a unit of Cowles Media Co., a Minneapolis
concern controlled by the Cowles family trust.
   In a telephone interview, Little said Cowles executives
approached him about whether he would be interested in the job.
Cowles Magazines president Jim Keough recently resigned.
   Little, who said he is a history buff, said the job will enable
him to live closer to his farm in Highland County, Virginia.
   ``I'm not somebody principally interested in prestige or
necessarily even money,'' he said.
   Little said his decision to leave Newsweek has nothing to do with
periodic speculation that Washington Post was considering selling
Newsweek.
   Little said Post officials have no such plans. Guyon Knight, a
spokesman for Washington Post, said the periodic sale rumors ``are
totally untrue.''
</TEXT>
