<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Steel     01-25 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Steel,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Reports Fourth Quarter Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. Wednesday reported an 8
percent decline in fourth-quarter earnings, largely because of costs
associated with rehabilating one plant and selling or shutting down
others.
   Specialty steelmaker Lukens Inc., meanwhile, said Wednesday it
enjoyed the best three months in company history with a 46 percent
increase in fourth-quarter earnings from $6.6 million, or 78 cents
per share, to $9.6 million, or $1.12 per share.
   Fourth-quarter earnings for Bethlehem, the nation's third-largest
steelmaker, fell from $71.5 million, or $1.07 per share, in 1987 to
$65.7 million, or 79 cents per share. Sales climbed 10 percent from
$1.20 billion to $1.33 billion.
   Bethlehem charged $35 million against fourth-quarter earnings to
reflect increased operating costs at its Burns Harbor plant in
Indiana, where it rehabilitated a blast furnace.
   The company also took a $55 million charge to reflect losses on
the sale of its remaining Kentucky coal operations and for costs
associated with previous plant shutdowns.
   In 1988, a good year throughout the steel industry, the company
earned $403 million, or $4.32 per share, up from $174.3 million, or
$2.77 per share, in 1987. Sales rose from $4.62 billion to $5.49
billion.
   Bethlehem lost a total of more than $2 billion in the five years
from 1982 through 1986.
   Lukens' quarterly sales rose 16.5 percent from $133.5 million to
$155.6 million.
   The Coatesville, Pa. company also set records with annual profits
of $33.4 million, or $3.91 per share, up 54 percent from $21.6
million, or $2.58 per share in 1987. Sales rose 20 percent from
$505.2 million to $605.3 million.
   ``Healthy shipments, near-capacity operating rates and increased
transaction prices more than offset rising scrap prices,'' said
Lukens Chairman W.R. Wilson.
   Bethlehem Chairman Walter F. Williams predicted a profitable
first quarter this year but no surge in demand.
   ``We anticipate that steel consumption will remain relatively
flat, and domestic steel shipments will decline since customers are
not expected to build steel inventories as they did in 1988,'' he
said.
   Williams projected 1989 industry shipments at 77 million tons,
down from the estimated 83 million tons shipped in 1988.
   ``We face a number of issues in 1989 which must be satisfactorily
resolved if we are to continue our progress in achieving sustained
profitability and rebuilding a sound financial base,'' Williams said.
   ``We must negotiate a ... new agreement which will permit
Bethlehem to continue to remain competitive with other steel
producers both domestic and foreign,'' Williams said.
   Bethlehem's contract with the United Steelworkers union expires
July 21.
   The major producers are also pressing President Bush to fulfill
his promise to renew the five-year voluntary steel import quotas due
to expire in September.
   ``We are relying on that commitment,'' Williams said. ``The basic
international conditions that required the policy _ excessive global
capacity in steel and unfair trade in our market _ have not been
corrected.''
   He said a five-year extension of the policy is essential.
   ``The steel industry has not yet achieved an adequate and
sustained level of profitability,'' Williams said.
</TEXT>
