<FIRST>u f AM-HomeSales 1stLd-Writethru f0130 01-25 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0130,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Sales Reach Highest Level in Nine Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to FIX garble; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, ``For
the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes last year
hit their highest level since 1979 as buyers shopped in lower price
ranges rather than leave the market when costs rose, a real estate
trade group said Wednesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said 3.63 million homes were
sold in 1988, up 2.9 percent from 1987 when 3.53 million homes had
been sold. It was the highest sales volume since 3.83 million homes
were sold in 1979.
   Sales shot up 11.4 percent in December to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 4.09 million units. It was the highest month-to-month
increase since an 11.6 percent rise in April 1986.
   ``For the most part, people seem to be buying less-expensive
homes,'' said Ira Gribin, president of the Realtors group. ``The
demand is there. People still appear to be going for the most they
can afford. They just can't afford as much.''
   Home prices slipped slightly to $87,700 in December compared with
a median sales price of $88,000 in November. Prices averaged $89,100
for all of 1988, a 4.1 percent increase from the previous year, when
the median sales price was $85,600.
   ``The strong sales volume of December, combined with a decline in
prices from November and overall modest price increases for the
year, suggest that the demand for home ownership is being fulfilled
at the lower end of the market,'' said John Tuccillo, chief
economist for the Realtors.
   He predicted similar buying patterns this year, but cautioned
that with mortgage interest rates expected to continue rising,
``economic conditions are not favorable to draw a large volume of
sales.''
   Interest on fixed-rate mortgages averaged 10.71 percent last
week, according to a national survey by the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp.
   Economist Mark Obrinsky of the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions credited the strong 1988 home sales to the general
health of the nation's economy.
   ``There is an underlying demand for housing that's fueled by
visions of home ownership but also by the economic reality of an
economy still in its expansion phase,'' he said. ``Relatively good
economic conditions are, at bottom, what's responsible for a fairly
strong level of homes sales despite slightly higher interest rates.''
   He predicted there would be a slight decline in home sales during
1989 as interest rates continue to rise early in the year and
economic growth slows later in the year.
   Prices were up in 1988 in all regions of the country, with the
fastest rate increase coming in the West, where prices rose 9.3
percent from 1987 to reach a median of $123,700 last year.
   The Northeast continued to have the highest sales prices of any
region, a median of $143,100 in 1988, up 7.4 percent from a year
earlier.
   Home prices rose 2.4 percent in the South to a median of $82,300
in 1988, while prices were up 3.5 percent in the Midwest to a median
of $68,300.
   The 11.4 percent sales increase nationwide in December followed
two months where sales held even at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 3.67 million units.
   Tuccillo said the figures revealed a shift in purchases from the
more expensive Northeast to less-costly markets in the Midwest and
South.
   December's increase in sales was led by a 15.8 percent increase
in the South, where sales ose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.61 million homes. Sales were up 10.4 percent in the Midwest,
where an economic revival is under way, to an annual rate of 1.06
million homes.
   In the West, sales rose 4.5 percent to 690,000 units, and sales
were up 4.4 percent in the Northeast to 710,000 dwellings.
</TEXT>
