<FIRST>u f AM-SmithKline     01-25 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SmithKline,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Of SmithKline Beckman Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. said Wednesday its
president has resigned amid differences over the direction of the
giant health care company at a time it is faced with sagging sales
of its blockbuster ulcer drug and takeover rumors.
   George W. Ebright's resignation coincided with the release of
SmithKline's earnings, which showed a 60 percent drop in the
company's 1988 profit.
   Ebright's resignation is effective immediately, the company said.
His duties will be assumed by Henry Wendt, SmithKline's chairman and
chief executive officer.
   ``George and I have had differences on matters of corporate
policy. Nevertheless, I accept his resignation with deep regret,''
Wendt said in a prepared statement. He added that Ebright ``has
played a major role in the diversification of SmithKline Beckman and
the building of our businesses.''
   SmithKline said its fourth-quarter net income rose 12 percent to
$159.4 million, or $1.28 a share, from $141.9 million, or $1.14 a
share in the year-earlier quarter. Revenue rose to $1.3 billion from
$1.2 billion in the 1987 period.
   The fourth-quarter figures were bolstered by income from the
partial spinnoff of Beckman Instruments, which brought in $46.1
million, the company said.
   Analysts said Ebright's abrupt resignation probably stemmed from
differences with Wendt over the future direction of the company.
   ``Mr. Ebright was probably in favor of retaining control at the
top and Mr. Wendt was probably in favor of more independence of the
units,'' said Ronald M. Nordmann, a stock analyst with PaineWebber.
   Ebright, who also was chief operating officer, stood to loose
responsibility with any independence given to the individual units,
Nordmann said.
   Ebright, 51, who became president April 1987, joined the company
in 1963 in the accounting department. Wendt, 55, became chairman the
same month, 32 years after joining SmithKline's international
marketing division.
   SmithKline ``has strong managers in place at the corporate level
and in our operating units, and I am confident of their ability to
lead our business into the future,'' Wendt said.
   Management has been under fire from critics who charge SmithKline
has failed to introduce a follow-up to its leading prescription
ulcer medication, Tagamet, as it has faced increased competition
from London-based Glaxo Holdings's Zantac.
   On the year, SmithKline's profit fell 60 percent to $229.2
million, or $1.84 a share, from $570.1 million, or $4.50 a share,
the company reported. Its sales rose 10 percent to $4.7 billion from
$4.3 billion in 1987.
   The yearly figures included a $389.3 million charge associated
with a corporate restructuring announced in September.
   Pharmaceutical sales were down 14 percent in the fourth quarter,
with Tagamet and high-blood pressure medication Dyazide sales
described as being down ``sharply.'' Tagamet's sales for the year
were $1.020 billion.
   A number of Wall Street analysts have labled SmithKline a
takeover target and, largely on the basis of rumors of an imminent
offer, its stock has fluctuated widely in the past months.
   The company's stock price was up 12.5 cents to 50| Tuesday and in
early trading today went up $1.25. The company's breakup value has
been estimated at $75 to $91 per share.
   The restructuring announced in September was viewed by many
analysts as an attempt to fend off possible suitors.
   But many said the partial spinoff of Beckman Instruments was not
enough and Wendt hinted in September that similar steps might be
applied to their Allergan and SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories
subsidiaries.
   The company has said partial spinoffs would focus stock market
attention on the value of the subsidiaries and, thus, increase
SmithKline's value.
   Analysts said today's resignation likely signals more partial
spinoffs within the corporation. Allergan and SmithKline Bio-Science
Laboratories are likely candidates for such a move.
</TEXT>
