<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Scotus-GAF     01-25 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-GAF,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marshall Allows Resumption of GAF Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice on Wednesday allowed
the resumption of a stock manipulation trial of GAF Corp. and its
vice chairman.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall lifted an order he issued Sunday that
temporarily halted the trial.
   GAF, based in Wayne, N.J., and Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin are
accused by the federal government of attempting to manipulate the
common stock of Union Carbide Corp. in advance of GAF's planned sale
of a large block of Carbide stock in November 1986.
   A trial in the case began in December in New York City but ended
in a mistrial on a motion by defense lawyers. U.S. District Judge
Mary Johnson Lowe ruled that a prosecutor improperly, but
unintentionally, withheld a report that key evidence had been
altered.
   A retrial began last week. But while jury selection was under
way, lawyers for GAF asked Marshall to block it on grounds that the
defendants' double jeopardy rights against being tried twice for the
same alleged crime were violated.
   Marshall, in an unusual move, ordered an interruption in the jury
selection Sunday while he studied arguments on the double jeopardy
issue. He issued a brief order Wednesday withdrawing the earlier
order.
   The Justice Department argued that retrying GAF and Sherwin is
permitted under a 1982 Supreme Court ruling that said double
jeopardy rights are violated in such cases only when the prosecution
intends to provoke a defendant into seeking a mistrial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
