<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasEastern-Coastal     01-25 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Eastern-Coastal,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal Chief Says Texas Eastern Fighting for Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. official James R. Paul said
Wednesday that Texas Eastern Corp.'s invitation to possible buyers
is a ploy to delay Coastal's attempted $260 billion takeover bid and
that the company's main goal is to remain independent.
   ``I think they're stalling to see whether they can find another
alternative and they're holding some remote hope of remaining
independent. I think their principal objective has been to remain
independent,'' said Paul, president and chief operating officer at
Coastal.
   ``They talk about studying the idea of auctioning the company,
but they haven't said they're going to do it. In fact, to date they
haven't taken any specific action except to stall,'' Paul said.
   However, Texas Eastern officials said Wednesday they already have
started scheduling appointments witth possible buyers, and denied
Paul's suggestion that their contacts with more than 50 possible
suitors is meant to delay a Coastal takeover by propping up stock
prices.
   ``The process is well under way,'' said Texas Eastern spokesman
Fred Wichlep. ``We have set up data rooms here in our building and
have already started making appointments with representatives of
other companies to come in and review our data and to hear
presentations by officers of the company,'' he said.
   Trading in Texas Eastern was suspended briefly on the New York
Stock Exchange Tuesday after a company lawyer told U.S. District
Judge Lynn N. Hughes the company might use a ``white knight'' to
block the Coastal bid and has a list of more than 50 possible buyers.
   Coastal officials later suggested that the comment was designed
to inflate stock prices and make their $42-a-share offer appear
inadequate.
   Texas Eastern officials say the number is legitimate and was
provided in court only to inform Hughes of their actions, but they
acknowledge that they are trying to maximize stock values.
   ``This is a bona fide effort in our ongoing process to determine
the maximum value of Texas Eastern stock,'' Wichlep said Wednesday.
   During the three-hour court hearing Tuesday, Hughes denied a
Texas Eastern request to delay a Feb. 7 hearing date in a Coastal
lawsuit designed to prevent Texas Eastern from using any
anti-takeover measures.
   Wichlep said Texas Eastern would not discuss the number of
companies planning visits to the company's Houston headquarters or
when they were expected. All companies are being asked to sign
confidentiality agreements, he said.
   Analysts and industry officials expressed doubt Wednesday that
there may be a large number of serious contenders to take over the
Houston-based natural gas company. Panhandle Eastern Corp., Arkla
Inc., Consolidated Natural Gas and Burlington Resources all have
reportedly turned down requests to enter the bidding.
   Houston-based Enron Corp., which operates the nation's largest
natural gas transmission system and long had been considered a
possible candidate for a Texas Eastern takeover, will not say
whether it is talking to the company.
   Others cited as possible suitors include Houston-based Pennzoil
and Williams Cos. of Tulsa, Okla. British Petroleum PLC's BP America
is said to have an interest in Texas Eastern's considerable oil and
natural gas reserves in the North Sea.
   Paul said his company has asked Texas Eastern for information
that would justify a higher offer than its $42-a-share cash bid, but
said the only response has been ``rhetoric and a stonewall meeting
last Sunday.''
   The meeting between executives of the two Houston-based natural
gas companies was the only face-to-face contact to occur since
Coastal's takeover bid was announced Jan. 16.
</TEXT>
