<FIRST>r f AM-CNNCenter     01-25 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CNN Center,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deal To Sell CNN Center Falls Through But Talks Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turner Broadcasting System Inc. said Wednesday a
letter of intent to sell its headquarters building, CNN Center in
downtown Atlanta, to a New Jersey real estate firm has expired
without completion of the sale.
   ``It is unfortunate that this transaction was not completed on
schedule,'' said Paul D. Beckham, TBS senior vice president of
finance and administration.
   ``Nonetheless, we have been continuing to talk with 66 Properties
Inc. (a unit of The Herrick Co., a Morristown, N.J.-based real
estate investment firm) and it remains the intent of the company to
sell CNN Center on the appropriate terms,'' he said.
   The signing of the letter of intent was announced Nov. 7. The
sale was to have been closed within about 60 days at a price of
about $170 million.
   The price is nearly three times the amount TBS paid for the Omni
International complex in 1986, later renaming it after its Cable
News Network.
   TBS purchased the property for $21.8 million in cash and the
assumption of $45 million in debt.
   In announcing the deal, TBS Chairman Ted Turner said the profit
would be used to pay down some of the debt TBS incurred in the $1.4
billion purchase of the MGM film library in 1986.
</TEXT>
