<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Squibb     01-25 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Squibb,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 15.2 Percent Rise in 4th-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Squibb Corp. said Wednesday it had a 15.2
percent increase in its fourth-quarter earnings compared to the
previous year.
   The drug manufacturer said it earned $97.5 million, or $1 a
share, in the fourth quarter compared with $84.6 million, or 81
cents per share, in the same period in 1987.
   Fourth-quarter sales rose 12 percent to $664.8 million from
$592.6 million in 1987.
   For the year, earnings rose 19 percent to $425.5 million, or
$4.30 a share, compared with $358.4 million, or $3.42 a share, in
1987. Sales for the year rose 20 percent to $2.6 billion from $2.2
billion in 1987.
   Richard M. Furlaud, chairman and chief execuutive, attributed the
increases to higher sales of Capoten, a drug used to treat
hypertension and heart failure.
   Sales of Capoten rose to more than $1 billion in 1988, a
first-time achievement for Squibb, Furlaud said.
   Sales of four other drugs _ Capozide, Corgard, Isovue and Azactam
_ also exceeded $100 million in annual sales, he said.
