<FILEID>AP-NR-01-25-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GibraltarSavings     01-25 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gibraltar Savings,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big S&amp;L Predicts Loss; Discusses FSLIC Supervision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of Gibraltar Savings said
Wednesday it expected to lose more than $30 million in its latest
quarter, and revealed it is discussing a supervisory agreement with
federal thrift regulators.
   Gibraltar, one of the nation's biggest savings and loans, has
been losing money for at least two years, in part because of
expansion into commercial lending and real estate development.
   Gibraltar Financial Corp., holding company for the thrift, said
losses in the quarter ended Dec. 31 are expected to be between $30
million and $35 million. Losses for the year will mount to between
$71 million and $76 million, the company said.
   Gibraltar revealed that regulators from the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board have ordered it to draw up a plan to boost its capital,
and have barred it from entering new business until the plan is
submitted.
   Gibraltar said it is discussing entering a supervisory agreement
with the Bank Board, under which regulators' approval would have to
be sought for major decisions.
   A Bank Board spokesman refused to discuss the company's position,
citing confidentiality rules. Publicly held companies like Gibraltar
are required to disclose such information because of its effect on
the price of their stock.
   James N. Thayer, president and chief executive officer of
Gibraltar Financial Corp., the holding company, blamed current
problems on the institution's big portfolio of fixed-rate loans. The
company's income from those loans is outpaced by the amount it must
pay in interest to short term depositors.
   ``That is a devastating combination in a period, such as the
present one, when short-term rates rise sharply,'' Thayer said in a
news release.
   At the end of June, Gibraltar Savings had assets of $13.2 billion.
</TEXT>
